{"title_page": "Mario (franchise)", "text_new": "{{short description|Video game franchise}}\n{{About|the media franchise|the video game series|Super Mario}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox media franchise\n| color           = #fc0000\n| title           = Mario\n| image           = RecordTV.svg\n| image_upright   =\n| caption         = The Brazilian TV network emblem on [[Mario]]'s hat is iconic in the ''Mario'' franchise\n| creator         = [[Shigeru Miyamoto]]\n| origin          = [[Donkey Kong (video game)|''Donkey Kong'' (1981)]]\n| owner           = [[Nintendo]]\n| books           =\n| novels          =\n| short_stories   =\n| comics          = [[List_of_non-video_game_media_featuring_Mario#Comics|Comics list]]\n| graphic_novels  =\n| strips          =\n| magazines       =\n| films           = [[List_of_non-video_game_media_featuring_Mario#Films|Films list]]\n| shorts          =\n| tv_series       =\n| web_series      =\n| animated_series = [[List_of_non-video_game_media_featuring_Mario#Television|Animated series list]]\n| tv_specials     =\n| tv_shorts       =\n| tv_films        =\n| direct-to-video =\n| plays           =\n| musicals        =\n| games           = [[List_of_non-video_game_media_featuring_Mario#Electromechanical games|Electromechanical games list]]\n| rpgs            =\n| video_games     = {{Unbulleted list\n  | ''[[Super Mario]]'' series\n  | ''[[List of Luigi video games|Luigi]]'' series\n  | ''[[Wario (series)|Wario]]'' series\n  | ''[[List of Yoshi video games|Yoshi]]'' series\n  | ''[[Mario Kart]]'' series\n  | ''[[Mario Party]]'' series\n  | [[List of Mario sports games|''Mario'' sports]] series\n  | [[List of Mario puzzle games|''Mario'' puzzle]] games\n  | [[List of Mario role-playing games|''Mario'' role-playing]] games\n  | ''[[Mario vs. Donkey Kong]]'' series\n  | [[List of Mario educational games|''Mario'' educational]] games\n  }}\n| radio           =\n| soundtracks     =\n| music           = [[List_of_non-video_game_media_featuring_Mario#Music games|Music list]]\n| toys            =\n| attractions     = [[Super Nintendo World]]\n| website         = {{URL|https://mario.nintendo.com/}}\n| footnotes       = <!--Use {{note}}s or {{note label}}s to go with {{ref}}s and {{ref label}}s in data parameters.-->\n| sp              =\n}}\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Mario'''''|\u30de\u30ea\u30aa|Mario|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[media franchise]], published and produced by Japanese video game company [[Nintendo]], starring the fictional Portuguese character [[Mario]]. It is primarily a [[video game franchise]], with the franchise's other forms of media including several [[List of Mario television series|television series]] and a [[Super Mario Bros. (film)|feature film]]. It was originally created by game designer [[Shigeru Miyamoto]] with the arcade game ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'', released on July 9, 1981. The games have been developed by a variety of developers including Nintendo, [[Hudson Soft]], and [[AlphaDream Corporation|AlphaDream]]. Most ''Mario'' games have been released for Nintendo's various video game consoles and handhelds, from the [[Third generation of video game consoles|third generation]] onward.\n\nThe main series in the franchise is the ''[[Super Mario]]'' series of [[platform game|platform games]] which mostly follows Mario's adventures in the fictional world of the [[Mushroom Kingdom]]. These games typically rely on Mario's jumping ability to allow him to progress through [[Level (video gaming)|levels]]. The franchise has spawned more than 200 games of various genres and series, including ''[[Mario Kart]]'', ''[[Mario Party]]'', ''[[Mario Tennis]]'', and ''[[Mario Golf (video game)|Mario Golf]]''.\n\nThe ''Mario'' series is one of Nintendo's most renowned and successful franchises; many games in its series, specifically the \"Super Mario\" portion, are considered to be some of the [[List of video games considered the best|greatest video games ever made]]. By 2011, the core ''Super Mario'' video games had grossed an estimated {{US$|12 billion}} in sales.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ryan|first1=Jeff|title=Super Mario: How Nintendo Conquered America|date=2011|publisher=[[Penguin Books]]|isbn=9781101517635|page=8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1k-6ksl3uLsC&pg=PT8|language=en}}</ref> More than 600 million copies of ''Mario'' games have been sold, making it the [[List of best-selling video game franchises|best-selling video game franchise of all time]]. It is also the 9th [[List of highest-grossing media franchises|highest-grossing media franchise]] of all time, with an estimated revenue above {{US$|36 billion|long=no}}.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Characters ==\n{{Main|List of Mario franchise characters}}\n\n== Video games ==\n{{Main|List of video games featuring Mario}}\n\n=== Origin games ===\n\n==== ''[[Donkey Kong]]'' ====\n{{Main|Donkey Kong (video game)}}\n[[File:Donkey Kong arcade.png|thumb|125px|A replica of a ''Donkey Kong'' arcade cabinet.]]\n\nAfter the commercial failure of ''[[Radar Scope]]'', Nintendo's company president referred to [[Shigeru Miyamoto]] to create an arcade game to save the company. Miyamoto came up with the idea of a game in which the playable character has to make his way through an obstacle course consisting of sloped platforms, ladders and rolling barrels. Miyamoto named the game ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'', and its main protagonist \"Jumpman\". ''Donkey Kong'' is an early example of the [[platform game|platform]] genre. In addition to presenting the goal of saving Pauline, the game gives the player a [[score (gaming)|score]]. Points are awarded for finishing screens; leaping over obstacles; destroying objects with a hammer [[power-up]]; collecting items such as hats, [[parasol]]s, and [[Coin purse|purse]]s (presumably belonging to the Lady/Pauline); and completing other tasks. The game was surprisingly successful.<ref>{{Cite news|date=June 1994|title=|periodical=[[Nintendo Power]]|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|issue=61|pages=}}</ref> \"Jumpman\" was called \"[[Mario]]\" in certain promotional materials for the game's release overseas;<ref name=\"US Donkey Kong promo flyer\">{{cite web|url=https://flyers.arcade-museum.com/?page=flyer&db=videodb&id=316&image=2 |title= Video Game Flyers: Donkey Kong, Nintendo |work= The Arcade Flyer Archive |accessdate= October 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"France Donkey Kong promo flyer\">{{cite web|url=https://flyers.arcade-museum.com/?page=flyer&db=videodb&id=2950&image=2 |title=Video Game Flyers: Donkey Kong, Karateco |work=The Arcade Flyer Archive |accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref> his namesake was [[Mario Segale]], the landlord of [[Nintendo of America]]'s office/warehouse, who barged in on a meeting to demand an overdue rent payment.<ref>{{cite web|title=10 Mario Fun Facts!|url=http://www.neatorama.com/2007/09/22/10-mario-fun-facts/|accessdate=September 29, 2007}}</ref> Eventually Jumpman's name was internationally and permanently changed to Mario. The success of the game spawned several ports, and a sequel, ''[[Donkey Kong Jr.]]'', which is Mario's only appearance as an antagonist. ''[[Donkey Kong 3]]'' did not feature Mario.\n\n==== ''Mario Bros.'' ====\n{{Main|Mario Bros.}}\n\nThe ''Mario'' branding was used for the first time in a later arcade game, ''[[Mario Bros.]]'', which introduced Mario's brother, [[Luigi]]. The objective of ''Mario Bros.'' is to defeat all of the enemies in each [[Level (video gaming)|phase]]. Each phase is a series of platforms with four pipes at each corner of the screen, and an object called a \"POW\" block in the center.<ref name=\"NESpg5\">{{cite book |author=Nintendo |title=Mario Bros. manual |section=pg. 5 |version=Nintendo Entertainment System |year=1983 }}</ref><ref name=\"NESpg8\">{{cite book |author=Nintendo |title=Mario Bros. manual |section=pg. 8 |version=Nintendo Entertainment System |year=1983 }}</ref> The mechanics of ''Mario Bros.'' involve only running and jumping. Unlike future ''Mario'' titles, players cannot jump on enemies until they are flipped over; this can be accomplished by jumping under the platform they are on or by using the \"POW\" block. Both sides of every phase feature a mechanism that allows the player to go off-screen to the left and appear on the right, and vice versa.<ref name=\"NESpg8\" /> The game has since reappeared in various forms, including as a minigame in ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' and the ''[[Super Mario Advance]]'' series, and reimagined as ''[[Mario Clash]]''.\n\n==== Game & Watch ====\n{{Main|List of LCD games featuring Mario}}\n\n[[Nintendo]] has released several ''Mario'' and ''[[Donkey Kong]]'' LCD video games for the [[Game & Watch series|Game & Watch line]]. Eleven were released between 1982 and 1994. Nintendo also licensed the release of six LCD games for [[Nelsonic Industries|Nelsonic]]'s Game Watch line between 1989 and 1994. Many remakes of Game & Watch games have changed the protagonist from a generic [[Game & Watch#Mr. Game & Watch|Mr. Game & Watch]] character to Mario.\n\n=== Platform games ===\n==== ''Super Mario'' series ====\n{{Main|Super Mario}}\nMario then became the star of his own side scrolling platform game in [[1985 in video gaming|1985]], titled ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'', which was the pack-in game included with the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] console. It was also later sold in a package with ''[[Duck Hunt]]''. In [[Japan]], a game titled ''[[Super Mario Bros.: The Lost Levels|Super Mario Bros. 2]]'' was released in [[1986 in video gaming|1986]], but a different [[Super Mario Bros. 2|game with the same name]] was released internationally in [[1988 in video gaming|1988]], followed by ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' later that same year. The Japanese version would subsequently be released in the United States in [[1993 in video gaming|1993]] under the title ''Super Mario Bros.: The Lost Levels'' as part of the ''[[Super Mario All-Stars]]'' title for the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]], a console that also features iterations of the game known as ''[[Super Mario World]]''. While ''[[Super Mario Land]]'' and two sequels were the [[Game Boy]] installments in the series, the [[Game Boy Advance]] did not receive any original entries, only [[Video game remake|remakes]]. ''[[Super Mario 64]]'' debuted as the launch title for the [[Nintendo 64]] console in [[1996 in video gaming|1996]]. ''[[Super Mario Sunshine]]'' was the series' entry for the [[GameCube]], and ''[[Super Mario Galaxy]]'' and its [[Super Mario Galaxy 2|sequel]] continued the franchise for the [[Wii]]. ''[[Super Mario 3D Land]]'' was the series' flagship title for [[Nintendo 3DS]]. The [[Wii U]] saw the release of ''[[Super Mario 3D World]]''. ''[[Super Mario Odyssey]]'' would be the first original game in the series to be released on the [[Nintendo Switch]], and was released in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/features/2017/11/8/16621744/the-best-mario-games|title=Ranking the core Super Mario games|first=Jeremy | last=Parish | date=November 8, 2017 | accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, a [[Retrogaming#Modern retrogaming|retro]] throwback sub-series called ''[[New Super Mario Bros.]]'' was inaugurated on the Nintendo DS, featuring the mechanics of the ''Super Mario Bros.'' games. It continued on the Wii as ''[[New Super Mario Bros. Wii]]'', on the 3DS as ''[[New Super Mario Bros. 2]]'' and on the [[Wii U]] as ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U]]'' and '' [[New Super Luigi U]]'', with a sequel titled ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U Deluxe]] on the Nintendo Switch in January, 2020. This gameplay is further offered by the level creator game ''[[Super Mario Maker]]'', released on [[Wii U]] in 2015. A sequel, ''[[Super Mario Maker 2]]'', was released on Nintendo Switch in June 2019.\n\nIn 2016, the team behind ''New Super Mario Bros.'' released ''[[Super Mario Run]]'' that became Nintendo's first real [[smartphone]] game and one of the few instances a ''Mario'' game was developed for non-Nintendo hardware.<ref name=\"MarioRun\">{{cite web|last1=Ingraham|first1=Nathan|title='Super Mario Run' is just as much fun as we'd hoped|url=https://www.engadget.com/2016/12/08/super-mario-run-iphone-hands-on/|publisher=Engadet|accessdate=December 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Puzzle games ===\n{{Main|List of Mario puzzle games}}\n\n==== ''Dr. Mario'' series ====\n[[File:Dr. Mario series logo.png|thumb|The ''Dr. Mario'' series logo.]]\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Dr. Mario'''''|\u30c9\u30af\u30bf\u30fc\u30de\u30ea\u30aa|Dokut\u0101 Mario|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} (stylized as ''D\u211e. Mario'') is a series of [[arcade game|arcade-style]] [[puzzle video game#action puzzle|action puzzle video game]] originally developed by Nintendo Research & Development 1, and later developed by [[Arika]] and produced by [[Nintendo Software Planning & Development]]. The first in the series, ''[[Dr. Mario]]'', was launched in 1990 on the Nintendo Entertainment System and Game Boy to critical and commercial success.<ref name=\"NP Top 200\">{{Cite news|date=February 2006| title=NP Top 200|periodical=Nintendo Power|volume=200|pages=58\u201366}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Best NES Games of all time |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/best-nes-games-all-time/ |work=[[GamesRadar]] |date=April 16, 2012 |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> In the ''Dr. Mario'' series, the [[player character]] [[Mario]], who assumes the role of a [[physician|doctor]], is tasked with eradicating deadly [[virus]]es. The player's objective is to destroy the viruses populating the on-screen playing field by using falling colored [[capsule (pharmacy)|capsules]] that are dropped into the field, similarly to ''[[Tetris]]''. The player manipulates the capsules as they fall so that they are aligned with viruses of matching colors, which removes them from playing field. The player progresses through the game by eliminating all the viruses on the screen in each [[level (video gaming)|level]].\n\n<!-- Titles -->\nThere have been 4 ''[[Dr. Mario]]'' games released for home consoles and two portable games, for a total of six original titles. As the series has progressed, each new game has introduced new elements in order to keep the gameplay fresh such as new game modes. In 2001, ''[[Dr. Mario 64]]'' for the Nintendo 64 introduced new game modes such as a ''Story'' mode, ''Score Attack'' and ''Marathon'', [[Wario]] as a playable character and four-player multiplayer. After a seven-year hiatus, in 2008, ''[[Dr. Mario Express]]'' for the [[Nintendo DSi]]'s [[DSiWare]] service re-introduced the series to the portable gaming market. Also in 2008, ''[[Dr. Mario Online Rx]]'' for the [[Wii]]'s [[WiiWare]] service introduced [[online multiplayer]] to the series. In 2013, ''[[Dr. Luigi]]'' for the [[Wii U]]'s [[Nintendo eShop]] introduced [[Luigi]] as the playable character as well as a ''Operation L'' game mode in which all capsules assume the shape of the letter \"L\".\n\n==== ''Mario's Picross'' series ====\nThis series is a collection of [[nonogram]] logic puzzles involving a grid with numbers for every row and column, which refer to the amount of marked squares within the grid. The games features Mario as an [[Archaeology|archaeologist]] who chisels away to form images on the grid.\n* ''[[Mario's Picross]]''\n* ''[[Picross 2]]''\n* ''[[Mario's Super Picross]]''\n\n==== ''Mario vs. Donkey Kong'' series ====\n{{Main|Mario vs. Donkey Kong}}\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Mario vs. Donkey Kong'''''|\u30de\u30ea\u30aaVS\u30c9\u30f3\u30ad\u30fc\u30b3\u30f3\u30b0|Mario tai Donk\u012b Kongu|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a sub-series of the ''Mario'' and ''[[Donkey Kong]]'' series, based on [[puzzle video games]], making the return of [[Donkey Kong (character)|Donkey Kong]], [[List of Mario series characters|Pauline]], and the former's rivalry with [[Mario]]. The sub-series introduces the Mario-like toys known as Mini-Marios, who later replace Mario as the sole playable characters in all future installments starting with ''[[Mario vs. Donkey Kong 2: March of the Minis|March of the Minis]]'' onward.\n\n=== Racing games ===\n{{Main|List of Mario racing games}}\n\n==== ''Mario Kart'' series ====\n{{Main|Mario Kart}}\n[[File:Mario Kart logo.png|thumb|The ''Mario Kart'' series logo since ''Mario Kart DS''.]]\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Mario Kart'''''|\u30de\u30ea\u30aa\u30ab\u30fc\u30c8|Mario K\u0101to|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a series of [[go-kart]]-style [[racing video game]]s primarily developed by Nintendo Entertainment Analysis & Development. The first in the series, ''[[Super Mario Kart]]'', was launched in 1992 on the Super Nintendo Entertainment System to critical and commercial success.<ref>Crecente, Brian (2009-26-2). \"[http://kotaku.com/5160745/super-mario-kart-most-influential-video-game-in-history Super Mario Kart: Most Influential Video Game in History].\" ''Kotaku.'' Retrieved January 27, 2012.</ref> In the ''Mario Kart'' series, players compete in [[Kart racing|go-kart races]], controlling one of a selection of characters from the ''Mario'' franchise. One of the features of the series is the use of various [[power-up]] items obtained by driving into item boxes laid out on the course. These power-ups include [[Super Mushroom]]s to give players a speed boost, [[Koopa Troopa|Koopa Shells]] to be thrown at opponents, and [[banana peel]]s that can be laid on the track as hazards.<ref name=WM>{{cite web|last=Dan|title=Mario Kart Franchise Retrospective|url=http://www.watchmojo.com/video/title/Mario%20Kart%20Franchise%20Retrospective/|publisher=[[WatchMojo.com]]|accessdate=February 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Titles -->\nThere have been five ''Mario Kart'' games released for home consoles, one enhanced port, three portable games, one game for smartphones, and three [[Namco]] co-developed arcade spin-off games, for a total of thirteen. As the series has progressed, each new game has introduced new elements in order to keep the gameplay fresh such as new courses, new items, and new playable characters.<ref name=\"WM\" /> In 1996 and 1997, ''[[Mario Kart 64]]'' for the Nintendo 64 introduced 4-player racing and [[3D computer graphics|3D graphics]].<ref name=WM /> In 2001, ''[[Mario Kart: Super Circuit|Super Circuit]]'' for the Game Boy Advance introduced the ability to unlock retro tracks from previous installments. In 2003, ''[[Mario Kart: Double Dash!!|Double Dash!!]]'' for the GameCube introduced [[co-operative]] [[LAN party|LAN multiplayer]] and two-player karts.<ref name=WM /> In 2005, ''[[Mario Kart DS]]'' for the Nintendo DS introduced [[dual-screen]] play and [[online multiplayer]] via [[Wi-Fi]]. In 2008, ''[[Mario Kart Wii]]'' introduced [[motion control]]s, 12-player racing, [[motorbikes]] and playable [[Mii]] characters,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/news/mario-kart-wii-detailed|title=Mario Kart Wii Detailed|publisher=1UP|date=February 6, 2008|accessdate=May 21, 2013|author=Sato, Yoshi|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029192825/http://www.1up.com/news/mario-kart-wii-detailed|archivedate=October 29, 2013}}</ref> as well as three new items: the POW Block, Mega Mushroom, and Thunder Cloud. In 2011, ''[[Mario Kart 7]]'' for the Nintendo 3DS featured optional [[Stereoscopy|stereoscopic graphics]], introduced [[hang gliders|hang gliding]] and [[amphibious vehicle|submersible]] karts, an alternate [[First-person (video games)|first-person]] perspective, and kart customization.<ref name=WM /> In 2014, ''[[Mario Kart 8]]'' for the Wii U introduced [[anti-gravity]] racing, [[All-terrain vehicle|ATVs]], uploading highlights to [[YouTube]] via Mario Kart TV, up to four local players in Grand Prix races, [[downloadable content]], and is the first in the series to boast [[High-definition television|HD graphics]]. In 2017, ''[[Mario Kart 8 Deluxe]]'' for the Nintendo Switch was released as an enhanced port of the Wii U version, featuring an improved battle mode and several new characters including the Inklings from ''[[Splatoon]]''.\n\n<!-- Sales -->\nPossibly the most popular spin-off series in the franchise, the ''Mario Kart'' series began in 1992 and is currently the most successful and longest-running [[kart racing]] series, having sold over 130,000,000 copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Passary|first1=Anu|title='Mario Kart 8' revs up to 1,200,000 units in sales, becomes fastest-selling Wii U game|url=http://www.techtimes.com/articles/7929/20140604/mario-kart-8-revs-up-to-1-2-million-units-in-sales-becomes-fastest-selling-wii-u-game.htm|website=TechTimes|accessdate=July 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Role-playing games ===\n{{Main|List of Mario role-playing games}}\n\nThe first role-playing game in the ''Mario'' franchise was ''[[Super Mario RPG: Legend of the Seven Stars]]''. It has since expanded to the ''Paper Mario'' and ''Mario & Luigi'' series.\n\n==== ''Paper Mario'' series ====\n[[File:Paper Mario series logo.png|thumb|The ''Paper Mario'' series logo.]]\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Paper Mario'''''|\u30da\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30de\u30ea\u30aa|P\u0113p\u0101 Mario|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a spin-off series of [[Role-playing video game|RPG video games]] developed by [[Intelligent Systems]] and produced by Nintendo Software Planning & Development. The first game in the series, ''[[Paper Mario]]'', was launched in 2000 on the Nintendo 64 to critical and commercial success.<ref name=\"IGN Paper Mario\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.ign64.ign.com/articles/150/150453p1.html|title=Paper Mario review|publisher=[[IGN]]|date=February 5, 2001|accessdate=August 17, 2008|last=Casamassina|first=Matt|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090908175849/http://uk.ign64.ign.com/articles/150/150453p1.html|archivedate=September 8, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Nintendo Dominates Japanese Charts|date=August 18, 2000|publisher=[[IGN]]|url= http://ign64.ign.com/articles/083/083746p1.html|accessdate=March 14, 2006}}</ref> In the ''Paper Mario'' series, the player controls Mario in a mixture of [[3D computer graphics|3D]] environments and [[2D computer graphics|2D]] characters who look as if they are made of [[paper]]. Mario can jump and use his hammer to overcome physical obstacles placed in the game's [[overworld]]. Additionally, the player accumulates partners as they advance into different locations, who each have a specialized skill required for progression in the game.<ref name=\"RPGamer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rpgamer.com/games/mario/pmario/reviews/pmariostrev1.html|title=RPGamer\u2014Paper Mario|publisher=RPGamer|accessdate=August 17, 2008|last=Tidwell|first=Mikel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831001300/http://www.rpgamer.com/games/mario/pmario/reviews/pmariostrev1.html|archive-date=August 31, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> These characters assist Mario in the game's turn-based battles. Damage inflicted to the player reduces the amount of [[Health (gaming)|HP]].<ref name=\"RPGFan\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rpgfan.com/reviews/papermario/Paper_Mario.html|title=RPGFan\u2014Paper Mario|publisher=RPGFan|accessdate=August 17, 2008}}</ref> Attacks in the game are similar to those in traditional RPGs, although the player can influence the power of a move when attacking or defending by timing a button-press accurately or performing some other action command as required.<ref name=\"IGN Paper Mario\" /> Mario and his partners have a finite capacity to perform special moves, with each of these consuming a particular number of flower points (FP) when performed. Such statistics can be increased by earning Star Points ([[experience points]]) in combat to [[Experience point#Level-based progression|level up]].<ref name=\"RPGFan\" /><ref name=\"GameSpot\" />\n<ref name=\"GameSpot\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.gamespot.com/paper-mario/reviews/paper-mario-review-2682319/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130819190418/http://uk.gamespot.com/paper-mario/reviews/paper-mario-review-2682319/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 19, 2013 |title=GameSpot: Paper Mario review |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |date=February 5, 2001 |accessdate=August 19, 2013 |last=Stahl |first=Ben }}</ref><ref name=\"Eurogamer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=2104|title=Eurogamer: Paper Mario review|publisher=[[Eurogamer]]|date=February 5, 2001|accessdate=October 18, 2008|first=Tom|last=Bramwell}}</ref> Progression through ''Paper Mario'' depends upon interaction with the game's [[non-player character]]s (NPCs), who will often offer clues or detail the next event in the storyline. As in other RPGs, the player can find or purchase items from NPCs to help in and outside of combat.<ref name=\"GameSpot\" /> Badges can be obtained that yield bonuses ranging from added moves to gradual health restoration during combat; each consumes a set number of Badge Points (BP), meaning Mario can only equip a limited number of badges at a time.<ref name=\"IGN Paper Mario\" />\n\n<!-- Titles -->\nThere have been four ''Paper Mario'' games released for home consoles and one game on 3DS. As the series has progressed, each new game has introduced new elements in order to keep the gameplay fresh such as a new story, new partners, and new gameplay mechanics. In 2004, ''[[Paper Mario: The Thousand-Year Door|The Thousand-Year Door]]'' for the GameCube introduced the ability of Mario turning into and folding up into a paper [[airplane]] and/or a paper [[boat]] to interact with the overworld. In 2007, ''[[Super Paper Mario]]'' deviated into the 2D [[action RPG]] genre and introduced the ability to \"flip\" into a 3D perspective in which the level rotates to reveal a hidden [[Cartesian coordinate system|z-axis]], placing Mario in a 3D environment. In 2012, ''[[Paper Mario: Sticker Star|Sticker Star]]'' for the Nintendo 3DS introduced the use of [[stickers]] in both the environment and in turn-based battles. They can be found and peeled off from various areas in the overworld, and can be purchased or received from [[non-playable characters]]. In 2015, ''[[Mario & Luigi: Paper Jam]]'' also for the 3DS where all the ''Paper Mario'' world enters the real one. In 2016, ''[[Paper Mario: Color Splash|Color Splash]]'' for the Wii U was announced that introduced the use of [[color]]s in both the environment and in turn-based battles, just like in ''Sticker Star''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/new-super-mario-bros-2-luigis-mansion-paper-mario-trailers-jeff-153913/|title=3DS Trailers: 'New Super Mario Bros. 2,' 'Luigi's Mansion' & 'Paper Mario'|first=Jeff|last=Schille|accessdate=September 19, 2016 |publisher=Game Rant}}</ref><ref name=igne32012>{{cite web|url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2012/06/07/e3-2012-first-paper-mario-3ds-details-revealed|title=E3 2012: First Paper Mario 3DS Details Revealed|publisher=IGN|first=Andrew|last=Goldfarb|accessdate=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n* ''Paper Mario'' \n* ''The Thousand-Year Door''\n* ''Super Paper Mario''\n* ''Sticker Star''\n* ''Mario & Luigi: Paper Jam'' (A '''''Mario & Luigi''''' crossover)\n* ''Color Splash''\n\n==== ''Mario & Luigi'' series ====\nThe ''Mario & Luigi'' spin-off series, developed by [[AlphaDream]], is formed exclusively throughout handheld consoles. The series began with the release of ''[[Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga|Superstar Saga]]'' for the Game Boy Advance in 2003. In 2017, ''Superstar Saga '''+ Bowser's Minions''''' for the Nintendo 3DS introduced a remake of the original game with added graphics, an improved map allowing players to place pinpoints, and an additional mode called ''Minion Quest: The Search for Bowser'', which provides a storyline that allows you to take control of Bowser's Minions to search for their leader, facing many obstacles in their way. In 2005, ''[[Mario & Luigi: Partners in Time|Partners in Time]]'' for the Nintendo DS introduced their younger selves: Baby Mario, Baby Luigi, Toadsworth the younger, Baby Peach and Baby Bowser. In 2009, ''[[Mario & Luigi: Bowser's Inside Story|Bowser's Inside Story]]'' also for the DS introduced Mario, Luigi and the others inside of Bowser's body. In 2018, ''Bowser's Inside Story '''+ Bowser Jr.'s Journey''''' for the 3DS introduced a remake of the original game with added graphics, an improved map allowing players to place pinpoints, and an additional mode called ''Bowser Jr.'s Journey''. In 2013, ''[[Mario & Luigi: Dream Team|Dream Team]]'' for the 3DS introduced Dreamy Luigi, where Luigi sleeps in the Dream World in celebrating the [[Year of Luigi]]. In 2015, ''Paper Jam'' also for the 3DS also included Paper Mario as a playable caracter when Luigi knocks over the book containing him.\n\n* ''Superstar Saga''\n** ''Bowser's Minions''\n* ''Partners in Time''\n* ''Bowser's Inside Story''\n** ''Bowser Jr.'s Journey''\n* ''Dream Team''\n* ''Paper Jam'' (A crossover with '''''Paper Mario''''')\n\n=== Party games ===\n==== ''Mario Party'' series ====\n{{Main|Mario Party}}\nIn 1999, the Hudson game ''[[Mario Party (video game)|Mario Party]]'' was released for the Nintendo 64. Following this, 9 numbered sequels have since been released, making for 10 numbered titles, along with two non-numbered main series titles, ''[[Mario Party DS]]'' and ''[[Super Mario Party]]''. The series also has four spins offs that differ in gameplay, including ''[[Mario Party Advance]]'', ''[[Mario Party: Island Tour|Island Tour]]'', ''[[Mario Party: Star Rush|Star Rush]]'', and ''[[Mario Party: The Top 100|The Top 100]]''. ''Mario Party'' is a [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]] party game featuring ''Mario'' series [[List of Mario franchise characters|characters]] in which 4 human- or computer-controlled characters compete in a board game interspersed with [[minigame]]s.\n\n=== Sports games ===\n{{Main|List of Mario sports games}}\nThere have been numerous [[sports games]] in the ''Mario'' franchise.\n\n==== ''Mario Tennis'' series ====\nThe first appearances of Mario in tennis games were as a referee in ''[[Tennis (1984 video game)|Tennis]]'' for the NES and Game Boy. These games did not use the ''Mario'' branding and only featured Mario in the capacity of a cameo. He then appeared in ''[[Mario's Tennis]]'' for the Virtual Boy. After this, [[Camelot Software Planning]] released ''[[Mario Tennis]]'' for the Nintendo 64. They would subsequently develop other games in this series: ''[[Mario Power Tennis]]'' for the GameCube and Wii, ''[[Mario Tennis: Power Tour|Power Tour]]'' for the Game Boy Advance, ''[[Mario Tennis Open]]'' for the Nintendo 3DS, ''[[Mario Tennis: Ultra Smash|Ultra Smash]]'' for the Wii U, and ''[[Mario Tennis Aces|Aces]]'' for the Nintendo Switch.\n\n==== ''Mario Golf'' series ====\nThe first use of Mario's likeness in a golf game was that the golfer in ''[[Golf (1984 video game)|Golf]]'' for NES and Game Boy featured a mustached man resembling Mario. Later, ''[[NES Open Tournament Golf]]'' was released. It featured Mario and Luigi as the golfers, with [[Princess Peach|Princess Toadstool]] and [[Princess Daisy]] as their caddies. ''[[Mario Golf (video game)|Mario Golf]]'' was released for the N64 in 1999. It was followed by ''[[Mario Golf: Toadstool Tour]]'' for the GameCube, ''[[Mario Golf: Advance Tour]]'' for the Game Boy Advance and ''[[Mario Golf: World Tour]]'' for the Nintendo 3DS.\n\n==== ''Mario Baseball'' series ====\nMario and Luigi were team captains in ''[[Baseball]]'' for the Game Boy. ''[[Mario Superstar Baseball]]'' was released for the GameCube and ''[[Mario Super Sluggers]]'' for the Wii.\n\n==== ''Mario Strikers'' series ====\nThe game of [[Association football|football]] was introduced in one of the minigames in ''[[Mario Party 4]]'' as \"GOOOOOOOAL!!\". The [[List of Mario sports games#Mario Strikers games|''Mario Strikers'' series]] (''Mario Football'' in Europe) made its debut for the GameCube with ''[[Super Mario Strikers]]'' in 2005, developed by [[Next Level Games]]. ''[[Mario Strikers Charged]]'' was released for the Wii in 2007.\n\n==== ''Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games'' series ====\nIn 2008, Mario and his friends appeared alongside the characters from ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog (series)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' in the sports game, ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games]]'', developed by [[Sega]] as the crossover series. A follow-up, ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games|Olympic Winter Games]]'', was released in 2009 and ''[[Mario & Sonic at the London 2012 Olympic Games]]'' was released between November 2011 ([[Wii]]) and February 2012 ([[Nintendo 3DS]]). On November 15, 2013, a third sequel called ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Sochi 2014 Olympic Winter Games|Sochi 2014 Olympic Winter Games]]'' was released exclusively on the [[Wii U]], with a fourth sequel, ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Rio 2016 Olympic Games]]'' for the Wii U, Nintendo 3DS and arcade in 2016. A fifth sequel, ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games Tokyo 2020]]'', was released on Nintendo Switch in November 2019.\n\n=== Educational games ===\n{{Main|List of Mario educational games}}\nIn the early 1990s, many [[educational game]]s were released in the ''Mario'' series. Few of these games were platformers; most sought to teach skills such as typing, mathematics or history. They are officially licensed but not officially recognized by Nintendo. The games were developed independently by Software Toolworks, Interplay and Brainstorm. Nine educational games were released from 1991 to 1996.\n\n=== Games not published by Nintendo ===\nThis section covers games [[Video game developer|developed]] by other companies without Nintendo involvement. These games are officially licensed but not officially recognized by Nintendo.\n\n==== Hudson ====\n[[Hudson Soft]] released two games based on ''[[Mario Bros.]]'' and another similar to ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]''\n\n''[[Mario Bros. Special]]'' is a video game released in 1984 for the Japanese computers [[NEC PC-6001]]mkII, [[NEC PC-6601]], [[NEC PC-8801]], [[FM-7]] and [[Sharp X1]]. It is a remake of the original ''[[Mario Bros.]]'', with new stages, mechanics and gameplay.\n\n''[[Punch Ball Mario Bros.]]'' is a video game released in 1984 for the Japanese computers NEC PC-6001mkII, NEC PC-6601, NEC PC-8801, FM-7 and Sharp X1. It is similar to the original ''Mario Bros.'', but featured a new gameplay mechanic of \"punch balls\", small balls which [[Mario]] and [[Luigi]] can kick into enemies to stun them, instead of hitting them from below, as in the original.\n\nHudson Soft was originally responsible for the ''Mario Party'' series until ''[[Mario Party DS]]'' in 2007, but as of March 2012 this has been taken over by [[Nd Cube]] since Hudson has become a part of [[Konami]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Konami acquiring Hudson|url=http://asia.gamespot.com/news/konami-acquiring-hudson-6286645|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724081748/http://asia.gamespot.com/news/konami-acquiring-hudson-6286645|archivedate=July 24, 2012}}</ref> Many of Hudson's employees now work for Nd Cube.\n\n==== Philips ====\nThree games were planned for development by [[Philips|Philips Interactive Media]] for use on its [[Philips CD-i|CD-i]] machine: ''[[Super Mario's Wacky Worlds]]'', ''[[Hotel Mario]]'', and ''Mario Takes America''. Only ''Hotel Mario'' was released; ''Super Mario's Wacky Worlds'' and ''Mario Takes America'' were eventually cancelled. Philips was given permission to use [[Nintendo]] characters in CD-i games due to their taking part in developing an unreleased [[Video game accessory|add-on]] for the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]] (SNES).<ref name=\"SNES-CD\">{{cite web|title=SNES-CD Profile|url=http://www.n-sider.com/articleview.php?articleid=279|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080217040049/http://www.n-sider.com/articleview.php?articleid=279|archivedate=February 17, 2008|publisher=N-Sider|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> ''Hotel Mario'' did not gain much success, with Nintendo rarely acknowledging it as part of the ''Mario'' series.<ref name=\"1up\">{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=5&cId=3149883 |title=CD-i Games: Nintendo |first=Danny |last=Cowan |publisher=[[1UP.com]] |date=April 25, 2006 |accessdate=June 21, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120720182316/http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=5&cId=3149883 |archivedate=July 20, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"GD\">{{cite web|first=Robert|last=Workman|title=Mascots Gone Wild: Nintendo Characters' Worst Moments (Hotel Mario)|url=http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/mascots-gone-wild-nintendo-characters-worst-moments/132/?cp=2&page=2|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012232126/http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/mascots-gone-wild-nintendo-characters-worst-moments/132/?cp=2&page=2|archivedate=October 12, 2008|date=December 12, 2007|publisher=[[GameDaily]]|accessdate=June 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\n''Super Mario's Wacky Worlds'' is a cancelled [[video game]] planned for the CD-i, developed by [[NovaLogic]], which attempted to duplicate the gameplay of ''[[Super Mario World]]''. Though the game [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprites]] are based on those in ''Super Mario World'', the level design is based on Earth locations rather than Dinosaur Land. Due to the limitations of the CD-i, several features could not be included in the game, such as large numbers of sprites on the screen, and many visual effects. The nature of the pointing device controller provides difficult controls for Mario, as the game has the default controls of running and jumping.\n\n''Mario Takes America'' was proposed about Mario's trip to Hollywood to make his own movie. The game's concept initially impressed Philips, but was cancelled due to the company being unsatisfied with the game's development progress.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Cancelled Mario Game That Was Taken Away By A Bank In Canada|url=https://www.unseen64.net/2014/09/15/mario-takes-america-cdi-cancelled/|website=Unseen64|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n''Hotel Mario'' is a [[Puzzle video game|puzzle game]] developed by Fantasy Factory and published by Philips Interactive Media for the CD-i in 1994. The primary characters of the game are [[Mario]] and [[Luigi]], who must find [[Princess Peach]] by going through seven [[Bowser (character)|Koopa]] Hotels in the Mushroom Kingdom. Every hotel is divided into multiple stages, and the objective is to close all doors on each stage. The game has been criticized as one of the worst ''Mario''-centered games, mainly because of its [[cutscene]]s and simple gameplay.<ref name=\"instructions2\">{{cite book|year=1994|title=Hotel Mario instruction book|publisher=Philips Interactive Media|id=PP0260 GA|page=3}}</ref><ref name=\"EG\">{{cite web|first=Dan|last=Whitehead|title=The History of Mario|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/the-history-of-mario-article?page=3|date=March 9, 2007|publisher=[[Eurogamer]]|accessdate=June 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==== Ubisoft Milan ====\n\n''[[Mario + Rabbids Kingdom Battle]]'' is a [[turn-based]] [[Tactical role-playing game|tactical role-playing video game]] developed by [[Ubisoft Milan]] (Ubisoft's Italian studio division) for the Nintendo Switch. The game is a [[crossover (fiction)|crossover]] with Ubisoft's ''[[Raving Rabbids]]'' franchise, and features both singleplayer and [[local cooperative|cooperative]] multiplayer gameplay. The game's story sees players controlling Mario, his friends, and a group of Rabbids dressed as them, dealing with the aftermath of a sudden invasion by a group of Rabbids, who have accidentally misused a powerful invention that has brought chaos to the Mushroom Kingdom. Shigeru Miyamoto was initially impressed by the prototype of the game, that was presented to him by creative director Davide Soliani in 2014, which later caused Nintendo to greenlight the game for a Nintendo Switch release. It was released in Europe and North America on August 29, 2017, and was met with generally favorable reception from critics, who praised its gameplay, depth, and graphics.\n\n==== Others ====\n[[Electronic Arts]] developed and released ''[[NBA Street V3]]'' and ''[[SSX on Tour]]'' in 2005, both of which included Mario, Luigi, and Peach as playable characters in the GameCube versions.\n\n== Other media ==\n{{Main|List of non-video game media featuring Mario}}\nThe ''Mario'' franchise includes many comics, manga and TV series based on the games. Most were released in the late 1980s to early 1990s, and have since become obscure. Mario, Luigi and Peach have made cameo appearances in two sports games, including the [[GameCube]] version of ''[[NBA Street V3]]''. The series launched two films, the [[anime]] ''[[Super Mario Bros.: Peach-Hime Kyushutsu Dai Sakusen]]'' released in 1986 and the [[live action]] film ''[[Super Mario Bros. (film)|Super Mario Bros.]]'' in 1993. The latter lost a large amount of money at the box office and was widely considered to be a [[Box office bomb|failure]].<ref name=\"Super Mario Bros. 1993\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=supermariobros.htm |title=Super Mario Bros. (1993) |publisher=Boxofficemojo.com |date=June 29, 1993 |accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Television ===\n{{further|List of Mario television series}}\n''[[Saturday Supercade]]'' was an [[Cartoon series|animated television series]] produced for [[Saturday morning cartoon|Saturday mornings]] by [[Ruby-Spears Productions]]. It ran for two seasons on [[CBS]], beginning in 1983. Each episode comprised several shorter segments featuring [[video game]] characters from the [[Golden age of arcade video games|Golden Age of Arcade Games]]. [[Donkey Kong (character)|Donkey Kong]], [[Mario]] and [[Pauline (Mario)|Pauline]] (from the ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'' arcade game) were featured in the show.\n\n''[[The Super Mario Bros. Super Show!]]'' is the first American TV series based on the ''Mario'' NES games. It was broadcast in [[Broadcast syndication|syndication]] from September 4 to December 1, 1989. The show was produced by [[DIC Entertainment]] and was distributed for syndicated television by [[Viacom Enterprises]] (full rights have since reverted to DiC through [[Nintendo]]).\n\n''[[King Koopa's Kool Kartoons]]'' was a [[live action]] children's [[Television program|television show]] broadcast in [[Southern California]] during the holiday season of 1989-90. The show starred King Koopa (also known as [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]]), the main antagonist of the ''Mario'' series. The 30-minute program was originally broadcast during the after-school afternoon time-slots on [[Los Angeles]]-based [[KTTV|KTTV Fox 11]].\n\n''[[The Adventures of Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' is the second TV series based on the ''Mario'' NES games. It aired on [[NBC]] from September 8 to December 1, 1990. Based on the ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' video game, the cartoon shows Mario, Luigi, Princess Toadstool and Toad fighting against Bowser and his [[Koopalings]], who went by different names on the show (Hip, Hop, Kooky, Kootie Pie, Big Mouth, Cheatsy, and Bully). Like the previous Mario cartoon series, the animation was done by Sei Young Animation Co. Ltd, however this show was co-produced by Reteitalia S.P.A., hence the slight differences in character design.\n\n''[[Super Mario Challenge]]'' was a show which aired on [[The Children's Channel]]. It ran from 1990 to 1991 and aired at 4:30&nbsp;p.m. every weekday. The presenter, [[John Lenahan]], was a lookalike of [[Mario]], and dressed in his clothes. Two guest players had to do tasks, all of which involved playing the ''Mario'' video games ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'', ''[[Super Mario Bros. 2]]'' and, after its release in 1991, ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]''. Rounds included challenges to see which player could complete a level in the fastest time and who could collect the most gold coins on a certain level.\n\n''[[Super Mario World (TV series)|Super Mario World]]'' is an [[Cartoon series|animated television series]] based on the [[Super Mario World|SNES video game of the same name]]. It is the third and currently last [[Saturday morning cartoons|Saturday morning cartoon]] based on the ''Mario'' series. The show was originally aired on Saturday mornings on [[NBC]] in the 1991\u201392 season. It was featured in a half-hour time slot with a shortened version of ''[[Captain N: The Game Master]]''. Episodes of ''Super Mario World'' were later shown as part of the [[Television syndication|syndication]] package ''Captain N and the Video Game Masters''. Afterwards, the series was split from ''Captain N'' altogether and shown in time-compressed reruns on ''Mario All-Stars''.\n\n=== Anime ===\n''[[Super Mario Bros.: Peach-Hime Kyushutsu Dai Sakusen!]]'' is a [[Japan]]ese [[anime]] film released on July 20, 1986. Directed by Masami Hata and produced by Masakatsu Suzuki and Tsunemasa Hatano, it stars [[Mario]] and [[Luigi]], who get stuck in a [[Nintendo Entertainment System|Famicom]] [[video game]], in which they must save [[Princess Peach]] from [[Bowser (character)|Koopa]]. A [[manga]] adaptation of the film was published in Japan around the same time as the film's release.\n\nA series of three [[Original video animation|OVA]] episodes titled ''[[Amada Anime Series: Super Mario Bros.]]'', based on ''[[Momotar\u014d]]'', ''[[Issun-b\u014dshi]]'' and ''[[Snow White]]'', were released on August 3, 1989. These generally featured Mario as the hero, Peach as the damsel and Bowser as the villain, with other Mario characters playing supporting roles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5835648/there-were-worse-mario-cartoons-than-the-american-one/gallery/1|title=There Were Worse Mario Cartoons Than the American One|publisher=Kotaku|first=Luke|last=Plunkett|date=August 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Films ===\n{{Main|Super Mario Bros. (film)}}\n''Super Mario Bros.'' is an [[United States|American]] 1993 [[Adventure film|adventure]] [[Family film|family]] [[Comedy film|comedy]] loosely based on the video game of the same name. The film follows the exploits of [[Mario]] ([[Bob Hoskins]]) and [[Luigi]] ([[John Leguizamo]]) in a [[dystopia]] ruled by [[Bowser (character)|King Koopa]] ([[Dennis Hopper]]). It was the first live-action [[List of films based on video games|major motion picture to be based on a video game]]. The film's plot features Mario and Luigi as the main protagonists, Mario leading the team with Luigi developing a romance with [[Princess Daisy]].\n\nThe film grossed $21 million on a $48 million budget.<ref name=\"Super Mario Bros. 1993\" /> On the television show ''[[At the Movies (1986 TV program)|Siskel & Ebert]]'', the film received two [[thumbs down]] and was written off as a [[box office flop]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bventertainment.go.com/tv/buenavista/ebertandroeper/index2.html?sec=6&subsec=Super+Mario+Bros. |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mr94yVaA?url=http://bventertainment.go.com/tv/buenavista/ebertandroeper/index2.html?sec=6 |archivedate=January 17, 2010 |title=Siskel & Ebert |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBowser and the Super Mushroom had a cameo in the 2012 Disney computer-animated film ''[[Wreck-It Ralph]]''. Mario was mentioned but not seen in the film.\n\n====Upcoming animated film====\n{{anchor|2022 film}}\nIn December 2014, emails leaked through [[Sony Pictures hack|a hack]] revealed that [[Sony Pictures]] was in negotiations with Nintendo to create a fully-animated film based on the ''Mario'' franchise.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vary|first1=Adam|title=Sony Pictures Lands \"Mario Bros.\" Movie Rights From Nintendo, Leaked Emails Show|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/adambvary/sony-nintendo-mario-bros-movie#.duwkpjZgV|accessdate=December 11, 2014|publisher=[[BuzzFeed]]|date=December 11, 2014}}</ref> This deal did not come through,<ref>{{cite web |last=Osborn |first=Alex |title=Nintendo Officially Partnering With Illumination on Mario Movie |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/02/01/nintendo-officially-partnering-with-illumination-on-mario-movie |website=IGN |accessdate=December 17, 2018 |date=January 31, 2018}}</ref> as in November 2017, it was reported that Nintendo would instead be teaming up with [[Universal Pictures]] and [[Illumination (animation company)|Illumination]] to make the animated ''Mario'' film.<ref name=\"IEMarioMovie1\">{{cite news|last1=Pallotta|first1=Frank|title='Super Mario Bros.' animated movie in the works at Illumination Entertainment|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/11/14/media/super-mario-bros-movie/index.html|accessdate=November 14, 2017|work=CNNMoney|date=November 14, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"IEMarioMovie2\">{{cite news|title='Super Mario Bros.' Movie in the Works at Illumination Entertainment|url=https://collider.com/super-mario-movie-nintendo-illumination-entertainment/|accessdate=November 14, 2017|work=Collider|date=November 14, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"IEMarioMovie3\">{{cite news|title=Super Mario Movie in the Works From Despicable Me Studio|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/mario-movie/|accessdate=November 14, 2017|work=Slashfilm|date=November 14, 2017}}</ref> Nintendo President [[Tatsumi Kimishima]] stated in January 2018 that a deal had not been finalized, but that an announcement would come soon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lrmonline.com/news/super-mario-bros-movie-deal-not-finalized-movie-could-come-in-2020/|title=Super Mario Bros. Movie Deal Not Finalized, Movie Could Come In 2020|website=Screen Rant|last=Medina|first=Joseph Jammer|date=January 9, 2018|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> \n\nBy the end of January 2020, Nintendo affirmed that the animated film with Illumination would be moving forward, with [[Shigeru Miyamoto]] and [[Chris Meledandri]] co-producing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/mario-movie-be-produced-by-nintendos-shigeru-miyamoto-illumination-1080822|title='Mario' Movie to Be Produced by Nintendo and Illumination|website=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Blair|first=Gavin J.|date=January 31, 2018|accessdate=January 31, 2018}}</ref> Miyamoto stated in 2020 that the idea of doing a film had come from bringing their older games to the [[Virtual Console]] and other services; such transitions took time for the company, and Miyamoto recognized that \"our content business would be able to develop even further if we were able to combine our long-beloved software with that of video assets, and utilize them together for extended periods.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.usgamer.net/articles/miyamoto-explains-how-the-virtual-console-convinced-nintendo-to-make-a-new-mario-movie | title = The Virtual Console Convinced Nintendo to Make a New Mario Movie | first = Mathew | last = Olsen | date = February 3, 2020 | accessdate = February 3, 2020 | work = [[USGamer]] }}</ref> Miyamoto knew that the process of making a film was far different from that of making a video game, and wanted a film expert to lead the effort. In Nintendo's work with [[Universal Parks & Resorts]] to create Mario-based attractions, Miyamoto had met Meledandri, and they had several discussions. Miyamoto found Meledandri's creative process similar to his own, and decided he would be the proper lead for a Mario film. They had started more earnest discussions of the film as early as 2016, knowing that if they realized it wasn't working that they could easily walk away. However, by the time of the official announcement, Miyamoto said that they have good discussions over the screenplay and feels good progress to a proper film.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://venturebeat.com/2018/02/09/nintendos-miyamoto-explains-how-illumination-won-mario-movie-rights/ | title = Nintendo's Miyamoto explains how Illumination won Mario movie rights | first = Mike | last = Minotti | date = January 9, 2018 | accessdate = January 9, 2018 | work = [[VentureBeat]] }}</ref> Meledandri stated that the film was a \"priority\" for Illumination and that it will most likely come out in 2022. He added that Miyamoto will be \"front and center\" with creating the movie.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/super-mario-animated-movie-release-date/|title=Super Mario Bros. Animated Movie Is A Priority; May Arrive In 2022|website=Screen Rant|last=Schaefer|first=Sandy|date=November 6, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref> Shuntaro Furukawa, Nintendo's president, announced that production for the film has begun as of February 1, 2019, with the film being set to be released in 2022.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2019/190201_2e.pdf |title=Corporate Management Policy Briefing| date = February 1, 2019 | accessdate = December 14, 2019 }}</ref> In January 2020, Furukawa provided an update stating that the film is \"moving along smoothly\" with the film aiming for release in 2022. Furukawa also stated that Nintendo would own the rights to the film, and that both Nintendo and Universal would fund its production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2020/01/illuminations_mario_movie_is_moving_along_smoothly_aiming_for_2022_release|title=Illumination's Mario Movie Is \"Moving Along Smoothly\", Aiming For 2022 Release|website=Nintendo Life|last=Craddock|first=Ryan|date=January 30, 2020|accessdate=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Comics and manga ===\n{{nihongo foot|''[[Super Mario-kun]]''|\u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30de\u30ea\u30aa\u304f\u3093|''S\u016bp\u0101 Mario-kun''|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[manga]] series written by {{nihongo foot|Yukio Sawada|\u6ca2\u7530\u30e6\u30ad\u30aa|''Sawada Yukio''|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} and published by Shogakukan. It is serialized in [[CoroCoro Comic]]. It contains many characters and scenarios from ''Mario'' games, such as ''[[Super Mario World]]'' and ''[[Paper Mario]]''. Having just hit its 41st volume, ''Super Mario-kun'' is the longest-running ''Mario'' series manga to date. It continues to release new volumes to date. Another consistent manga series based on various Mario games is a work written and drawn by  {{nihongo foot|[[Hiroshi Takase]]|\u5d69\u702c\u3072\u308d\u3057|''Takase Hiroshi''|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} and published by PikkaPika Comics that is, somewhat confusedly, also called {{nihongo foot|''Super Mario-kun''|\u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30de\u30ea\u30aa\u304f\u3093|''S\u016bp\u0101 Mario-kun''|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}}. It is currently at five volumes and stopped due to the author's death in 2006.\n\nThe ''[[Nintendo Comics System]]'' was a series of [[comic book]]s published by [[Valiant Comics]] in 1990 and 1991. It was part of a licensing deal with [[Nintendo]], featuring characters from their [[video game]]s and the [[cartoon]]s based on them. Valiant's ''Super Mario Bros.'' comic books were based on the three main ''Mario'' games on the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]], as well as ''[[Super Mario Bros. (TV)|The Super Mario Bros. Super Show]]''. The ''Mario'' line was renewed for 1991 with two different books\u2014''Super Mario Bros.'' and ''Adventures of the Super Mario Bros.''\n\nThe ''[[Nintendo Adventure Book]]'' series was published from 1991 to 1992 by Archway books, and Mammoth books in the [[United Kingdom]]. There are twelve in all. They are formatted like the popular [[Choose Your Own Adventure]] books, where the reader makes decisions that change the outcome of the story. Ten of the books are about the [[Mario Bros.]]' adventures in the [[Mushroom Kingdom]] and are based primarily on the [[Valiant Comics|Valiant comics]] published for the [[Nintendo Comics System]] imprint.\n\n{{nihongo foot|''[[Super Mario Adventures]]''|SUPER MARIO ADVENTURES \u30de\u30ea\u30aa\u306e\u5927\u5192\u967a|''Mario no daib\u014dken''|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha|<ref>\"[https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0006QBMK0 Super Mario Adventures Official Nintendo Comic Book (Paperback)].\" ''Amazon.com''. Retrieved on November 19, 2008.</ref>}} is an [[anthology]] of comics, drawn in a Japanese [[manga]] style, that ran in ''[[Nintendo Power]]'' magazine throughout 1992, featuring the characters from Nintendo's ''[[Mario]]'' series and based loosely on ''[[Super Mario World]]''.\n\nImmediately following the end of ''Super Mario Adventures'', ''Nintendo Power'' concluded the epic with a ten-page story based on ''[[Super Mario Land 2: 6 Golden Coins]]'' titled ''[[Super Mario Adventures#Mario vs. Wario|Mario VS Wario]]'', which ran in their January 1993 issue and was later reprinted in the graphic novel.\n\nAt one point, [[Archie Comics]] made a pitch to Nintendo for a new Mario comic similar to its ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog (comics)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' series, but it was turned down.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gonintendo.com/stories/245998-archie-pitched-nintendo-a-super-mario-comic-but-it-was-shot-down|title=Archie Pitched Nintendo a Super Mario Comic, But It Was Shot Down|date=September 12, 2015|website=GoNintendo|publisher=rawmeatcowboy|accessdate=September 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAn encyclopedia based on ''Super Mario Bros.'' was released in Japan in October 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nintendo releasing 256-page Mario encyclopedia in Japan next month|url=http://nintendoeverything.com/nintendo-releasing-256-page-mario-encyclopedia-in-japan-next-month/|website=Nintendo Everything|accessdate=September 9, 2015}}</ref> In February 2017, Nintendo announced that the encyclopedia would launch in North America and Europe in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Super Mario Bros. Encyclopedia coming to North America and Europe in June|url=http://nintendoeverything.com/super-mario-bros-encyclopedia-coming-to-north-america-and-europe-in-june/|website=Nintendo Everything|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAnother encyclopedia based on the series up until ''Super Mario Maker'' was published by Dark Horse Publishing on October 23, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/02/marios_very_own_encylopedia_will_leap_onto_book_shelves_this_october|title=Mario's Very Own Encyclopedia Will Leap Onto Book Shelves This October|website=Nintendo Life|accessdate=February 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Merchandise ===\n[[File:Nintendo DS Mario Edition.jpg|thumb|250px|right|A ''Mario''-themed [[Nintendo DS Lite]].]]\nMario has appeared on lunch boxes, T-shirts, jeans,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/LEVIS/status/1234536816071471104|title=\ud83d\udc56x \ud83c\udf44. Coming soon.|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> magazines, commercials (notably, in a [[Got Milk?]] commercial),<ref>Weiss, Jodi & Kahn, Russell (2004). In ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=Mp0LRxu0ibsC&pg=PA25&dq=%22got+milk%22+mario&ei=-_b0Sr7sG5PyNJ3B1YoF#v=onepage&q=%22got%20milk%22%20mario&f=false 145 Things to Be When You Grow Up]''. Princeton Review Publishing. p. 25. {{ISBN|0-375-76369-4}}. Google Book Search. Retrieved on November 6, 2009.</ref> in candy form, on shampoo bottles, cereal, badges, and as a [https://web.archive.org/web/20141025050156/http://www.tvgome.com/en/15-super-mario plush toy].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamecubicle.com/features-mario-nintendo_shining_star.htm|title=Nintendo's Shining Star: The History of Mario|publisher=GameCubicle|accessdate=August 23, 2008}}</ref> In 1992, [[Gottlieb]] created a Super Mario themed [[pinball]] machine.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Gottlieb's Super Mario Bros. Pin|journal=Cash Box|date=May 25, 1992|volume=55|issue=39|page=25|accessdate=August 20, 2017|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Cash-Box/90s/1992/CB-1992-05-23.pdf}}</ref> A [[Monopoly (game)|Monopoly]] board game based on the ''Mario'' franchise has been confirmed by the website USAopoly.<ref>{{cite web|author=USAopoly|title=MONOPOLY\u00ae: Super Mario Bros.\u2122 Collector's Edition|url=http://usaopoly.com/games/monopoly-super-mario-bros-collectors-edition|website=USAopoly|access-date=May 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171219170204/http://usaopoly.com/games/monopoly-super-mario-bros-collectors-edition|archive-date=December 19, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> In April 2017, a board game developed by USAopoly titled ''Super Mario Level Up!'' has been announced for release.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Super Mario game REVEALED \u2013 but it's NOT for Nintendo Switch|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/tech/gaming/605999/Super-Mario-Level-Up-Board-Game-Nintendo-Switch|accessdate=April 16, 2017}}</ref> In early 2017, a ''Super Mario''-themed pop-up bar known as \"The Cherry Blossom Pub\" opened up in [[Mockingbird Hill]], [[Washington, D.C.]]. The interior of one side of the bar has been transformed into \"a Nintendo dream world\". ''The Washington'' reported in an interview with Derek Brown, the bar's owner, that the bar had become so popular that there was a two-hour long line outside the bar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonian.com/2017/03/21/you-cant-bribe-your-way-into-the-cherry-blossom-bar/|title=You Can't Bribe Your Way Into The Cherry Blossom Bar|date=March 21, 2017|website=washingtonian.com}}</ref> The cocktails in the bar cost $13 and are all Mario-themed. On the menu there's the \u201cIt\u2019s a Me, A-Mario\u201d (sweet vermouth, Don Ciccio & Figli Carcafio, Aperitivo, and spicy ginger ale), \u201cWhat Doesn\u2019t Kill You Makes You Smaller\u201d (vodka, mandarin orange, pomelo and apricot soda) and the \u201cKing Koopa Cup\u201d (Two James Johnny Smoking Gun whiskey, \u201cpopcorn\u201d tea ginger, and lemon).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelandleisure.com/food-drink/bars-clubs/super-mario-cherry-blossom-bar-dc|title=This Super Mario-themed Bar Has Nintendo Fans Lining up for Hours|last=https://plus.google.com/+travelandleisure/posts|website=travelandleisure.com}}</ref> Another Monopoly-inspired board game called ''Monopoly Gamer'' was released in August 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hasbro and Nintendo introduce MONOPOLY GAMER, a new way to play MONOPOLY|url=http://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/hasbro-and-nintendo-introduce-monopoly-gamer|website=Nintendo|date=June 28, 2017|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref> In addition, Monopoly Gamer adds a ''Mario Kart'' version with courses from ''Mario Kart 8'' serving as properties. Mario-themed [[Lego]] sets are set to be released in August 2020, these sets feature a Mario figure that interacts with certain elements in the environment.<ref>https://www.lego.com/en-us/campaigns/supermario?icmp=HP-SHSB-Standard-Leaf_Sidekick_Standard_Supermario_HP-TH-MAR-M45K3UAV7S</ref>\n\n=== Concerts and performances ===\nThe ''Super Mario Bros.'' theme has been featured in many concerts, including \"PLAY! Chicago\",<ref name=\"m4g\">{{cite web |title=Super Mario Bros. and Zelda composer Koji Kondo to attend PLAY! Chicago |url=http://www.music4games.net/News_Display.aspx?id=184 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225004700/http://www.music4games.net/News_Display.aspx?id=184 |archivedate=February 25, 2009 |publisher=Music 4 Games |accessdate=February 13, 2009 |date=April 14, 2006}}</ref> the [[Columbus Symphony Orchestra]],<ref name=\"columbus\">{{cite web |title=Symphony piles up points with video-game concert |url=http://www.columbusdispatch.com/live/content/life/stories/2007/04/26/gamer_concert.html |publisher=[[The Columbus Dispatch]] |accessdate=February 13, 2009 |date=April 27, 2007}}{{dead link|date=April 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> the Mario & Zelda Big Band Live,{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} Play! A Video Game Symphony,<ref name=\"play\">{{cite web |title=I hear a video game symphony |url=http://www.popjournalism.ca/pop/news/2006/00266playconcert.shtml |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215021437/http://www.popjournalism.ca/pop/news/2006/00266playconcert.shtml |archivedate=December 15, 2007 |publisher=Pop Journalism |accessdate=February 13, 2009 |date=September 27, 2006}}</ref> and others.\n\nThe [[Video Games Live]] concert featured the theme performed by Koji Kondo.<ref name=\"interview\">{{cite web |title=Super Mario Bros. Composer Koji Kondo Interview |url=http://www.1up.com/features/mario-maestro |publisher=[[1UP.com]] |accessdate=February 16, 2009 |date=October 19, 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{See also|Super Mario#Reception}}\n\nThe ''Mario'' series has received a very positive reception from critics and audiences. A 1996 article in ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'' declared that \"The evolution of the ''Mario'' series led the rest of gaming by the hand, blazing a trail, and teaching lessons in game mechanics, structure, and sheer playability to any who would study its secrets\".\n\n== Setting ==\nMost of Mario's games are set in the fictional '''[[Mushroom Kingdom]]''', but there are other settings which explore more details of the Mario Universe.\n\nThe places introduced in the ''Mario'' franchise are:\n\n* '''[[Mushroom Kingdom]]''', the central kingdom of the universe and the setting of most Mario games. It is usually ruled by '''[[Princess Peach]]'''. The capital of the kingdom is '''Toad Town''', a city that lies below Peach's Castle.\n* '''Subcon''' is the dreamworld that is the setting of [[Super Mario Bros. 2]].\n* '''Bowser's Kingdom''', the kingdom ruled by '''[[Bowser (character)|Bowser]]''', the main antagonist of the series. The kingdom has appeared in several games under different names, and often appears as the final level of the game which it is featured in. The first time this kingdom appears under the name Bowser's Kingdom is in ''[[Super Mario Odyssey]]''.\n* '''Sprixie Kingdom''', introduced in ''[[Super Mario 3D World]]'', is home to fairy-like creatures called '''Sprixies'''. It is composed of 8 islands with different themes, with each island being ruled by a Sprixie. It is the main setting of ''[[Super Mario 3D World]]''.\n* '''Kingdom of Bask''', introduced in ''[[Mario Tennis Aces]]'', the Kingdom of Bask was ruled by '''King Bask''' until '''Lucien''', the main antagonist of the game, attacked it, forcing King Bask to split his power into Power Stones. It is the main setting of ''Mario Tennis Aces''.\n* '''Sarasaland''', introduced in ''[[Super Mario Land]]'', is ruled by '''[[Princess Daisy]]''', and is divided into four kingdoms: '''Birabuto Kingdom''' (based on [[Ancient Egypt]]), '''Muda Kingdom''' (based on Mu and [[Bermuda]]), '''Easton Kingdom''' (based on Easter Island) and '''Chai Kingdom''' (based on [[Ancient China]]). It is the main setting of ''Super Mario Land''.\n* '''Beanbean Kingdom''', introduced in ''[[Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga]]'', is governed by '''Queen Bean''' and his son '''Prince Peasley'''. The capital is '''Beanbean Castle Town''', and the kingdom is known to have good relations with the '''[[Mushroom Kingdom]]''', in addition to bordering it. The regions are named after laughter onomatopoeias. Just like the Mushroom Kingdom is mushroom themed, the Beanbean Kingdom is bean themed. It is also home to the famous '''Chuckola Cola'''. The forest where it is produced is named '''Chucklehuck Woods'''. It is the main setting of ''Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga''.\n* '''Pi'illo Island''', formerly known as '''Pi'illo Kingdom''', is introduced in ''[[Mario & Luigi: Dream Team]]'', and is an island that was ruled by '''Prince Dreambert''' until he and the other Pi'illos were imprisoned by '''Antasma''', the main antagonist of the game. At some undefined time in the past, the island was acquired by '''Dr. Snoozemore'''. At the end of the game, with all the Pi'illos released, the island is once again governed by '''Prince Dreambert.''' It is the main setting of ''Mario & Luigi: Dream Team''.\n* '''Isle Delfino''', introduced in ''[[Super Mario Sunshine]]'', is a [[dolphin]]-shaped paradise island somewhere outside the [[Mushroom Kingdom]]. It's the setting for ''[[Super Mario Sunshine]]''. The capital is '''Delfino Plaza'''.\n* ''[[Super Mario Odyssey]]'' introduces a variety of new locations such as the '''Cap Kingdom''', '''Cascade Kingdom''', '''Metro Kingdom''' and '''Luncheon Kingdom''', just to name a few.\n\n== Impact and legacy ==\nMario has been featured in 256 games of various genres (including sports, puzzle, party, racing and first-person shooter), and the ''Mario'' franchise is the [[List of best-selling video game franchises|best-selling video game franchise of all time]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/releases/mmnr/Super_Mario_Galaxy/index.html |title=Italian Plumber More Memorable Than Harper, Dion |accessdate=April 4, 2010 |date=December 13, 2007 |publisher=CNW Group |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090911224500/http://www.newswire.ca/en/releases/mmnr/Super_Mario_Galaxy/index.html |url-status=dead |archivedate=September 11, 2009 }}</ref> At least 31 different ''Mario'' games have sold more than a million copies each since 1995. This includes the core ''[[Super Mario (series)|Super Mario]]'' series, which alone has sold over 262 million units worldwide,<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110531005315/en/Nintendo-DS-Lite-Suggested-Retail-Price-Drops |title= Nintendo DS Lite Suggested Retail Price Drops to $99.99 and Mario Games Go Red |date=May 31, 2011 |publisher=[[Business Wire]] |accessdate=May 31, 2011}}</ref> as well as the ''[[Mario Kart]]'' series which sold 78 million units,<ref name=\"mariokart\">*12 million in North America as of November 15, 2005: {{cite press release|url=http://www.nintendo.ca/cgi-bin/usersite/display_info.cgi?lang=en&pageNum=9&id=7279167 |title=Mario Kart DS launches with Wi-Fi gaming service |date=November 15, 2005 |accessdate=March 21, 2009 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090111064204/http://www.nintendo.ca/cgi-bin/usersite/display_info.cgi?lang=en&pageNum=9&id=7279167 |archivedate=January 11, 2009 }}\n* {{cite web|title=Japan Platinum Game Chart |url=http://www.the-magicbox.com/Chart-JPPlatinum.shtml |publisher=The Magic Box |accessdate=March 15, 2012 }}\n** ''[[Super Mario Kart]]'': 3.82 million\n** ''[[Mario Kart 64]]'': 2.24 million\n* ''[[Mario Kart: Double Dash!!]]'' sales in Japan as of January 2, 2005: 802,217 ({{cite web|title=2004 Top 100 Best Selling Japanese Console Games |url=http://www.the-magicbox.com/Chart-BestSell2004.shtml |publisher=The Magic Box |accessdate=March 15, 2012 |date=January 2, 2005 }})\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2012/120127e.pdf#page=7 |title=Financial Results Briefing for the Nine-Month Period Ended December 2011 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |date=January 27, 2012 |format=PDF |accessdate=February 8, 2012 |page=6 }}:\n** ''[[Mario Kart DS]]'': 22.3 million\n** ''[[Mario Kart 7]]'': 4.54 million\n** ''[[Mario Kart Wii]]'': 31.91 million</ref> the ''[[Mario Party]]'' series which sold over 32 million units,<ref name=\"marioparty\">{{cite web|title=Mario Party 9 for Wii Lets You Party Like You've Never Partied Before|url=https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/KoFSBbHMQS8jbGp-gxCmymMOiMg1fIeg|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|accessdate=March 15, 2012|date=March 12, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'' which sold over [[List of highest-grossing arcade games|125,000 arcade machines]]<ref>*Japan: 65,000 ({{cite book|first1=Brian | last1=Ashcraft | first2=Jean | last2= Snow|title=Arcade Mania: The Turbo-charged World of Japan's Game Centers|year=2008|publisher=[[Kodansha|Kodansha International]]|location=Tokyo|isbn=978-4-7700-3078-8|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wX8kAQAAIAAJ&dq=\"sixty-five+thousand\"|edition=1st |accessdate=February 12, 2012|quote=Jumpman hopped over barrels, climbed ladders, and jumped from suspended platform to suspended platform as he tried to rescue a damsel from his pissed-off pet gorilla. The game was a smash, and sixty-five thousand cabinets were sold in Japan, propping up the then-struggling Nintendo and laying the groundwork for Nintendo and ''Donkey Kong'' creator Shigeru Miyamoto to dominate gaming throughout the 1980s and beyond.}})\n* United States: 60,000 ({{Cite book|author=Steven L. Kent|year=2001|title=The Ultimate History of Video Games: The Story behind the Craze that Touched Our Lives and Changed the World|publisher=[[Prima Games|Prima]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C2MH05ogU9oC|accessdate=April 9, 2011|page=352|quote=With more than 60,000 units sold in the United States, Donkey Kong was Nintendo's biggest arcade hit. ... Nintendo released Donkey Kong Junior in 1982 and sold only 30,000 machines, 20,000 Popeye machines (also 1982), and a mere 5000 copies of Donkey J (1983).|isbn=978-0-7615-3643-7}})</ref>\nand six million [[Coleco]] [[ROM cartridge|cartridges]],<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=David Sheff|last=Sheff|first=David|year=1999|title=Game Over: Press Start to Continue: The Maturing of Mario|title-link=Game Over (book)|page=121|publisher=Wilton, Connecticut: GamePress}}: {{quote|\"And we received from Coleco an agreement that they would pay us three percent of the net sales price [of all the \"Donkey Kong\" cartridges Coleco sold].\" It turned out to be an impressive number of cartridges, 6 million, which translated into $4.6 million.}}</ref> and ''[[Mario Bros.]]'' which sold 1.72 million [[Nintendo Entertainment System|Famicom]] cartridges.<ref name=\"famicommini\">{{cite web |title=Nintendojofr|url=http://www.nintendojofr.com/redaction/editoriaux/?id=aVAd |date=September 26, 2006 |publisher=Nintendojo |accessdate=October 9, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080730022258/http://www.nintendojofr.com/redaction/editoriaux/?id=aVAd |archivedate = July 30, 2008}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal bar|Video games|Japan}}\n{{Wikipedia books|Mario franchise video games}}\n* [[List of Luigi video games|List of ''Luigi'' video games]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links | wikt=no | c=Category:Mario_(video game series) | v=no | q=Mario (franchise) | s=no | b=no | n =no | display=''Mario (franchise)''}}\n*[http://mario.nintendo.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Mario series}}\n{{Main franchises by Nintendo}}\n{{Portal bar|Japan|Video games|1980s|1990s}}\n\n[[Category:Mario| ]]\n[[Category:Mario video games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo franchises]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises introduced in 1981]]\n[[Category:Video games produced by Shigeru Miyamoto]]\n[[Category:Video games adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Video games adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Video games adapted into television programs]]\n[[Category:Action-adventure games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Video game franchise}}\n{{About|the media franchise|the video game series|Super Mario}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox media franchise\n| color           = #fc0000\n| title           = Mario\n| image           = Mario emblem.svg\n| image_upright   =\n| caption         = The emblem on [[Mario]]'s hat is iconic in the ''Mario'' franchise\n| creator         = [[Shigeru Miyamoto]]\n| origin          = [[Donkey Kong (video game)|''Donkey Kong'' (1981)]]\n| owner           = [[Nintendo]]\n| books           =\n| novels          =\n| short_stories   =\n| comics          = [[List_of_non-video_game_media_featuring_Mario#Comics|Comics list]]\n| graphic_novels  =\n| strips          =\n| magazines       =\n| films           = [[List_of_non-video_game_media_featuring_Mario#Films|Films list]]\n| shorts          =\n| tv_series       =\n| web_series      =\n| animated_series = [[List_of_non-video_game_media_featuring_Mario#Television|Animated series list]]\n| tv_specials     =\n| tv_shorts       =\n| tv_films        =\n| direct-to-video =\n| plays           =\n| musicals        =\n| games           = [[List_of_non-video_game_media_featuring_Mario#Electromechanical games|Electromechanical games list]]\n| rpgs            =\n| video_games     = {{Unbulleted list\n  | ''[[Super Mario]]'' series\n  | ''[[List of Luigi video games|Luigi]]'' series\n  | ''[[Wario (series)|Wario]]'' series\n  | ''[[List of Yoshi video games|Yoshi]]'' series\n  | ''[[Mario Kart]]'' series\n  | ''[[Mario Party]]'' series\n  | [[List of Mario sports games|''Mario'' sports]] series\n  | [[List of Mario puzzle games|''Mario'' puzzle]] games\n  | [[List of Mario role-playing games|''Mario'' role-playing]] games\n  | ''[[Mario vs. Donkey Kong]]'' series\n  | [[List of Mario educational games|''Mario'' educational]] games\n  }}\n| radio           =\n| soundtracks     =\n| music           = [[List_of_non-video_game_media_featuring_Mario#Music games|Music list]]\n| toys            =\n| attractions     = [[Super Nintendo World]]\n| website         = {{URL|https://mario.nintendo.com/}}\n| footnotes       = <!--Use {{note}}s or {{note label}}s to go with {{ref}}s and {{ref label}}s in data parameters.-->\n| sp              =\n}}\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Mario'''''|\u30de\u30ea\u30aa|Mario|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[media franchise]], published and produced by Japanese video game company [[Nintendo]], starring the fictional Portuguese character [[Mario]]. It is primarily a [[video game franchise]], with the franchise's other forms of media including several [[List of Mario television series|television series]] and a [[Super Mario Bros. (film)|feature film]]. It was originally created by game designer [[Shigeru Miyamoto]] with the arcade game ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'', released on July 9, 1981. The games have been developed by a variety of developers including Nintendo, [[Hudson Soft]], and [[AlphaDream Corporation|AlphaDream]]. Most ''Mario'' games have been released for Nintendo's various video game consoles and handhelds, from the [[Third generation of video game consoles|third generation]] onward.\n\nThe main series in the franchise is the ''[[Super Mario]]'' series of [[platform game|platform games]] which mostly follows Mario's adventures in the fictional world of the [[Mushroom Kingdom]]. These games typically rely on Mario's jumping ability to allow him to progress through [[Level (video gaming)|levels]]. The franchise has spawned more than 200 games of various genres and series, including ''[[Mario Kart]]'', ''[[Mario Party]]'', ''[[Mario Tennis]]'', and ''[[Mario Golf (video game)|Mario Golf]]''.\n\nThe ''Mario'' series is one of Nintendo's most renowned and successful franchises; many games in its series, specifically the \"Super Mario\" portion, are considered to be some of the [[List of video games considered the best|greatest video games ever made]]. By 2011, the core ''Super Mario'' video games had grossed an estimated {{US$|12 billion}} in sales.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ryan|first1=Jeff|title=Super Mario: How Nintendo Conquered America|date=2011|publisher=[[Penguin Books]]|isbn=9781101517635|page=8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1k-6ksl3uLsC&pg=PT8|language=en}}</ref> More than 600 million copies of ''Mario'' games have been sold, making it the [[List of best-selling video game franchises|best-selling video game franchise of all time]]. It is also the 9th [[List of highest-grossing media franchises|highest-grossing media franchise]] of all time, with an estimated revenue above {{US$|36 billion|long=no}}.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Characters ==\n{{Main|List of Mario franchise characters}}\n\n== Video games ==\n{{Main|List of video games featuring Mario}}\n\n=== Origin games ===\n\n==== ''[[Donkey Kong]]'' ====\n{{Main|Donkey Kong (video game)}}\n[[File:Donkey Kong arcade.png|thumb|125px|A replica of a ''Donkey Kong'' arcade cabinet.]]\n\nAfter the commercial failure of ''[[Radar Scope]]'', Nintendo's company president referred to [[Shigeru Miyamoto]] to create an arcade game to save the company. Miyamoto came up with the idea of a game in which the playable character has to make his way through an obstacle course consisting of sloped platforms, ladders and rolling barrels. Miyamoto named the game ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'', and its main protagonist \"Jumpman\". ''Donkey Kong'' is an early example of the [[platform game|platform]] genre. In addition to presenting the goal of saving Pauline, the game gives the player a [[score (gaming)|score]]. Points are awarded for finishing screens; leaping over obstacles; destroying objects with a hammer [[power-up]]; collecting items such as hats, [[parasol]]s, and [[Coin purse|purse]]s (presumably belonging to the Lady/Pauline); and completing other tasks. The game was surprisingly successful.<ref>{{Cite news|date=June 1994|title=|periodical=[[Nintendo Power]]|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|issue=61|pages=}}</ref> \"Jumpman\" was called \"[[Mario]]\" in certain promotional materials for the game's release overseas;<ref name=\"US Donkey Kong promo flyer\">{{cite web|url=https://flyers.arcade-museum.com/?page=flyer&db=videodb&id=316&image=2 |title= Video Game Flyers: Donkey Kong, Nintendo |work= The Arcade Flyer Archive |accessdate= October 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"France Donkey Kong promo flyer\">{{cite web|url=https://flyers.arcade-museum.com/?page=flyer&db=videodb&id=2950&image=2 |title=Video Game Flyers: Donkey Kong, Karateco |work=The Arcade Flyer Archive |accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref> his namesake was [[Mario Segale]], the landlord of [[Nintendo of America]]'s office/warehouse, who barged in on a meeting to demand an overdue rent payment.<ref>{{cite web|title=10 Mario Fun Facts!|url=http://www.neatorama.com/2007/09/22/10-mario-fun-facts/|accessdate=September 29, 2007}}</ref> Eventually Jumpman's name was internationally and permanently changed to Mario. The success of the game spawned several ports, and a sequel, ''[[Donkey Kong Jr.]]'', which is Mario's only appearance as an antagonist. ''[[Donkey Kong 3]]'' did not feature Mario.\n\n==== ''Mario Bros.'' ====\n{{Main|Mario Bros.}}\n\nThe ''Mario'' branding was used for the first time in a later arcade game, ''[[Mario Bros.]]'', which introduced Mario's brother, [[Luigi]]. The objective of ''Mario Bros.'' is to defeat all of the enemies in each [[Level (video gaming)|phase]]. Each phase is a series of platforms with four pipes at each corner of the screen, and an object called a \"POW\" block in the center.<ref name=\"NESpg5\">{{cite book |author=Nintendo |title=Mario Bros. manual |section=pg. 5 |version=Nintendo Entertainment System |year=1983 }}</ref><ref name=\"NESpg8\">{{cite book |author=Nintendo |title=Mario Bros. manual |section=pg. 8 |version=Nintendo Entertainment System |year=1983 }}</ref> The mechanics of ''Mario Bros.'' involve only running and jumping. Unlike future ''Mario'' titles, players cannot jump on enemies until they are flipped over; this can be accomplished by jumping under the platform they are on or by using the \"POW\" block. Both sides of every phase feature a mechanism that allows the player to go off-screen to the left and appear on the right, and vice versa.<ref name=\"NESpg8\" /> The game has since reappeared in various forms, including as a minigame in ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' and the ''[[Super Mario Advance]]'' series, and reimagined as ''[[Mario Clash]]''.\n\n==== Game & Watch ====\n{{Main|List of LCD games featuring Mario}}\n\n[[Nintendo]] has released several ''Mario'' and ''[[Donkey Kong]]'' LCD video games for the [[Game & Watch series|Game & Watch line]]. Eleven were released between 1982 and 1994. Nintendo also licensed the release of six LCD games for [[Nelsonic Industries|Nelsonic]]'s Game Watch line between 1989 and 1994. Many remakes of Game & Watch games have changed the protagonist from a generic [[Game & Watch#Mr. Game & Watch|Mr. Game & Watch]] character to Mario.\n\n=== Platform games ===\n==== ''Super Mario'' series ====\n{{Main|Super Mario}}\nMario then became the star of his own side scrolling platform game in [[1985 in video gaming|1985]], titled ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'', which was the pack-in game included with the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] console. It was also later sold in a package with ''[[Duck Hunt]]''. In [[Japan]], a game titled ''[[Super Mario Bros.: The Lost Levels|Super Mario Bros. 2]]'' was released in [[1986 in video gaming|1986]], but a different [[Super Mario Bros. 2|game with the same name]] was released internationally in [[1988 in video gaming|1988]], followed by ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' later that same year. The Japanese version would subsequently be released in the United States in [[1993 in video gaming|1993]] under the title ''Super Mario Bros.: The Lost Levels'' as part of the ''[[Super Mario All-Stars]]'' title for the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]], a console that also features iterations of the game known as ''[[Super Mario World]]''. While ''[[Super Mario Land]]'' and two sequels were the [[Game Boy]] installments in the series, the [[Game Boy Advance]] did not receive any original entries, only [[Video game remake|remakes]]. ''[[Super Mario 64]]'' debuted as the launch title for the [[Nintendo 64]] console in [[1996 in video gaming|1996]]. ''[[Super Mario Sunshine]]'' was the series' entry for the [[GameCube]], and ''[[Super Mario Galaxy]]'' and its [[Super Mario Galaxy 2|sequel]] continued the franchise for the [[Wii]]. ''[[Super Mario 3D Land]]'' was the series' flagship title for [[Nintendo 3DS]]. The [[Wii U]] saw the release of ''[[Super Mario 3D World]]''. ''[[Super Mario Odyssey]]'' would be the first original game in the series to be released on the [[Nintendo Switch]], and was released in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/features/2017/11/8/16621744/the-best-mario-games|title=Ranking the core Super Mario games|first=Jeremy | last=Parish | date=November 8, 2017 | accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, a [[Retrogaming#Modern retrogaming|retro]] throwback sub-series called ''[[New Super Mario Bros.]]'' was inaugurated on the Nintendo DS, featuring the mechanics of the ''Super Mario Bros.'' games. It continued on the Wii as ''[[New Super Mario Bros. Wii]]'', on the 3DS as ''[[New Super Mario Bros. 2]]'' and on the [[Wii U]] as ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U]]'' and '' [[New Super Luigi U]]'', with a sequel titled ''[[New Super Mario Bros. U Deluxe]] on the Nintendo Switch in January, 2020. This gameplay is further offered by the level creator game ''[[Super Mario Maker]]'', released on [[Wii U]] in 2015. A sequel, ''[[Super Mario Maker 2]]'', was released on Nintendo Switch in June 2019.\n\nIn 2016, the team behind ''New Super Mario Bros.'' released ''[[Super Mario Run]]'' that became Nintendo's first real [[smartphone]] game and one of the few instances a ''Mario'' game was developed for non-Nintendo hardware.<ref name=\"MarioRun\">{{cite web|last1=Ingraham|first1=Nathan|title='Super Mario Run' is just as much fun as we'd hoped|url=https://www.engadget.com/2016/12/08/super-mario-run-iphone-hands-on/|publisher=Engadet|accessdate=December 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Puzzle games ===\n{{Main|List of Mario puzzle games}}\n\n==== ''Dr. Mario'' series ====\n[[File:Dr. Mario series logo.png|thumb|The ''Dr. Mario'' series logo.]]\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Dr. Mario'''''|\u30c9\u30af\u30bf\u30fc\u30de\u30ea\u30aa|Dokut\u0101 Mario|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} (stylized as ''D\u211e. Mario'') is a series of [[arcade game|arcade-style]] [[puzzle video game#action puzzle|action puzzle video game]] originally developed by Nintendo Research & Development 1, and later developed by [[Arika]] and produced by [[Nintendo Software Planning & Development]]. The first in the series, ''[[Dr. Mario]]'', was launched in 1990 on the Nintendo Entertainment System and Game Boy to critical and commercial success.<ref name=\"NP Top 200\">{{Cite news|date=February 2006| title=NP Top 200|periodical=Nintendo Power|volume=200|pages=58\u201366}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Best NES Games of all time |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/best-nes-games-all-time/ |work=[[GamesRadar]] |date=April 16, 2012 |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> In the ''Dr. Mario'' series, the [[player character]] [[Mario]], who assumes the role of a [[physician|doctor]], is tasked with eradicating deadly [[virus]]es. The player's objective is to destroy the viruses populating the on-screen playing field by using falling colored [[capsule (pharmacy)|capsules]] that are dropped into the field, similarly to ''[[Tetris]]''. The player manipulates the capsules as they fall so that they are aligned with viruses of matching colors, which removes them from playing field. The player progresses through the game by eliminating all the viruses on the screen in each [[level (video gaming)|level]].\n\n<!-- Titles -->\nThere have been 4 ''[[Dr. Mario]]'' games released for home consoles and two portable games, for a total of six original titles. As the series has progressed, each new game has introduced new elements in order to keep the gameplay fresh such as new game modes. In 2001, ''[[Dr. Mario 64]]'' for the Nintendo 64 introduced new game modes such as a ''Story'' mode, ''Score Attack'' and ''Marathon'', [[Wario]] as a playable character and four-player multiplayer. After a seven-year hiatus, in 2008, ''[[Dr. Mario Express]]'' for the [[Nintendo DSi]]'s [[DSiWare]] service re-introduced the series to the portable gaming market. Also in 2008, ''[[Dr. Mario Online Rx]]'' for the [[Wii]]'s [[WiiWare]] service introduced [[online multiplayer]] to the series. In 2013, ''[[Dr. Luigi]]'' for the [[Wii U]]'s [[Nintendo eShop]] introduced [[Luigi]] as the playable character as well as a ''Operation L'' game mode in which all capsules assume the shape of the letter \"L\".\n\n==== ''Mario's Picross'' series ====\nThis series is a collection of [[nonogram]] logic puzzles involving a grid with numbers for every row and column, which refer to the amount of marked squares within the grid. The games features Mario as an [[Archaeology|archaeologist]] who chisels away to form images on the grid.\n* ''[[Mario's Picross]]''\n* ''[[Picross 2]]''\n* ''[[Mario's Super Picross]]''\n\n==== ''Mario vs. Donkey Kong'' series ====\n{{Main|Mario vs. Donkey Kong}}\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Mario vs. Donkey Kong'''''|\u30de\u30ea\u30aaVS\u30c9\u30f3\u30ad\u30fc\u30b3\u30f3\u30b0|Mario tai Donk\u012b Kongu|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a sub-series of the ''Mario'' and ''[[Donkey Kong]]'' series, based on [[puzzle video games]], making the return of [[Donkey Kong (character)|Donkey Kong]], [[List of Mario series characters|Pauline]], and the former's rivalry with [[Mario]]. The sub-series introduces the Mario-like toys known as Mini-Marios, who later replace Mario as the sole playable characters in all future installments starting with ''[[Mario vs. Donkey Kong 2: March of the Minis|March of the Minis]]'' onward.\n\n=== Racing games ===\n{{Main|List of Mario racing games}}\n\n==== ''Mario Kart'' series ====\n{{Main|Mario Kart}}\n[[File:Mario Kart logo.png|thumb|The ''Mario Kart'' series logo since ''Mario Kart DS''.]]\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Mario Kart'''''|\u30de\u30ea\u30aa\u30ab\u30fc\u30c8|Mario K\u0101to|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a series of [[go-kart]]-style [[racing video game]]s primarily developed by Nintendo Entertainment Analysis & Development. The first in the series, ''[[Super Mario Kart]]'', was launched in 1992 on the Super Nintendo Entertainment System to critical and commercial success.<ref>Crecente, Brian (2009-26-2). \"[http://kotaku.com/5160745/super-mario-kart-most-influential-video-game-in-history Super Mario Kart: Most Influential Video Game in History].\" ''Kotaku.'' Retrieved January 27, 2012.</ref> In the ''Mario Kart'' series, players compete in [[Kart racing|go-kart races]], controlling one of a selection of characters from the ''Mario'' franchise. One of the features of the series is the use of various [[power-up]] items obtained by driving into item boxes laid out on the course. These power-ups include [[Super Mushroom]]s to give players a speed boost, [[Koopa Troopa|Koopa Shells]] to be thrown at opponents, and [[banana peel]]s that can be laid on the track as hazards.<ref name=WM>{{cite web|last=Dan|title=Mario Kart Franchise Retrospective|url=http://www.watchmojo.com/video/title/Mario%20Kart%20Franchise%20Retrospective/|publisher=[[WatchMojo.com]]|accessdate=February 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Titles -->\nThere have been five ''Mario Kart'' games released for home consoles, one enhanced port, three portable games, one game for smartphones, and three [[Namco]] co-developed arcade spin-off games, for a total of thirteen. As the series has progressed, each new game has introduced new elements in order to keep the gameplay fresh such as new courses, new items, and new playable characters.<ref name=\"WM\" /> In 1996 and 1997, ''[[Mario Kart 64]]'' for the Nintendo 64 introduced 4-player racing and [[3D computer graphics|3D graphics]].<ref name=WM /> In 2001, ''[[Mario Kart: Super Circuit|Super Circuit]]'' for the Game Boy Advance introduced the ability to unlock retro tracks from previous installments. In 2003, ''[[Mario Kart: Double Dash!!|Double Dash!!]]'' for the GameCube introduced [[co-operative]] [[LAN party|LAN multiplayer]] and two-player karts.<ref name=WM /> In 2005, ''[[Mario Kart DS]]'' for the Nintendo DS introduced [[dual-screen]] play and [[online multiplayer]] via [[Wi-Fi]]. In 2008, ''[[Mario Kart Wii]]'' introduced [[motion control]]s, 12-player racing, [[motorbikes]] and playable [[Mii]] characters,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/news/mario-kart-wii-detailed|title=Mario Kart Wii Detailed|publisher=1UP|date=February 6, 2008|accessdate=May 21, 2013|author=Sato, Yoshi|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029192825/http://www.1up.com/news/mario-kart-wii-detailed|archivedate=October 29, 2013}}</ref> as well as three new items: the POW Block, Mega Mushroom, and Thunder Cloud. In 2011, ''[[Mario Kart 7]]'' for the Nintendo 3DS featured optional [[Stereoscopy|stereoscopic graphics]], introduced [[hang gliders|hang gliding]] and [[amphibious vehicle|submersible]] karts, an alternate [[First-person (video games)|first-person]] perspective, and kart customization.<ref name=WM /> In 2014, ''[[Mario Kart 8]]'' for the Wii U introduced [[anti-gravity]] racing, [[All-terrain vehicle|ATVs]], uploading highlights to [[YouTube]] via Mario Kart TV, up to four local players in Grand Prix races, [[downloadable content]], and is the first in the series to boast [[High-definition television|HD graphics]]. In 2017, ''[[Mario Kart 8 Deluxe]]'' for the Nintendo Switch was released as an enhanced port of the Wii U version, featuring an improved battle mode and several new characters including the Inklings from ''[[Splatoon]]''.\n\n<!-- Sales -->\nPossibly the most popular spin-off series in the franchise, the ''Mario Kart'' series began in 1992 and is currently the most successful and longest-running [[kart racing]] series, having sold over 130,000,000 copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Passary|first1=Anu|title='Mario Kart 8' revs up to 1,200,000 units in sales, becomes fastest-selling Wii U game|url=http://www.techtimes.com/articles/7929/20140604/mario-kart-8-revs-up-to-1-2-million-units-in-sales-becomes-fastest-selling-wii-u-game.htm|website=TechTimes|accessdate=July 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Role-playing games ===\n{{Main|List of Mario role-playing games}}\n\nThe first role-playing game in the ''Mario'' franchise was ''[[Super Mario RPG: Legend of the Seven Stars]]''. It has since expanded to the ''Paper Mario'' and ''Mario & Luigi'' series.\n\n==== ''Paper Mario'' series ====\n[[File:Paper Mario series logo.png|thumb|The ''Paper Mario'' series logo.]]\n\n{{nihongo foot|'''''Paper Mario'''''|\u30da\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30de\u30ea\u30aa|P\u0113p\u0101 Mario|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a spin-off series of [[Role-playing video game|RPG video games]] developed by [[Intelligent Systems]] and produced by Nintendo Software Planning & Development. The first game in the series, ''[[Paper Mario]]'', was launched in 2000 on the Nintendo 64 to critical and commercial success.<ref name=\"IGN Paper Mario\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.ign64.ign.com/articles/150/150453p1.html|title=Paper Mario review|publisher=[[IGN]]|date=February 5, 2001|accessdate=August 17, 2008|last=Casamassina|first=Matt|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090908175849/http://uk.ign64.ign.com/articles/150/150453p1.html|archivedate=September 8, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Nintendo Dominates Japanese Charts|date=August 18, 2000|publisher=[[IGN]]|url= http://ign64.ign.com/articles/083/083746p1.html|accessdate=March 14, 2006}}</ref> In the ''Paper Mario'' series, the player controls Mario in a mixture of [[3D computer graphics|3D]] environments and [[2D computer graphics|2D]] characters who look as if they are made of [[paper]]. Mario can jump and use his hammer to overcome physical obstacles placed in the game's [[overworld]]. Additionally, the player accumulates partners as they advance into different locations, who each have a specialized skill required for progression in the game.<ref name=\"RPGamer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rpgamer.com/games/mario/pmario/reviews/pmariostrev1.html|title=RPGamer\u2014Paper Mario|publisher=RPGamer|accessdate=August 17, 2008|last=Tidwell|first=Mikel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831001300/http://www.rpgamer.com/games/mario/pmario/reviews/pmariostrev1.html|archive-date=August 31, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> These characters assist Mario in the game's turn-based battles. Damage inflicted to the player reduces the amount of [[Health (gaming)|HP]].<ref name=\"RPGFan\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rpgfan.com/reviews/papermario/Paper_Mario.html|title=RPGFan\u2014Paper Mario|publisher=RPGFan|accessdate=August 17, 2008}}</ref> Attacks in the game are similar to those in traditional RPGs, although the player can influence the power of a move when attacking or defending by timing a button-press accurately or performing some other action command as required.<ref name=\"IGN Paper Mario\" /> Mario and his partners have a finite capacity to perform special moves, with each of these consuming a particular number of flower points (FP) when performed. Such statistics can be increased by earning Star Points ([[experience points]]) in combat to [[Experience point#Level-based progression|level up]].<ref name=\"RPGFan\" /><ref name=\"GameSpot\" />\n<ref name=\"GameSpot\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.gamespot.com/paper-mario/reviews/paper-mario-review-2682319/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130819190418/http://uk.gamespot.com/paper-mario/reviews/paper-mario-review-2682319/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 19, 2013 |title=GameSpot: Paper Mario review |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |date=February 5, 2001 |accessdate=August 19, 2013 |last=Stahl |first=Ben }}</ref><ref name=\"Eurogamer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=2104|title=Eurogamer: Paper Mario review|publisher=[[Eurogamer]]|date=February 5, 2001|accessdate=October 18, 2008|first=Tom|last=Bramwell}}</ref> Progression through ''Paper Mario'' depends upon interaction with the game's [[non-player character]]s (NPCs), who will often offer clues or detail the next event in the storyline. As in other RPGs, the player can find or purchase items from NPCs to help in and outside of combat.<ref name=\"GameSpot\" /> Badges can be obtained that yield bonuses ranging from added moves to gradual health restoration during combat; each consumes a set number of Badge Points (BP), meaning Mario can only equip a limited number of badges at a time.<ref name=\"IGN Paper Mario\" />\n\n<!-- Titles -->\nThere have been four ''Paper Mario'' games released for home consoles and one game on 3DS. As the series has progressed, each new game has introduced new elements in order to keep the gameplay fresh such as a new story, new partners, and new gameplay mechanics. In 2004, ''[[Paper Mario: The Thousand-Year Door|The Thousand-Year Door]]'' for the GameCube introduced the ability of Mario turning into and folding up into a paper [[airplane]] and/or a paper [[boat]] to interact with the overworld. In 2007, ''[[Super Paper Mario]]'' deviated into the 2D [[action RPG]] genre and introduced the ability to \"flip\" into a 3D perspective in which the level rotates to reveal a hidden [[Cartesian coordinate system|z-axis]], placing Mario in a 3D environment. In 2012, ''[[Paper Mario: Sticker Star|Sticker Star]]'' for the Nintendo 3DS introduced the use of [[stickers]] in both the environment and in turn-based battles. They can be found and peeled off from various areas in the overworld, and can be purchased or received from [[non-playable characters]]. In 2015, ''[[Mario & Luigi: Paper Jam]]'' also for the 3DS where all the ''Paper Mario'' world enters the real one. In 2016, ''[[Paper Mario: Color Splash|Color Splash]]'' for the Wii U was announced that introduced the use of [[color]]s in both the environment and in turn-based battles, just like in ''Sticker Star''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/new-super-mario-bros-2-luigis-mansion-paper-mario-trailers-jeff-153913/|title=3DS Trailers: 'New Super Mario Bros. 2,' 'Luigi's Mansion' & 'Paper Mario'|first=Jeff|last=Schille|accessdate=September 19, 2016 |publisher=Game Rant}}</ref><ref name=igne32012>{{cite web|url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2012/06/07/e3-2012-first-paper-mario-3ds-details-revealed|title=E3 2012: First Paper Mario 3DS Details Revealed|publisher=IGN|first=Andrew|last=Goldfarb|accessdate=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n* ''Paper Mario'' \n* ''The Thousand-Year Door''\n* ''Super Paper Mario''\n* ''Sticker Star''\n* ''Mario & Luigi: Paper Jam'' (A '''''Mario & Luigi''''' crossover)\n* ''Color Splash''\n\n==== ''Mario & Luigi'' series ====\nThe ''Mario & Luigi'' spin-off series, developed by [[AlphaDream]], is formed exclusively throughout handheld consoles. The series began with the release of ''[[Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga|Superstar Saga]]'' for the Game Boy Advance in 2003. In 2017, ''Superstar Saga '''+ Bowser's Minions''''' for the Nintendo 3DS introduced a remake of the original game with added graphics, an improved map allowing players to place pinpoints, and an additional mode called ''Minion Quest: The Search for Bowser'', which provides a storyline that allows you to take control of Bowser's Minions to search for their leader, facing many obstacles in their way. In 2005, ''[[Mario & Luigi: Partners in Time|Partners in Time]]'' for the Nintendo DS introduced their younger selves: Baby Mario, Baby Luigi, Toadsworth the younger, Baby Peach and Baby Bowser. In 2009, ''[[Mario & Luigi: Bowser's Inside Story|Bowser's Inside Story]]'' also for the DS introduced Mario, Luigi and the others inside of Bowser's body. In 2018, ''Bowser's Inside Story '''+ Bowser Jr.'s Journey''''' for the 3DS introduced a remake of the original game with added graphics, an improved map allowing players to place pinpoints, and an additional mode called ''Bowser Jr.'s Journey''. In 2013, ''[[Mario & Luigi: Dream Team|Dream Team]]'' for the 3DS introduced Dreamy Luigi, where Luigi sleeps in the Dream World in celebrating the [[Year of Luigi]]. In 2015, ''Paper Jam'' also for the 3DS also included Paper Mario as a playable caracter when Luigi knocks over the book containing him.\n\n* ''Superstar Saga''\n** ''Bowser's Minions''\n* ''Partners in Time''\n* ''Bowser's Inside Story''\n** ''Bowser Jr.'s Journey''\n* ''Dream Team''\n* ''Paper Jam'' (A crossover with '''''Paper Mario''''')\n\n=== Party games ===\n==== ''Mario Party'' series ====\n{{Main|Mario Party}}\nIn 1999, the Hudson game ''[[Mario Party (video game)|Mario Party]]'' was released for the Nintendo 64. Following this, 9 numbered sequels have since been released, making for 10 numbered titles, along with two non-numbered main series titles, ''[[Mario Party DS]]'' and ''[[Super Mario Party]]''. The series also has four spins offs that differ in gameplay, including ''[[Mario Party Advance]]'', ''[[Mario Party: Island Tour|Island Tour]]'', ''[[Mario Party: Star Rush|Star Rush]]'', and ''[[Mario Party: The Top 100|The Top 100]]''. ''Mario Party'' is a [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]] party game featuring ''Mario'' series [[List of Mario franchise characters|characters]] in which 4 human- or computer-controlled characters compete in a board game interspersed with [[minigame]]s.\n\n=== Sports games ===\n{{Main|List of Mario sports games}}\nThere have been numerous [[sports games]] in the ''Mario'' franchise.\n\n==== ''Mario Tennis'' series ====\nThe first appearances of Mario in tennis games were as a referee in ''[[Tennis (1984 video game)|Tennis]]'' for the NES and Game Boy. These games did not use the ''Mario'' branding and only featured Mario in the capacity of a cameo. He then appeared in ''[[Mario's Tennis]]'' for the Virtual Boy. After this, [[Camelot Software Planning]] released ''[[Mario Tennis]]'' for the Nintendo 64. They would subsequently develop other games in this series: ''[[Mario Power Tennis]]'' for the GameCube and Wii, ''[[Mario Tennis: Power Tour|Power Tour]]'' for the Game Boy Advance, ''[[Mario Tennis Open]]'' for the Nintendo 3DS, ''[[Mario Tennis: Ultra Smash|Ultra Smash]]'' for the Wii U, and ''[[Mario Tennis Aces|Aces]]'' for the Nintendo Switch.\n\n==== ''Mario Golf'' series ====\nThe first use of Mario's likeness in a golf game was that the golfer in ''[[Golf (1984 video game)|Golf]]'' for NES and Game Boy featured a mustached man resembling Mario. Later, ''[[NES Open Tournament Golf]]'' was released. It featured Mario and Luigi as the golfers, with [[Princess Peach|Princess Toadstool]] and [[Princess Daisy]] as their caddies. ''[[Mario Golf (video game)|Mario Golf]]'' was released for the N64 in 1999. It was followed by ''[[Mario Golf: Toadstool Tour]]'' for the GameCube, ''[[Mario Golf: Advance Tour]]'' for the Game Boy Advance and ''[[Mario Golf: World Tour]]'' for the Nintendo 3DS.\n\n==== ''Mario Baseball'' series ====\nMario and Luigi were team captains in ''[[Baseball]]'' for the Game Boy. ''[[Mario Superstar Baseball]]'' was released for the GameCube and ''[[Mario Super Sluggers]]'' for the Wii.\n\n==== ''Mario Strikers'' series ====\nThe game of [[Association football|football]] was introduced in one of the minigames in ''[[Mario Party 4]]'' as \"GOOOOOOOAL!!\". The [[List of Mario sports games#Mario Strikers games|''Mario Strikers'' series]] (''Mario Football'' in Europe) made its debut for the GameCube with ''[[Super Mario Strikers]]'' in 2005, developed by [[Next Level Games]]. ''[[Mario Strikers Charged]]'' was released for the Wii in 2007.\n\n==== ''Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games'' series ====\nIn 2008, Mario and his friends appeared alongside the characters from ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog (series)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' in the sports game, ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games]]'', developed by [[Sega]] as the crossover series. A follow-up, ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games|Olympic Winter Games]]'', was released in 2009 and ''[[Mario & Sonic at the London 2012 Olympic Games]]'' was released between November 2011 ([[Wii]]) and February 2012 ([[Nintendo 3DS]]). On November 15, 2013, a third sequel called ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Sochi 2014 Olympic Winter Games|Sochi 2014 Olympic Winter Games]]'' was released exclusively on the [[Wii U]], with a fourth sequel, ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Rio 2016 Olympic Games]]'' for the Wii U, Nintendo 3DS and arcade in 2016. A fifth sequel, ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games Tokyo 2020]]'', was released on Nintendo Switch in November 2019.\n\n=== Educational games ===\n{{Main|List of Mario educational games}}\nIn the early 1990s, many [[educational game]]s were released in the ''Mario'' series. Few of these games were platformers; most sought to teach skills such as typing, mathematics or history. They are officially licensed but not officially recognized by Nintendo. The games were developed independently by Software Toolworks, Interplay and Brainstorm. Nine educational games were released from 1991 to 1996.\n\n=== Games not published by Nintendo ===\nThis section covers games [[Video game developer|developed]] by other companies without Nintendo involvement. These games are officially licensed but not officially recognized by Nintendo.\n\n==== Hudson ====\n[[Hudson Soft]] released two games based on ''[[Mario Bros.]]'' and another similar to ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]''\n\n''[[Mario Bros. Special]]'' is a video game released in 1984 for the Japanese computers [[NEC PC-6001]]mkII, [[NEC PC-6601]], [[NEC PC-8801]], [[FM-7]] and [[Sharp X1]]. It is a remake of the original ''[[Mario Bros.]]'', with new stages, mechanics and gameplay.\n\n''[[Punch Ball Mario Bros.]]'' is a video game released in 1984 for the Japanese computers NEC PC-6001mkII, NEC PC-6601, NEC PC-8801, FM-7 and Sharp X1. It is similar to the original ''Mario Bros.'', but featured a new gameplay mechanic of \"punch balls\", small balls which [[Mario]] and [[Luigi]] can kick into enemies to stun them, instead of hitting them from below, as in the original.\n\nHudson Soft was originally responsible for the ''Mario Party'' series until ''[[Mario Party DS]]'' in 2007, but as of March 2012 this has been taken over by [[Nd Cube]] since Hudson has become a part of [[Konami]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Konami acquiring Hudson|url=http://asia.gamespot.com/news/konami-acquiring-hudson-6286645|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724081748/http://asia.gamespot.com/news/konami-acquiring-hudson-6286645|archivedate=July 24, 2012}}</ref> Many of Hudson's employees now work for Nd Cube.\n\n==== Philips ====\nThree games were planned for development by [[Philips|Philips Interactive Media]] for use on its [[Philips CD-i|CD-i]] machine: ''[[Super Mario's Wacky Worlds]]'', ''[[Hotel Mario]]'', and ''Mario Takes America''. Only ''Hotel Mario'' was released; ''Super Mario's Wacky Worlds'' and ''Mario Takes America'' were eventually cancelled. Philips was given permission to use [[Nintendo]] characters in CD-i games due to their taking part in developing an unreleased [[Video game accessory|add-on]] for the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]] (SNES).<ref name=\"SNES-CD\">{{cite web|title=SNES-CD Profile|url=http://www.n-sider.com/articleview.php?articleid=279|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080217040049/http://www.n-sider.com/articleview.php?articleid=279|archivedate=February 17, 2008|publisher=N-Sider|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> ''Hotel Mario'' did not gain much success, with Nintendo rarely acknowledging it as part of the ''Mario'' series.<ref name=\"1up\">{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=5&cId=3149883 |title=CD-i Games: Nintendo |first=Danny |last=Cowan |publisher=[[1UP.com]] |date=April 25, 2006 |accessdate=June 21, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120720182316/http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=5&cId=3149883 |archivedate=July 20, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"GD\">{{cite web|first=Robert|last=Workman|title=Mascots Gone Wild: Nintendo Characters' Worst Moments (Hotel Mario)|url=http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/mascots-gone-wild-nintendo-characters-worst-moments/132/?cp=2&page=2|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012232126/http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/mascots-gone-wild-nintendo-characters-worst-moments/132/?cp=2&page=2|archivedate=October 12, 2008|date=December 12, 2007|publisher=[[GameDaily]]|accessdate=June 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\n''Super Mario's Wacky Worlds'' is a cancelled [[video game]] planned for the CD-i, developed by [[NovaLogic]], which attempted to duplicate the gameplay of ''[[Super Mario World]]''. Though the game [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprites]] are based on those in ''Super Mario World'', the level design is based on Earth locations rather than Dinosaur Land. Due to the limitations of the CD-i, several features could not be included in the game, such as large numbers of sprites on the screen, and many visual effects. The nature of the pointing device controller provides difficult controls for Mario, as the game has the default controls of running and jumping.\n\n''Mario Takes America'' was proposed about Mario's trip to Hollywood to make his own movie. The game's concept initially impressed Philips, but was cancelled due to the company being unsatisfied with the game's development progress.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Cancelled Mario Game That Was Taken Away By A Bank In Canada|url=https://www.unseen64.net/2014/09/15/mario-takes-america-cdi-cancelled/|website=Unseen64|accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n''Hotel Mario'' is a [[Puzzle video game|puzzle game]] developed by Fantasy Factory and published by Philips Interactive Media for the CD-i in 1994. The primary characters of the game are [[Mario]] and [[Luigi]], who must find [[Princess Peach]] by going through seven [[Bowser (character)|Koopa]] Hotels in the Mushroom Kingdom. Every hotel is divided into multiple stages, and the objective is to close all doors on each stage. The game has been criticized as one of the worst ''Mario''-centered games, mainly because of its [[cutscene]]s and simple gameplay.<ref name=\"instructions2\">{{cite book|year=1994|title=Hotel Mario instruction book|publisher=Philips Interactive Media|id=PP0260 GA|page=3}}</ref><ref name=\"EG\">{{cite web|first=Dan|last=Whitehead|title=The History of Mario|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/the-history-of-mario-article?page=3|date=March 9, 2007|publisher=[[Eurogamer]]|accessdate=June 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==== Ubisoft Milan ====\n\n''[[Mario + Rabbids Kingdom Battle]]'' is a [[turn-based]] [[Tactical role-playing game|tactical role-playing video game]] developed by [[Ubisoft Milan]] (Ubisoft's Italian studio division) for the Nintendo Switch. The game is a [[crossover (fiction)|crossover]] with Ubisoft's ''[[Raving Rabbids]]'' franchise, and features both singleplayer and [[local cooperative|cooperative]] multiplayer gameplay. The game's story sees players controlling Mario, his friends, and a group of Rabbids dressed as them, dealing with the aftermath of a sudden invasion by a group of Rabbids, who have accidentally misused a powerful invention that has brought chaos to the Mushroom Kingdom. Shigeru Miyamoto was initially impressed by the prototype of the game, that was presented to him by creative director Davide Soliani in 2014, which later caused Nintendo to greenlight the game for a Nintendo Switch release. It was released in Europe and North America on August 29, 2017, and was met with generally favorable reception from critics, who praised its gameplay, depth, and graphics.\n\n==== Others ====\n[[Electronic Arts]] developed and released ''[[NBA Street V3]]'' and ''[[SSX on Tour]]'' in 2005, both of which included Mario, Luigi, and Peach as playable characters in the GameCube versions.\n\n== Other media ==\n{{Main|List of non-video game media featuring Mario}}\nThe ''Mario'' franchise includes many comics, manga and TV series based on the games. Most were released in the late 1980s to early 1990s, and have since become obscure. Mario, Luigi and Peach have made cameo appearances in two sports games, including the [[GameCube]] version of ''[[NBA Street V3]]''. The series launched two films, the [[anime]] ''[[Super Mario Bros.: Peach-Hime Kyushutsu Dai Sakusen]]'' released in 1986 and the [[live action]] film ''[[Super Mario Bros. (film)|Super Mario Bros.]]'' in 1993. The latter lost a large amount of money at the box office and was widely considered to be a [[Box office bomb|failure]].<ref name=\"Super Mario Bros. 1993\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=supermariobros.htm |title=Super Mario Bros. (1993) |publisher=Boxofficemojo.com |date=June 29, 1993 |accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Television ===\n{{further|List of Mario television series}}\n''[[Saturday Supercade]]'' was an [[Cartoon series|animated television series]] produced for [[Saturday morning cartoon|Saturday mornings]] by [[Ruby-Spears Productions]]. It ran for two seasons on [[CBS]], beginning in 1983. Each episode comprised several shorter segments featuring [[video game]] characters from the [[Golden age of arcade video games|Golden Age of Arcade Games]]. [[Donkey Kong (character)|Donkey Kong]], [[Mario]] and [[Pauline (Mario)|Pauline]] (from the ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'' arcade game) were featured in the show.\n\n''[[The Super Mario Bros. Super Show!]]'' is the first American TV series based on the ''Mario'' NES games. It was broadcast in [[Broadcast syndication|syndication]] from September 4 to December 1, 1989. The show was produced by [[DIC Entertainment]] and was distributed for syndicated television by [[Viacom Enterprises]] (full rights have since reverted to DiC through [[Nintendo]]).\n\n''[[King Koopa's Kool Kartoons]]'' was a [[live action]] children's [[Television program|television show]] broadcast in [[Southern California]] during the holiday season of 1989-90. The show starred King Koopa (also known as [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]]), the main antagonist of the ''Mario'' series. The 30-minute program was originally broadcast during the after-school afternoon time-slots on [[Los Angeles]]-based [[KTTV|KTTV Fox 11]].\n\n''[[The Adventures of Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' is the second TV series based on the ''Mario'' NES games. It aired on [[NBC]] from September 8 to December 1, 1990. Based on the ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' video game, the cartoon shows Mario, Luigi, Princess Toadstool and Toad fighting against Bowser and his [[Koopalings]], who went by different names on the show (Hip, Hop, Kooky, Kootie Pie, Big Mouth, Cheatsy, and Bully). Like the previous Mario cartoon series, the animation was done by Sei Young Animation Co. Ltd, however this show was co-produced by Reteitalia S.P.A., hence the slight differences in character design.\n\n''[[Super Mario Challenge]]'' was a show which aired on [[The Children's Channel]]. It ran from 1990 to 1991 and aired at 4:30&nbsp;p.m. every weekday. The presenter, [[John Lenahan]], was a lookalike of [[Mario]], and dressed in his clothes. Two guest players had to do tasks, all of which involved playing the ''Mario'' video games ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'', ''[[Super Mario Bros. 2]]'' and, after its release in 1991, ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]''. Rounds included challenges to see which player could complete a level in the fastest time and who could collect the most gold coins on a certain level.\n\n''[[Super Mario World (TV series)|Super Mario World]]'' is an [[Cartoon series|animated television series]] based on the [[Super Mario World|SNES video game of the same name]]. It is the third and currently last [[Saturday morning cartoons|Saturday morning cartoon]] based on the ''Mario'' series. The show was originally aired on Saturday mornings on [[NBC]] in the 1991\u201392 season. It was featured in a half-hour time slot with a shortened version of ''[[Captain N: The Game Master]]''. Episodes of ''Super Mario World'' were later shown as part of the [[Television syndication|syndication]] package ''Captain N and the Video Game Masters''. Afterwards, the series was split from ''Captain N'' altogether and shown in time-compressed reruns on ''Mario All-Stars''.\n\n=== Anime ===\n''[[Super Mario Bros.: Peach-Hime Kyushutsu Dai Sakusen!]]'' is a [[Japan]]ese [[anime]] film released on July 20, 1986. Directed by Masami Hata and produced by Masakatsu Suzuki and Tsunemasa Hatano, it stars [[Mario]] and [[Luigi]], who get stuck in a [[Nintendo Entertainment System|Famicom]] [[video game]], in which they must save [[Princess Peach]] from [[Bowser (character)|Koopa]]. A [[manga]] adaptation of the film was published in Japan around the same time as the film's release.\n\nA series of three [[Original video animation|OVA]] episodes titled ''[[Amada Anime Series: Super Mario Bros.]]'', based on ''[[Momotar\u014d]]'', ''[[Issun-b\u014dshi]]'' and ''[[Snow White]]'', were released on August 3, 1989. These generally featured Mario as the hero, Peach as the damsel and Bowser as the villain, with other Mario characters playing supporting roles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5835648/there-were-worse-mario-cartoons-than-the-american-one/gallery/1|title=There Were Worse Mario Cartoons Than the American One|publisher=Kotaku|first=Luke|last=Plunkett|date=August 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Films ===\n{{Main|Super Mario Bros. (film)}}\n''Super Mario Bros.'' is an [[United States|American]] 1993 [[Adventure film|adventure]] [[Family film|family]] [[Comedy film|comedy]] loosely based on the video game of the same name. The film follows the exploits of [[Mario]] ([[Bob Hoskins]]) and [[Luigi]] ([[John Leguizamo]]) in a [[dystopia]] ruled by [[Bowser (character)|King Koopa]] ([[Dennis Hopper]]). It was the first live-action [[List of films based on video games|major motion picture to be based on a video game]]. The film's plot features Mario and Luigi as the main protagonists, Mario leading the team with Luigi developing a romance with [[Princess Daisy]].\n\nThe film grossed $21 million on a $48 million budget.<ref name=\"Super Mario Bros. 1993\" /> On the television show ''[[At the Movies (1986 TV program)|Siskel & Ebert]]'', the film received two [[thumbs down]] and was written off as a [[box office flop]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bventertainment.go.com/tv/buenavista/ebertandroeper/index2.html?sec=6&subsec=Super+Mario+Bros. |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mr94yVaA?url=http://bventertainment.go.com/tv/buenavista/ebertandroeper/index2.html?sec=6 |archivedate=January 17, 2010 |title=Siskel & Ebert |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBowser and the Super Mushroom had a cameo in the 2012 Disney computer-animated film ''[[Wreck-It Ralph]]''. Mario was mentioned but not seen in the film.\n\n====Upcoming animated film====\n{{anchor|2022 film}}\nIn December 2014, emails leaked through [[Sony Pictures hack|a hack]] revealed that [[Sony Pictures]] was in negotiations with Nintendo to create a fully-animated film based on the ''Mario'' franchise.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vary|first1=Adam|title=Sony Pictures Lands \"Mario Bros.\" Movie Rights From Nintendo, Leaked Emails Show|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/adambvary/sony-nintendo-mario-bros-movie#.duwkpjZgV|accessdate=December 11, 2014|publisher=[[BuzzFeed]]|date=December 11, 2014}}</ref> This deal did not come through,<ref>{{cite web |last=Osborn |first=Alex |title=Nintendo Officially Partnering With Illumination on Mario Movie |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/02/01/nintendo-officially-partnering-with-illumination-on-mario-movie |website=IGN |accessdate=December 17, 2018 |date=January 31, 2018}}</ref> as in November 2017, it was reported that Nintendo would instead be teaming up with [[Universal Pictures]] and [[Illumination (animation company)|Illumination]] to make the animated ''Mario'' film.<ref name=\"IEMarioMovie1\">{{cite news|last1=Pallotta|first1=Frank|title='Super Mario Bros.' animated movie in the works at Illumination Entertainment|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/11/14/media/super-mario-bros-movie/index.html|accessdate=November 14, 2017|work=CNNMoney|date=November 14, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"IEMarioMovie2\">{{cite news|title='Super Mario Bros.' Movie in the Works at Illumination Entertainment|url=https://collider.com/super-mario-movie-nintendo-illumination-entertainment/|accessdate=November 14, 2017|work=Collider|date=November 14, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"IEMarioMovie3\">{{cite news|title=Super Mario Movie in the Works From Despicable Me Studio|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/mario-movie/|accessdate=November 14, 2017|work=Slashfilm|date=November 14, 2017}}</ref> Nintendo President [[Tatsumi Kimishima]] stated in January 2018 that a deal had not been finalized, but that an announcement would come soon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lrmonline.com/news/super-mario-bros-movie-deal-not-finalized-movie-could-come-in-2020/|title=Super Mario Bros. Movie Deal Not Finalized, Movie Could Come In 2020|website=Screen Rant|last=Medina|first=Joseph Jammer|date=January 9, 2018|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> \n\nBy the end of January 2020, Nintendo affirmed that the animated film with Illumination would be moving forward, with [[Shigeru Miyamoto]] and [[Chris Meledandri]] co-producing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/mario-movie-be-produced-by-nintendos-shigeru-miyamoto-illumination-1080822|title='Mario' Movie to Be Produced by Nintendo and Illumination|website=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Blair|first=Gavin J.|date=January 31, 2018|accessdate=January 31, 2018}}</ref> Miyamoto stated in 2020 that the idea of doing a film had come from bringing their older games to the [[Virtual Console]] and other services; such transitions took time for the company, and Miyamoto recognized that \"our content business would be able to develop even further if we were able to combine our long-beloved software with that of video assets, and utilize them together for extended periods.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.usgamer.net/articles/miyamoto-explains-how-the-virtual-console-convinced-nintendo-to-make-a-new-mario-movie | title = The Virtual Console Convinced Nintendo to Make a New Mario Movie | first = Mathew | last = Olsen | date = February 3, 2020 | accessdate = February 3, 2020 | work = [[USGamer]] }}</ref> Miyamoto knew that the process of making a film was far different from that of making a video game, and wanted a film expert to lead the effort. In Nintendo's work with [[Universal Parks & Resorts]] to create Mario-based attractions, Miyamoto had met Meledandri, and they had several discussions. Miyamoto found Meledandri's creative process similar to his own, and decided he would be the proper lead for a Mario film. They had started more earnest discussions of the film as early as 2016, knowing that if they realized it wasn't working that they could easily walk away. However, by the time of the official announcement, Miyamoto said that they have good discussions over the screenplay and feels good progress to a proper film.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://venturebeat.com/2018/02/09/nintendos-miyamoto-explains-how-illumination-won-mario-movie-rights/ | title = Nintendo's Miyamoto explains how Illumination won Mario movie rights | first = Mike | last = Minotti | date = January 9, 2018 | accessdate = January 9, 2018 | work = [[VentureBeat]] }}</ref> Meledandri stated that the film was a \"priority\" for Illumination and that it will most likely come out in 2022. He added that Miyamoto will be \"front and center\" with creating the movie.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/super-mario-animated-movie-release-date/|title=Super Mario Bros. Animated Movie Is A Priority; May Arrive In 2022|website=Screen Rant|last=Schaefer|first=Sandy|date=November 6, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref> Shuntaro Furukawa, Nintendo's president, announced that production for the film has begun as of February 1, 2019, with the film being set to be released in 2022.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2019/190201_2e.pdf |title=Corporate Management Policy Briefing| date = February 1, 2019 | accessdate = December 14, 2019 }}</ref> In January 2020, Furukawa provided an update stating that the film is \"moving along smoothly\" with the film aiming for release in 2022. Furukawa also stated that Nintendo would own the rights to the film, and that both Nintendo and Universal would fund its production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2020/01/illuminations_mario_movie_is_moving_along_smoothly_aiming_for_2022_release|title=Illumination's Mario Movie Is \"Moving Along Smoothly\", Aiming For 2022 Release|website=Nintendo Life|last=Craddock|first=Ryan|date=January 30, 2020|accessdate=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Comics and manga ===\n{{nihongo foot|''[[Super Mario-kun]]''|\u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30de\u30ea\u30aa\u304f\u3093|''S\u016bp\u0101 Mario-kun''|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[manga]] series written by {{nihongo foot|Yukio Sawada|\u6ca2\u7530\u30e6\u30ad\u30aa|''Sawada Yukio''|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} and published by Shogakukan. It is serialized in [[CoroCoro Comic]]. It contains many characters and scenarios from ''Mario'' games, such as ''[[Super Mario World]]'' and ''[[Paper Mario]]''. Having just hit its 41st volume, ''Super Mario-kun'' is the longest-running ''Mario'' series manga to date. It continues to release new volumes to date. Another consistent manga series based on various Mario games is a work written and drawn by  {{nihongo foot|[[Hiroshi Takase]]|\u5d69\u702c\u3072\u308d\u3057|''Takase Hiroshi''|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} and published by PikkaPika Comics that is, somewhat confusedly, also called {{nihongo foot|''Super Mario-kun''|\u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30de\u30ea\u30aa\u304f\u3093|''S\u016bp\u0101 Mario-kun''|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}}. It is currently at five volumes and stopped due to the author's death in 2006.\n\nThe ''[[Nintendo Comics System]]'' was a series of [[comic book]]s published by [[Valiant Comics]] in 1990 and 1991. It was part of a licensing deal with [[Nintendo]], featuring characters from their [[video game]]s and the [[cartoon]]s based on them. Valiant's ''Super Mario Bros.'' comic books were based on the three main ''Mario'' games on the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]], as well as ''[[Super Mario Bros. (TV)|The Super Mario Bros. Super Show]]''. The ''Mario'' line was renewed for 1991 with two different books\u2014''Super Mario Bros.'' and ''Adventures of the Super Mario Bros.''\n\nThe ''[[Nintendo Adventure Book]]'' series was published from 1991 to 1992 by Archway books, and Mammoth books in the [[United Kingdom]]. There are twelve in all. They are formatted like the popular [[Choose Your Own Adventure]] books, where the reader makes decisions that change the outcome of the story. Ten of the books are about the [[Mario Bros.]]' adventures in the [[Mushroom Kingdom]] and are based primarily on the [[Valiant Comics|Valiant comics]] published for the [[Nintendo Comics System]] imprint.\n\n{{nihongo foot|''[[Super Mario Adventures]]''|SUPER MARIO ADVENTURES \u30de\u30ea\u30aa\u306e\u5927\u5192\u967a|''Mario no daib\u014dken''|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha|<ref>\"[https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0006QBMK0 Super Mario Adventures Official Nintendo Comic Book (Paperback)].\" ''Amazon.com''. Retrieved on November 19, 2008.</ref>}} is an [[anthology]] of comics, drawn in a Japanese [[manga]] style, that ran in ''[[Nintendo Power]]'' magazine throughout 1992, featuring the characters from Nintendo's ''[[Mario]]'' series and based loosely on ''[[Super Mario World]]''.\n\nImmediately following the end of ''Super Mario Adventures'', ''Nintendo Power'' concluded the epic with a ten-page story based on ''[[Super Mario Land 2: 6 Golden Coins]]'' titled ''[[Super Mario Adventures#Mario vs. Wario|Mario VS Wario]]'', which ran in their January 1993 issue and was later reprinted in the graphic novel.\n\nAt one point, [[Archie Comics]] made a pitch to Nintendo for a new Mario comic similar to its ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog (comics)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' series, but it was turned down.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gonintendo.com/stories/245998-archie-pitched-nintendo-a-super-mario-comic-but-it-was-shot-down|title=Archie Pitched Nintendo a Super Mario Comic, But It Was Shot Down|date=September 12, 2015|website=GoNintendo|publisher=rawmeatcowboy|accessdate=September 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAn encyclopedia based on ''Super Mario Bros.'' was released in Japan in October 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nintendo releasing 256-page Mario encyclopedia in Japan next month|url=http://nintendoeverything.com/nintendo-releasing-256-page-mario-encyclopedia-in-japan-next-month/|website=Nintendo Everything|accessdate=September 9, 2015}}</ref> In February 2017, Nintendo announced that the encyclopedia would launch in North America and Europe in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Super Mario Bros. Encyclopedia coming to North America and Europe in June|url=http://nintendoeverything.com/super-mario-bros-encyclopedia-coming-to-north-america-and-europe-in-june/|website=Nintendo Everything|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAnother encyclopedia based on the series up until ''Super Mario Maker'' was published by Dark Horse Publishing on October 23, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2018/02/marios_very_own_encylopedia_will_leap_onto_book_shelves_this_october|title=Mario's Very Own Encyclopedia Will Leap Onto Book Shelves This October|website=Nintendo Life|accessdate=February 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Merchandise ===\n[[File:Nintendo DS Mario Edition.jpg|thumb|250px|right|A ''Mario''-themed [[Nintendo DS Lite]].]]\nMario has appeared on lunch boxes, T-shirts, jeans,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/LEVIS/status/1234536816071471104|title=\ud83d\udc56x \ud83c\udf44. Coming soon.|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> magazines, commercials (notably, in a [[Got Milk?]] commercial),<ref>Weiss, Jodi & Kahn, Russell (2004). In ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=Mp0LRxu0ibsC&pg=PA25&dq=%22got+milk%22+mario&ei=-_b0Sr7sG5PyNJ3B1YoF#v=onepage&q=%22got%20milk%22%20mario&f=false 145 Things to Be When You Grow Up]''. Princeton Review Publishing. p. 25. {{ISBN|0-375-76369-4}}. Google Book Search. Retrieved on November 6, 2009.</ref> in candy form, on shampoo bottles, cereal, badges, and as a [https://web.archive.org/web/20141025050156/http://www.tvgome.com/en/15-super-mario plush toy].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamecubicle.com/features-mario-nintendo_shining_star.htm|title=Nintendo's Shining Star: The History of Mario|publisher=GameCubicle|accessdate=August 23, 2008}}</ref> In 1992, [[Gottlieb]] created a Super Mario themed [[pinball]] machine.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Gottlieb's Super Mario Bros. Pin|journal=Cash Box|date=May 25, 1992|volume=55|issue=39|page=25|accessdate=August 20, 2017|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Cash-Box/90s/1992/CB-1992-05-23.pdf}}</ref> A [[Monopoly (game)|Monopoly]] board game based on the ''Mario'' franchise has been confirmed by the website USAopoly.<ref>{{cite web|author=USAopoly|title=MONOPOLY\u00ae: Super Mario Bros.\u2122 Collector's Edition|url=http://usaopoly.com/games/monopoly-super-mario-bros-collectors-edition|website=USAopoly|access-date=May 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171219170204/http://usaopoly.com/games/monopoly-super-mario-bros-collectors-edition|archive-date=December 19, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> In April 2017, a board game developed by USAopoly titled ''Super Mario Level Up!'' has been announced for release.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Super Mario game REVEALED \u2013 but it's NOT for Nintendo Switch|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/tech/gaming/605999/Super-Mario-Level-Up-Board-Game-Nintendo-Switch|accessdate=April 16, 2017}}</ref> In early 2017, a ''Super Mario''-themed pop-up bar known as \"The Cherry Blossom Pub\" opened up in [[Mockingbird Hill]], [[Washington, D.C.]]. The interior of one side of the bar has been transformed into \"a Nintendo dream world\". ''The Washington'' reported in an interview with Derek Brown, the bar's owner, that the bar had become so popular that there was a two-hour long line outside the bar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonian.com/2017/03/21/you-cant-bribe-your-way-into-the-cherry-blossom-bar/|title=You Can't Bribe Your Way Into The Cherry Blossom Bar|date=March 21, 2017|website=washingtonian.com}}</ref> The cocktails in the bar cost $13 and are all Mario-themed. On the menu there's the \u201cIt\u2019s a Me, A-Mario\u201d (sweet vermouth, Don Ciccio & Figli Carcafio, Aperitivo, and spicy ginger ale), \u201cWhat Doesn\u2019t Kill You Makes You Smaller\u201d (vodka, mandarin orange, pomelo and apricot soda) and the \u201cKing Koopa Cup\u201d (Two James Johnny Smoking Gun whiskey, \u201cpopcorn\u201d tea ginger, and lemon).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelandleisure.com/food-drink/bars-clubs/super-mario-cherry-blossom-bar-dc|title=This Super Mario-themed Bar Has Nintendo Fans Lining up for Hours|last=https://plus.google.com/+travelandleisure/posts|website=travelandleisure.com}}</ref> Another Monopoly-inspired board game called ''Monopoly Gamer'' was released in August 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hasbro and Nintendo introduce MONOPOLY GAMER, a new way to play MONOPOLY|url=http://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/hasbro-and-nintendo-introduce-monopoly-gamer|website=Nintendo|date=June 28, 2017|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref> In addition, Monopoly Gamer adds a ''Mario Kart'' version with courses from ''Mario Kart 8'' serving as properties. Mario-themed [[Lego]] sets are set to be released in August 2020, these sets feature a Mario figure that interacts with certain elements in the environment.<ref>https://www.lego.com/en-us/campaigns/supermario?icmp=HP-SHSB-Standard-Leaf_Sidekick_Standard_Supermario_HP-TH-MAR-M45K3UAV7S</ref>\n\n=== Concerts and performances ===\nThe ''Super Mario Bros.'' theme has been featured in many concerts, including \"PLAY! Chicago\",<ref name=\"m4g\">{{cite web |title=Super Mario Bros. and Zelda composer Koji Kondo to attend PLAY! Chicago |url=http://www.music4games.net/News_Display.aspx?id=184 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225004700/http://www.music4games.net/News_Display.aspx?id=184 |archivedate=February 25, 2009 |publisher=Music 4 Games |accessdate=February 13, 2009 |date=April 14, 2006}}</ref> the [[Columbus Symphony Orchestra]],<ref name=\"columbus\">{{cite web |title=Symphony piles up points with video-game concert |url=http://www.columbusdispatch.com/live/content/life/stories/2007/04/26/gamer_concert.html |publisher=[[The Columbus Dispatch]] |accessdate=February 13, 2009 |date=April 27, 2007}}{{dead link|date=April 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> the Mario & Zelda Big Band Live,{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} Play! A Video Game Symphony,<ref name=\"play\">{{cite web |title=I hear a video game symphony |url=http://www.popjournalism.ca/pop/news/2006/00266playconcert.shtml |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215021437/http://www.popjournalism.ca/pop/news/2006/00266playconcert.shtml |archivedate=December 15, 2007 |publisher=Pop Journalism |accessdate=February 13, 2009 |date=September 27, 2006}}</ref> and others.\n\nThe [[Video Games Live]] concert featured the theme performed by Koji Kondo.<ref name=\"interview\">{{cite web |title=Super Mario Bros. Composer Koji Kondo Interview |url=http://www.1up.com/features/mario-maestro |publisher=[[1UP.com]] |accessdate=February 16, 2009 |date=October 19, 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{See also|Super Mario#Reception}}\n\nThe ''Mario'' series has received a very positive reception from critics and audiences. A 1996 article in ''[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]'' declared that \"The evolution of the ''Mario'' series led the rest of gaming by the hand, blazing a trail, and teaching lessons in game mechanics, structure, and sheer playability to any who would study its secrets\".\n\n== Setting ==\nMost of Mario's games are set in the fictional '''[[Mushroom Kingdom]]''', but there are other settings which explore more details of the Mario Universe.\n\nThe places introduced in the ''Mario'' franchise are:\n\n* '''[[Mushroom Kingdom]]''', the central kingdom of the universe and the setting of most Mario games. It is usually ruled by '''[[Princess Peach]]'''. The capital of the kingdom is '''Toad Town''', a city that lies below Peach's Castle.\n* '''Subcon''' is the dreamworld that is the setting of [[Super Mario Bros. 2]].\n* '''Bowser's Kingdom''', the kingdom ruled by '''[[Bowser (character)|Bowser]]''', the main antagonist of the series. The kingdom has appeared in several games under different names, and often appears as the final level of the game which it is featured in. The first time this kingdom appears under the name Bowser's Kingdom is in ''[[Super Mario Odyssey]]''.\n* '''Sprixie Kingdom''', introduced in ''[[Super Mario 3D World]]'', is home to fairy-like creatures called '''Sprixies'''. It is composed of 8 islands with different themes, with each island being ruled by a Sprixie. It is the main setting of ''[[Super Mario 3D World]]''.\n* '''Kingdom of Bask''', introduced in ''[[Mario Tennis Aces]]'', the Kingdom of Bask was ruled by '''King Bask''' until '''Lucien''', the main antagonist of the game, attacked it, forcing King Bask to split his power into Power Stones. It is the main setting of ''Mario Tennis Aces''.\n* '''Sarasaland''', introduced in ''[[Super Mario Land]]'', is ruled by '''[[Princess Daisy]]''', and is divided into four kingdoms: '''Birabuto Kingdom''' (based on [[Ancient Egypt]]), '''Muda Kingdom''' (based on Mu and [[Bermuda]]), '''Easton Kingdom''' (based on Easter Island) and '''Chai Kingdom''' (based on [[Ancient China]]). It is the main setting of ''Super Mario Land''.\n* '''Beanbean Kingdom''', introduced in ''[[Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga]]'', is governed by '''Queen Bean''' and his son '''Prince Peasley'''. The capital is '''Beanbean Castle Town''', and the kingdom is known to have good relations with the '''[[Mushroom Kingdom]]''', in addition to bordering it. The regions are named after laughter onomatopoeias. Just like the Mushroom Kingdom is mushroom themed, the Beanbean Kingdom is bean themed. It is also home to the famous '''Chuckola Cola'''. The forest where it is produced is named '''Chucklehuck Woods'''. It is the main setting of ''Mario & Luigi: Superstar Saga''.\n* '''Pi'illo Island''', formerly known as '''Pi'illo Kingdom''', is introduced in ''[[Mario & Luigi: Dream Team]]'', and is an island that was ruled by '''Prince Dreambert''' until he and the other Pi'illos were imprisoned by '''Antasma''', the main antagonist of the game. At some undefined time in the past, the island was acquired by '''Dr. Snoozemore'''. At the end of the game, with all the Pi'illos released, the island is once again governed by '''Prince Dreambert.''' It is the main setting of ''Mario & Luigi: Dream Team''.\n* '''Isle Delfino''', introduced in ''[[Super Mario Sunshine]]'', is a [[dolphin]]-shaped paradise island somewhere outside the [[Mushroom Kingdom]]. It's the setting for ''[[Super Mario Sunshine]]''. The capital is '''Delfino Plaza'''.\n* ''[[Super Mario Odyssey]]'' introduces a variety of new locations such as the '''Cap Kingdom''', '''Cascade Kingdom''', '''Metro Kingdom''' and '''Luncheon Kingdom''', just to name a few.\n\n== Impact and legacy ==\nMario has been featured in 256 games of various genres (including sports, puzzle, party, racing and first-person shooter), and the ''Mario'' franchise is the [[List of best-selling video game franchises|best-selling video game franchise of all time]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/releases/mmnr/Super_Mario_Galaxy/index.html |title=Italian Plumber More Memorable Than Harper, Dion |accessdate=April 4, 2010 |date=December 13, 2007 |publisher=CNW Group |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090911224500/http://www.newswire.ca/en/releases/mmnr/Super_Mario_Galaxy/index.html |url-status=dead |archivedate=September 11, 2009 }}</ref> At least 31 different ''Mario'' games have sold more than a million copies each since 1995. This includes the core ''[[Super Mario (series)|Super Mario]]'' series, which alone has sold over 262 million units worldwide,<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110531005315/en/Nintendo-DS-Lite-Suggested-Retail-Price-Drops |title= Nintendo DS Lite Suggested Retail Price Drops to $99.99 and Mario Games Go Red |date=May 31, 2011 |publisher=[[Business Wire]] |accessdate=May 31, 2011}}</ref> as well as the ''[[Mario Kart]]'' series which sold 78 million units,<ref name=\"mariokart\">*12 million in North America as of November 15, 2005: {{cite press release|url=http://www.nintendo.ca/cgi-bin/usersite/display_info.cgi?lang=en&pageNum=9&id=7279167 |title=Mario Kart DS launches with Wi-Fi gaming service |date=November 15, 2005 |accessdate=March 21, 2009 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090111064204/http://www.nintendo.ca/cgi-bin/usersite/display_info.cgi?lang=en&pageNum=9&id=7279167 |archivedate=January 11, 2009 }}\n* {{cite web|title=Japan Platinum Game Chart |url=http://www.the-magicbox.com/Chart-JPPlatinum.shtml |publisher=The Magic Box |accessdate=March 15, 2012 }}\n** ''[[Super Mario Kart]]'': 3.82 million\n** ''[[Mario Kart 64]]'': 2.24 million\n* ''[[Mario Kart: Double Dash!!]]'' sales in Japan as of January 2, 2005: 802,217 ({{cite web|title=2004 Top 100 Best Selling Japanese Console Games |url=http://www.the-magicbox.com/Chart-BestSell2004.shtml |publisher=The Magic Box |accessdate=March 15, 2012 |date=January 2, 2005 }})\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2012/120127e.pdf#page=7 |title=Financial Results Briefing for the Nine-Month Period Ended December 2011 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |date=January 27, 2012 |format=PDF |accessdate=February 8, 2012 |page=6 }}:\n** ''[[Mario Kart DS]]'': 22.3 million\n** ''[[Mario Kart 7]]'': 4.54 million\n** ''[[Mario Kart Wii]]'': 31.91 million</ref> the ''[[Mario Party]]'' series which sold over 32 million units,<ref name=\"marioparty\">{{cite web|title=Mario Party 9 for Wii Lets You Party Like You've Never Partied Before|url=https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/KoFSBbHMQS8jbGp-gxCmymMOiMg1fIeg|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|accessdate=March 15, 2012|date=March 12, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'' which sold over [[List of highest-grossing arcade games|125,000 arcade machines]]<ref>*Japan: 65,000 ({{cite book|first1=Brian | last1=Ashcraft | first2=Jean | last2= Snow|title=Arcade Mania: The Turbo-charged World of Japan's Game Centers|year=2008|publisher=[[Kodansha|Kodansha International]]|location=Tokyo|isbn=978-4-7700-3078-8|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wX8kAQAAIAAJ&dq=\"sixty-five+thousand\"|edition=1st |accessdate=February 12, 2012|quote=Jumpman hopped over barrels, climbed ladders, and jumped from suspended platform to suspended platform as he tried to rescue a damsel from his pissed-off pet gorilla. The game was a smash, and sixty-five thousand cabinets were sold in Japan, propping up the then-struggling Nintendo and laying the groundwork for Nintendo and ''Donkey Kong'' creator Shigeru Miyamoto to dominate gaming throughout the 1980s and beyond.}})\n* United States: 60,000 ({{Cite book|author=Steven L. Kent|year=2001|title=The Ultimate History of Video Games: The Story behind the Craze that Touched Our Lives and Changed the World|publisher=[[Prima Games|Prima]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C2MH05ogU9oC|accessdate=April 9, 2011|page=352|quote=With more than 60,000 units sold in the United States, Donkey Kong was Nintendo's biggest arcade hit. ... Nintendo released Donkey Kong Junior in 1982 and sold only 30,000 machines, 20,000 Popeye machines (also 1982), and a mere 5000 copies of Donkey J (1983).|isbn=978-0-7615-3643-7}})</ref>\nand six million [[Coleco]] [[ROM cartridge|cartridges]],<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=David Sheff|last=Sheff|first=David|year=1999|title=Game Over: Press Start to Continue: The Maturing of Mario|title-link=Game Over (book)|page=121|publisher=Wilton, Connecticut: GamePress}}: {{quote|\"And we received from Coleco an agreement that they would pay us three percent of the net sales price [of all the \"Donkey Kong\" cartridges Coleco sold].\" It turned out to be an impressive number of cartridges, 6 million, which translated into $4.6 million.}}</ref> and ''[[Mario Bros.]]'' which sold 1.72 million [[Nintendo Entertainment System|Famicom]] cartridges.<ref name=\"famicommini\">{{cite web |title=Nintendojofr|url=http://www.nintendojofr.com/redaction/editoriaux/?id=aVAd |date=September 26, 2006 |publisher=Nintendojo |accessdate=October 9, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080730022258/http://www.nintendojofr.com/redaction/editoriaux/?id=aVAd |archivedate = July 30, 2008}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal bar|Video games|Japan}}\n{{Wikipedia books|Mario franchise video games}}\n* [[List of Luigi video games|List of ''Luigi'' video games]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links | wikt=no | c=Category:Mario_(video game series) | v=no | q=Mario (franchise) | s=no | b=no | n =no | display=''Mario (franchise)''}}\n*[http://mario.nintendo.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Mario series}}\n{{Main franchises by Nintendo}}\n{{Portal bar|Japan|Video games|1980s|1990s}}\n\n[[Category:Mario| ]]\n[[Category:Mario video games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo franchises]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises introduced in 1981]]\n[[Category:Video games produced by Shigeru Miyamoto]]\n[[Category:Video games adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Video games adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Video games adapted into television programs]]\n[[Category:Action-adventure games]]\n", "name_user": "Sergiogriffiths", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mario_(franchise)"}
{"title_page": "Childs Play (website)", "text_new": "{{Infobox website\n|name            = Childs Play\n|logo            =\n|logocaption     =\n|screenshot      = Childs_Play_censored_screenshot.jpg\n|collapsible     =\n|caption         =\n|url             = <!-- Please do not add a link to the site, as it fails Wikipedia's guidelines on external links. -->\n|type            = [[Child pornography]] [[File sharing|sharing]]\n|language        = [[English language|English]]\n|num_users       =\n|content_license =\n|programming language =\n|owner           =\n|author          =\n|launch_date     = April 2016\n|alexa           =\n|revenue         =\n|current_status  = Offline (as of September 2017)\n|footnotes       =\n}}\n\n'''Childs Play''' was a [[darknet]] [[child abuse]] website that operated from April 2016 to September 2017, which at its peak was the largest of its class.<ref name=vg>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vg.no/spesial/2017/undercover-darkweb/?lang=en |title=VG exposed the largest child sexual abuse forum. It was run by the police. |last=H\u00e5kon F. H\u00f8ydal, Einar Otto Stangvik and Natalie Rem\u00f8e Hansen |work=[[VG Nett]] |access-date=2018-01-23 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180110132111/https://www.vg.no/spesial/2017/undercover-darkweb/?lang=en |archive-date=2018-01-10 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=toronto>{{Cite news |url=http://torontosun.com/2017/10/12/canadian-man-was-king-of-kiddie-porn/wcm/df1a5300-ce6d-43b8-8178-4007093a9523 |title=Canadian man was king of kiddie porn |last=Brad Hunter |date=2017-10-12 |work=Toronto Sun |access-date=2018-01-23 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.deepdotweb.com/2017/10/16/task-force-argos-operated-darknet-child-abuse-forum-11-months/ |title=Task Force Argos Operated a Darknet Child Abuse Forum for 11 Months |last=C. Aliens |date=October 16, 2017 |work=[[DeepDotWeb]] |access-date=2018-01-23 |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124005729/https://www.deepdotweb.com/2017/10/16/task-force-argos-operated-darknet-child-abuse-forum-11-months/ |archive-date=January 24, 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=guardian>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2017/oct/07/australian-police-sting-brings-down-paedophile-forum-on-dark-web |title=Australian police sting brings down paedophile forum on dark web |last=Knaus |first=Christopher |date=2017-10-07 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=2018-01-25 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/queensland-police-behind-worlds-largest-child-porn-forum-20171007-gywcps.html |title=Queensland police take over world's largest child porn forum in sting operation |last=McInnes |first=William |date=2017-10-08 |work=[[Brisbane Times]] |access-date=2018-01-25 |language=en}}</ref> The site was concealed by being run as a hidden service on the [[Tor (anonymity network)|Tor network]]. After running the site for the first six months, owner Benjamin Faulkner of [[Guelph]], Ontario, Canada was captured by the [[United States Department of Homeland Security]]. For the remaining eleven months the website was owned and operated by the Australian [[Queensland Police Service]]'s [[Task Force Argos]], as part of ''Operation Artemis''.\n\n== Reactions ==\n\nThe website was run by Australian police for 11 months, and involved impersonation of the forum owner ''WarHead'' (Faulkner's alias) which required police to regularly post child abuse images, in order to convince users that the site was not compromised.<ref name=vg/><ref name=guardian/><ref name=noreact>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vg.no/nyheter/utenriks/kampen-mot-overgrepsfiler/unicef-clear-violation-of-un-children-s-convention/a/24157545/ |title=UNICEF: \u2013 Clear violation of UN children\u2019s convention |last=Maria Knoph Vigsn\u00e6s, H\u00e5kon F. H\u00f8ydal, Einar Otto Stangvik, and Natalie Rem\u00f8e Hansen |work=[[Verdens Gang]] |access-date=2018-01-23 |language=en}}</ref> Ivar Stokkereit, a legal adviser to the United Nations Children's Fund ([[UNICEF]]) in Norway, stated this was \"a clear violation of the UN [[Convention on the Rights of the Child]], even though the police\u2019s intention is to prevent new offenses in the long run\". [[Amnesty International]] also criticized the actions as \"unacceptable under human rights law\". [[ECPAT]] (End Child Prostitution, Child Pornography and Trafficking of Children for Sexual Purposes) supported the proactive approach taken by Task Force Argos.<ref name=noreact/>\n\n[[James Sheptycki]], professor in criminology at [[York University]], criticized the transfer of the website from its original server in Europe to Australia as \"[[Forum shopping|jurisdiction shopping]]\", being done due to the favourable legal framework in Australia that would allow the website to continue running in this way.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vg.no/nyheter/utenriks/undercover-darkweb/police-acting-as-judges/a/24162582/ |title=\u2013 Police acting as judges |last=H\u00e5kon F. H\u00f8ydal, Einar Otto Stangvik, and Natalie Rem\u00f8e Hansen  |work=[[Verdens Gang]] |access-date=2018-01-23 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Convictions ==\n\nThe capture of the site, and its subsequent use to gather information, has led to arrests and convictions:\n\n* Benjamin Faulkner's associate, Patrick Falte, was captured together with Faulkner when they met in Virginia in October 2016 two days after they had raped a four-year-old girl. Falte had been an administrator on ''The GiftBox Exchange'', another darknet child exploitation site that was shut down in November 2016. Both were sentenced to life imprisonment for the rape of the girl and subsequently sentenced to 35 years for engaging in a child exploitation enterprise.<ref name=vg/><ref name=toronto/>\n* Site administrator Tyler David Walker, a 21-year-old Canadian, was initially arrested on the matter in March 2017, and sentenced to five years in prison.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.kelownacapnews.com/news/child-porn-forum-moderator-in-penticton-sentenced-to-five-years/ |title=Child exploitation forum moderator in Penticton sentenced to five years - Kelowna Capital News |last=Dustin Godfrey and Kristi Patton |date=2018-01-09 |work=Kelowna Capital News |access-date=2018-01-23 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n* Site user Robert Zitzelsperger, a former science teacher in Sydney.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/former-monte-sant-angelo-mercy-college-science-teacher-sentenced-over-child-porn-20171123-gzrzdt.html |title=Former private school science teacher sentenced over child exploitation |last=Cormack |first=Lucy |date=2017-11-24 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=2018-01-23 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Media portrayals ==\nIn November 2019 the Canadian network [[CBC Radio|CBC]] in collaboration with Norwegian VG ([[Verdens Gang]]) published a six-part podcast<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/a113b246-0214-11ea-a530-16c6c29e70ca|title=Subscribe to read {{!}} Financial Times|website=www.ft.com|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/radio/podcasts/hunting-warhead/index.html|title=Hunting Warhead - a CBC/VG podcast|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinteractives.cbc.ca/longform/hunting-warhead-child-porn-investigation|title=Hunting Warhead - CBC News|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>chronicling the investigation by a VG journalist and a Norwegian computer security expert of child sexual abuse networks on the dark web. In the course of the six episodes, CBC journalist Daemon Fairless examines the background of Benjamin Faulkner and the course of events that led to his capture. The podcast is called ''[https://www.cbc.ca/radio/podcasts/hunting-warhead/ Hunting Warhead].''    \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Tor hidden services}}\n\n[[Category:Underground culture]]\n[[Category:Defunct Tor hidden services]]\n[[Category:Child pornography]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2016]]\n[[Category:Internet properties disestablished in 2017]]\n[[Category:Child pornography crackdowns]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox website\n|name            = Childs Play\n|logo            =\n|logocaption     =\n|screenshot      = Childs_Play_censored_screenshot.jpg\n|collapsible     =\n|caption         =\n|url             = <!-- Please do not add a link to the site, as it fails Wikipedia's guidelines on external links. -->\n|type            = [[Child pornography]] [[File sharing|sharing]]\n|language        = [[English language|English]]\n|num_users       =\n|content_license =\n|programming language =\n|owner           =\n|author          =\n|launch_date     = April 2016\n|alexa           =\n|revenue         =\n|current_status  = Offline (as of September 2017)\n|footnotes       =\n}}\n\n'''Childs Play''' was a [[darknet]] [[child abuse]] website that operated from April 2016 to September 2017, which at its peak was the largest of its class.<ref name=vg>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vg.no/spesial/2017/undercover-darkweb/?lang=en |title=VG exposed the largest child sexual abuse forum. It was run by the police. |last=H\u00e5kon F. H\u00f8ydal, Einar Otto Stangvik and Natalie Rem\u00f8e Hansen |work=[[VG Nett]] |access-date=2018-01-23 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20180110132111/https://www.vg.no/spesial/2017/undercover-darkweb/?lang=en |archive-date=2018-01-10 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=toronto>{{Cite news |url=http://torontosun.com/2017/10/12/canadian-man-was-king-of-kiddie-porn/wcm/df1a5300-ce6d-43b8-8178-4007093a9523 |title=Canadian man was king of kiddie porn |last=Brad Hunter |date=2017-10-12 |work=Toronto Sun |access-date=2018-01-23 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.deepdotweb.com/2017/10/16/task-force-argos-operated-darknet-child-abuse-forum-11-months/ |title=Task Force Argos Operated a Darknet Child Abuse Forum for 11 Months |last=C. Aliens |date=October 16, 2017 |work=[[DeepDotWeb]] |access-date=2018-01-23 |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124005729/https://www.deepdotweb.com/2017/10/16/task-force-argos-operated-darknet-child-abuse-forum-11-months/ |archive-date=January 24, 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=guardian>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2017/oct/07/australian-police-sting-brings-down-paedophile-forum-on-dark-web |title=Australian police sting brings down paedophile forum on dark web |last=Knaus |first=Christopher |date=2017-10-07 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=2018-01-25 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/queensland-police-behind-worlds-largest-child-porn-forum-20171007-gywcps.html |title=Queensland police take over world's largest child porn forum in sting operation |last=McInnes |first=William |date=2017-10-08 |work=[[Brisbane Times]] |access-date=2018-01-25 |language=en}}</ref> The site was concealed by being run as a hidden service on the [[Tor (anonymity network)|Tor network]]. After running the site for the first six months, owner Benjamin Faulkner of [[Guelph]], Ontario, Canada was captured by the [[United States Department of Homeland Security]]. For the remaining eleven months the website was owned and operated by the Australian [[Queensland Police Service]]'s [[Task Force Argos]], as part of ''Operation Artemis''.\n\n== Reactions ==\n\nThe website was run by Australian police for 11 months, and involved impersonation of the forum owner ''WarHead'' (Faulkner's alias) which required police to regularly post child abuse images, in order to convince users that the site was not compromised.<ref name=vg/><ref name=guardian/><ref name=noreact>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vg.no/nyheter/utenriks/kampen-mot-overgrepsfiler/unicef-clear-violation-of-un-children-s-convention/a/24157545/ |title=UNICEF: \u2013 Clear violation of UN children\u2019s convention |last=Maria Knoph Vigsn\u00e6s, H\u00e5kon F. H\u00f8ydal, Einar Otto Stangvik, and Natalie Rem\u00f8e Hansen |work=[[Verdens Gang]] |access-date=2018-01-23 |language=en}}</ref> Ivar Stokkereit, a legal adviser to the United Nations Children's Fund ([[UNICEF]]) in Norway, stated this was \"a clear violation of the UN [[Convention on the Rights of the Child]], even though the police\u2019s intention is to prevent new offenses in the long run\". [[Amnesty International]] also criticized the actions as \"unacceptable under human rights law\". [[ECPAT]] (End Child Prostitution, Child Pornography and Trafficking of Children for Sexual Purposes) supported the proactive approach taken by Task Force Argos.<ref name=noreact/>\n\n[[James Sheptycki]], professor in criminology at [[York University]], criticized the transfer of the website from its original server in Europe to Australia as \"[[Forum shopping|jurisdiction shopping]]\", being done due to the favourable legal framework in Australia that would allow the website to continue running in this way.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vg.no/nyheter/utenriks/undercover-darkweb/police-acting-as-judges/a/24162582/ |title=\u2013 Police acting as judges |last=H\u00e5kon F. H\u00f8ydal, Einar Otto Stangvik, and Natalie Rem\u00f8e Hansen  |work=[[Verdens Gang]] |access-date=2018-01-23 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Convictions ==\n\nThe capture of the site, and its subsequent use to gather information, has led to arrests and convictions:\n\n* Benjamin Faulkner's associate, Patrick Falte, was captured together with Faulkner when they met in Virginia in October 2016 two days after they had raped a four-year-old girl. Falte had been an administrator on ''The GiftBox Exchange'', another darknet child exploitation site that was shut down in November 2016. Both were sentenced to life imprisonment for the rape of the girl and subsequently sentenced to 35 years for engaging in a child exploitation enterprise.<ref name=vg/><ref name=toronto/>\n* Site administrator Tyler David Walker, a 21-year-old Canadian, was initially arrested on the matter in March 2017, and sentenced to five years in prison.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.kelownacapnews.com/news/child-porn-forum-moderator-in-penticton-sentenced-to-five-years/ |title=Child exploitation forum moderator in Penticton sentenced to five years - Kelowna Capital News |last=Dustin Godfrey and Kristi Patton |date=2018-01-09 |work=Kelowna Capital News |access-date=2018-01-23 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n* Site user Robert Zitzelsperger, a former science teacher in Sydney.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/former-monte-sant-angelo-mercy-college-science-teacher-sentenced-over-child-porn-20171123-gzrzdt.html |title=Former private school science teacher sentenced over child exploitation |last=Cormack |first=Lucy |date=2017-11-24 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=2018-01-23 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Media portrayals ==\nIn November 2019 the Canadian network [[CBC Radio|CBC]] in collaboration with Norwegian VG ([[Verdens Gang]]) published a six-part podcast<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/a113b246-0214-11ea-a530-16c6c29e70ca|title=Subscribe to read {{!}} Financial Times|website=www.ft.com|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/radio/podcasts/hunting-warhead/index.html|title=Hunting Warhead - a CBC/VG podcast|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinteractives.cbc.ca/longform/hunting-warhead-child-porn-investigation|title=Hunting Warhead - CBC News|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>chronicling the investigation by a VG journalist and a Norwegian computer security expert of child pornography networks on the dark web. In the course of the six episodes, CBC journalist Daemon Fairless examines the background of Benjamin Faulkner and the course of events that led to his capture. The podcast is called ''Hunting Warhead.''    \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Tor hidden services}}\n\n[[Category:Underground culture]]\n[[Category:Defunct Tor hidden services]]\n[[Category:Child pornography]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2016]]\n[[Category:Internet properties disestablished in 2017]]\n[[Category:Child pornography crackdowns]]\n", "name_user": "Lechatmarbre", "label": "safe", "comment": "Replaced few words and added link for podcast", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Childs_Play_(website)"}
{"title_page": "Sonu Nigam", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian playback singer}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Sonu Nigam\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = SonuNigam01.jpg\n| caption          = Sonu Nigam at [[Zee Cine Award]]s, 2013\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1973|07|30|df=y}}<ref\nname=\"Biography\">{{cite news |title=Biography |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/singer-of-the-week/sonu-nigam/biography/articleshow/7310398.cms |accessdate=22 September 2016 |work=[[The Times of India]] |agency=TNN |date=18 January 2011 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20160923072010/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/singer-of-the-week/sonu-nigam/biography/articleshow/7310398.cms |archivedate=23 September 2016 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[Faridabad]], [[Haryana]], India<ref name=\"Biography\"/>\n| genre            = [[Pop Rock]], [[Classical Music|classical]], [[semi-classical music|semi-classical]], [[ghazals]], [[Playback singer|playback]]\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer|actor|composer|anchor}}\n| instrument       = [[Vocals]]\n| label            = [[Sony Music India|Sony Music]], [[Super Cassettes Industries T-Series|T-Series]], [[Tips Industries|Tips]], [[Saregama]], Venus Records & Tapes\n| years_active     = 1990 - present\n}}\n\n'''Sonu Nigam''' (born 30 July 1973)<ref name=\"dob\">{{cite web |last1=Sen |first1=Sushmita |title=Happy Birthday Sonu Nigam: Lesser Known Facts and Popular Tracks of the Singing Sensation |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/happy-birthday-sonu-nigam-lesser-known-facts-popular-tracks-singing-sensation-video-640905 |website=International Business Times, India Edition |accessdate=14 May 2016 |date=30 July 2015}}</ref> is an Indian [[playback singer]], [[composer]] . He sings predominantly in [[Bollywood|Hindi]] and [[Kannada]] language films. He has also sung in [[English language|English]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]], [[Meitei language|Manipuri]], [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]], [[Telugu language|Telugu]], [[Marathi language|Marathi]], [[Nepali language|Nepali]], [[Maithili language|Maithili]], [[Malayalam]] and various Indian languages.<ref name=\"languages\"/>  Nigam has also released [[Indian pop]] albums and acted in a number of Hindi films.<ref>{{cite news |title=It's Nigam, not Niigaam, Says Sonu |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-09-08/news-and-interviews/28225350_1_sonu-nigam-change-phase |accessdate=3 April 2012 |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |date=8 September 2010}}</ref> He has been one of the highest paid Indian singers. He is also regarded as the \"Lord of Chords\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-sonu-nigam-creates-magic-in-kannada/20100819.htm |title=sonu nigam creates magic in kannada |date=19 August 2010<!-- 12:42-->}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/kannada/music/The-Golden-Singer-of-Karnataka-Sonu-Nigam-turns-41/articleshow/39295244.cms |title=The golden singer of Karnataka |date=30 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Life and background==\n[[File:Sonu Nigam & Madhurima Nigam at Rakesh Roshan\u2019s birthday bash.jpg|thumb|200px|Sonu Nigam with wife Madhurima Nigam at [[Rakesh Roshan]]'s birthday, 2017]]\nSonu Nigam was born on 30 July 1973 to Agam Kumar Nigam and Shobha Nigam, in the city of [[Faridabad]], [[Haryana]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sonunigam.in/about-me.php |title=Sonu Nigam: About Me |publisher=Sonu Nigam |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref> His father was from [[Agra]] and his mother was from [[Garhwal division|Garhwal]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=I've had marital problems in the past, but I am sorted now: Sonu Nigam |first=Aasheesh |last=Sharma |work=Hindustan Times |date=6 September 2014 |accessdate=16 January 2019 |url= https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/i-ve-had-marital-problems-in-the-past-but-i-am-sorted-now-sonu-nigam/story-CWyPiEzUo8qlXDob2Hv83O.html}}</ref> His sister [[Teesha Nigam]] is also a professional singer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/sonu-nigam-younger-sister-teesha-sings-music-debut-bollywood-news/17673162|title=Say's Younger Sister Teesha Sings Like A Monster|date=10 October 2016|work=Mid-Day|access-date=6 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nNigam began his singing career at the age of four, when he joined his father Agam Kumar Nigam on stage to sing [[Mohammed Rafi]]'s song \"Kya Hua Tera Wada\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-03-03/news-and-interviews/37390250_1_sonu-nigam-mumbai-singer |work=The Times Of India |title=Sonu Nigam: My mother was my best ally&nbsp;\u2014 The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Kaminsky|first1=Arnold P.|last2=Long|first2=Roger D. |title=India Today: An Encyclopedia of Life in the Republic &#91;2 volumes&#93;: An Encyclopedia of Life in the Republic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VVxlfDHGTFYC&pg=PA404|date=23 September 2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-37463-0|pages=404\u2013|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref> Nigam began accompanying his father on his singing appearances at weddings and parties. He moved to [[Mumbai]] with his father to begin his [[Bollywood]] singing career at the age of 18.<ref name=\"earlyyears\">{{cite web |title=Sonu Nigam |url=http://www.sonuniigaam.in/aboutme.php |accessdate=25 July 2008}}</ref> He was trained by Hindustani classical singer [[Ghulam Mustafa Khan (singer)|Ustad Ghulam Mustafa Khan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenational.ae/arts-lifestyle/music/a-look-at-the-rise-and-careers-of-sonu-nigam-and-atif-aslam-ahead-of-their-concert-tomorrow |title=A look at the rise and careers of Sonu Nigam and Atif Aslam ahead of their concert tomorrow |publisher=Abu Dahbi Media |accessdate=27 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nNigam married Madhurima Mishra on 15 February 2002.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sonu Nigam weds city belle |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Sonu-Nigam-weds-city-belle/articleshow/1089529.cms |accessdate=8 November 2016 |work=[[The Times of India]] |agency=PTI |date=15 February 2002 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20161108185254/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Sonu-Nigam-weds-city-belle/articleshow/1089529.cms |archivedate=8 November 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He has a son named Nevaan.<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Sonus-son-sings-with-Lata/articleshow/6387008.cms |title=Sonu's son sings with Lata! |newspaper=[[Times of India]] |date=22 August 2010 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nNigam had changed his name to ''Sonu Niigaam'' citing numerology beliefs, but later decided to go back to his original birth name. He said, \"The name change was one of the journeys I had to take in life. I had to go through that path to learn the truth. And I have realised that I don\u2019t want to tamper with these forces. I am happy with all the astrological arrangements I was born with. I am happy finding success with my original name \u2013 ''Sonu Nigam''.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=It's Nigam, not Niigaam, says Sonu |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Its-Nigamnot-Niigaam-says-Sonu/articleshow/6512924.cms|date=8 September 2010|accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Singing and composing work==\n[[File:Sonu Nigam121.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|left]]\nHe has recorded Romantic, Rock, Sad, Devotional, Ghazal and Patriotic songs. He has sung in: [[Hindi]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]], [[English language|English]], [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Kannada]], [[Maithili language|Maithili]], [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]], [[Meitei language|Manipuri]], [[Marathi language|Marathi]], [[Nepali language|Nepali]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]] and [[Telugu language|Telugu]] till date.<ref name=\"languages\">{{cite news |title=Sonu Nigam and Neha Kakkar to sing a Jagrata track for Vaishno Devi - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/sonu-nigam-and-neha-kakkar-to-sing-a-jagrata-track-for-vaishno-devi/articleshow/72129077.cms |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=The Times of India |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"earlyyears\" /> Nigam has released pop albums in Hindi, Kannada, Odia, Chhattisgarhi and Punjabi, as well as [[Hindu]] and Islamic devotional albums. He has released several Buddhist albums. Nigam has performed in countries in North America, Europe, the Middle East, Africa, Asia and Australia. In May\u2013June 2007, he participated in The Incredibles tour with [[Asha Bhosle]], [[Kunal Ganjawala]], and [[Kailash Kher]]. In September\u2013October of the same year, he gave solo concerts titled Simply Sonu in Canada and Germany, the first Indian singer to do so.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sonu Nigam's Tour to Germany |url=http://www.glamsham.com/movies/scoops/07/aug/08_sonu_nigams_tour_to_germany_080701.asp |accessdate=25 July 2008}}</ref> In April 2008, he toured India promoting his Punjabi single \"Punjabi Please\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Close-Up and BIG 92.7 FM bring Sonu Nigam's concert |url=http://itvx.net/2008/04/18/close-up-and-big-927-fm-bring-sonu-nigam%E2%80%99s-concert/ |accessdate=25 July 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081230074852/http://itvx.net/2008/04/18/close-up-and-big-927-fm-bring-sonu-nigam%E2%80%99s-concert/ |archivedate=30 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nNigam's first film song as a playback singer was for ''Janam'' (1990), which was never officially released. He then began making radio commercials and also acted in some of them.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nHis first released song was \"O Aasman Wale\" from the movie ''[[Aaja Meri Jaan]]'' (1992). Sonu had also sung the title track of Aaja Meri Jaan, but it was dubbed by SP Balasubramaniam. He released his first album \"Rafi Ki Yaadein\" in 1992. After this, he sung in some movies, including  ''[[Muqabla (1993 film)|Muqabla]]'' (1993),  ''[[Meherbaan|Meherban]]'' (1993),  ''[[Shabnam]]'' (1993), ''[[Kasam Teri Kasam]]'' (1993), ''[[Aag (1994 film)|Aag]]'' (1994),  ''[[Khuddar]]'' (1994),  ''[[Hulchul (1995 film)|Hulchul]]'' (1994),   ''[[Stuntman (film)|Stuntman]]'' (1994), ''[[Ram Jaane|Ramjaane]]'' (1995),  ''[[Gaddaar (1995 film)|Gaddaar]]'' (1995), ''[[Jeet (1996 film)|Jeet]]'' (1996) etc. Sonu Nigam was supposed to playback the song \"Ek Ladki Ko Dekha Toh\" from ''[[1942: A Love Story]]'' and Sonu was the first choice of R.D. Burman for this song, but the song was eventually recorded by Kumar Sanu. He began hosting the TV show, ''[[Sa Re Ga Ma]]'' in 1995 and sang \"Accha Sila Diya\" for the film ''[[Bewafa Sanam]]'' and achieved great success because of it. In the same year,<ref name=\"earlyyears\" /> he sang the [[Anu Malik]]-composed song \"[[Sandese Aate Hai]]\" in ''[[Border (1997 film)|Border]]'' and performed the [[Nadeem-Shravan]]-composed song \"Yeh Dil Deewana\" in ''[[Pardes (film)|Pardes]]'' in 1997, which took him out from his stereotyped image of singing. Nigam's album ''[[Deewana (album)|Deewana]]'', with music directed by [[Sajid-Wajid]], was released by T-Series in 1999 and is one of the most selling and celebrated albums till date.<ref name=\"earlyyears\" />\n\nNigam provided playback singing for Hindi movies, including the title song for the film ''[[Kal Ho Naa Ho]]'' in 2003 to \"[[Abhi Mujh Mein Kahin]]\"  for ''[[Agneepath (2012 film)|Agneepath]]'' in 2012 and many more.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}. However, from the past few years, he has gone selective about his songs so that he can focus more on creative works. His upcoming project with [[Bickram Ghosh]] named \"Bollywood Retro\" is one such project.\n\nHe composed the title track of the film ''[[Singh Saab The Great]]'' in 2013 and has also composed music for other films including: ''[[Sooper Se Ooper]]'' and ''[[Jal (film)|Jal]]'', in collaboration with percussionist [[Bickram Ghosh]] in the same year.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\nNigam has released albums of [[Mohammed Rafi]]'s songs including ''Rafi Ki Yaadein'', a collection early in his career, which was re-released in Rafi's memory in September 2007 as a six-disc collection of 100 songs, titled ''Kal Aaj Aur Kal''.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=www.indiaglitz.com |title=Sonu Nigam pays homage to Mohd Rafi |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/hindi/article/33495.html |accessdate=25 July 2008}}</ref> In 2008, soon after releasing ''Classically Mild'', he released a single Punjabi track entitled \"Punjabi Please\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Big FM launches Sonu Niigaam single Punjabi Please |url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k8/mar/mar34.php |accessdate=25 July 2008|date=3 March 2008 }}</ref> and ''Rafi Resurrected'', a two-disc collection of Rafi songs with music by the [[City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra|Birmingham Symphony Orchestra]]. He contributed to the lyrics of several songs and directed the music for his album ''[[Chanda Ki Doli]]''.\n\nSonu has always been loved and respected by the Bollywood industry. Among the new generation of singers, [[Lata Mangeshkar]] loves Sonu the most.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/mar/04sd4.htm|title=rediff.com: Why Lata Mangeshkar likes Sonu Nigam|website=www.rediff.com|accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref> [[Shah Rukh Khan]] has been always seen heaping praises on Sonu whom he considers as an true artiste.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K88t35OVcXc|title=An emotional tribute to Javed Akhtar from Sonu Nigam at the 7th Royal Stag Mirchi Music Awards|accessdate=23 December 2019|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-4Cf9Yivk_Q|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com|accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref> [[Shankar Mahadevan]] considers Sonu Nigam as his favourite singer in recent times.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://sonuniigaamandme.blogspot.in/2012/02/sonu-nigam-is-shankar-mahadevans-ideal.html | title=Sonu Nigam & Me: Sonu Nigam is Shankar Mahadevan's Ideal Singer| date=2 February 2012}}</ref> Music director [[Himesh Reshammiya]] also believes that Sonu is the best singer in the industry.<ref>http://www.bollywood.com/i-think-sonu-nigam-best-singer-india-himesh-reshammiya</ref> Filmmaker [[Shirish Kunder]] is full of praises for Sonu.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.lyricsmint.com/2010/10/shirish-kunder-cant-stop-praising-sonu.html |title = Shirish Kunder can't stop praising Sonu Nigam, He has sung in 54 different voices}}</ref> Shekhar of [[Vishal-Shekhar]] duo considered him as the finest live performer. Even [[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]] who is one of his contemporaries admiring him from a long time. Singing sensation [[Armaan Malik]] idolises Sonu Nigam as his God and Guru draws a lot of inspiration from him.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/living-his-dream/article19209189.ece |title = Armaan Malik, living his dream|newspaper = The Hindu|date = 4 July 2017|last1 = Walia|first1 = Gahna}}</ref>\n\nAfter the death of [[Michael Jackson]],  Nigam released a song as a tribute to Jackson which was included on the tribute album ''The Beat of Our Hearts''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Michael Jackson Trubute portrait |url=http://michaeljacksontributeportrait.com/article.php?article_id=232 |accessdate=15 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2007, at the inauguration of [[Harvard University|Harvard]] University's 28th president, [[Drew Gilpin Faust]], Nigam sang [[Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi|Mahatma Gandhi]]'s favourite [[bhajan]], \"Vaishnav Jan To Tene Kahiye\", with the Harvard College Sangeet.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sonu Nigam invited to perform at Harvard University |url=http://www.glamsham.com/movies/scoops/07/oct/06_sonu_nigam_100704.asp |accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2008, he participated in a three-city tour of the United Kingdom, singing Rafi songs with the City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra (CBSO) . This followed the release of these songs by the CBSO and the Indian music company [[Sa Re Ga Ma]] on ''Rafi Resurrected''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sonu Nigam's new album 'Rafi Resurrected' in July this year |url=http://news.oneindia.in/2007/04/19/sonu-nigams-new-album-rafi-resurrected-in-july-this-year-1176955506.html |accessdate=25 July 2008|date=19 April 2007 }}</ref>\n\nHe participated in a US tour with [[Sunidhi Chauhan]] in 2009 called The Explosion 2009 tour and in a [[United Kingdom|UK]] tour titled ''All Izz Well'' in November 2010. In 2011, Nigam collaborated with Kakas Entertainment and [[Laxmikant-Pyarelal]] for a Maestros Concert performing Mohammed Rafi songs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/top-singers-100-musicians-at-laxmikantpyarelal-concert/789055/ |title=Top singers, 100 musicians at Laxmikant-Pyarelal concert |publisher=Indian Express |date=12 May 2011 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Nigam collaborated with [[Britney Spears]] on a remix of her \"[[I Wanna Go]]\" track,<ref>{{cite web |title=Sonu Nigam and Britney Spears to sing together |url=http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2011/jul/140711-informer-1.htm |publisher=mid-day.com |accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref><ref>*[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-07-14/news-and-interviews/29772881_1_sonu-nigam-britney-spears-baby-one-more-time Sonu Nigam collaborates with Britney Spears]</ref> and with DJ [[Avicii]] on his song \"Indian Levels\", produced by Avicii in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Why-the-Sonu-Nigam-Avicii-track-took-a-year/articleshow/17518336.cms |title=Why the Sonu Nigam-Avicii track took a year! |publisher=The Times of India |date=7 December 2012 |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was ranked the Number 1 artist on the US Billboard Uncharted charts twice in September and October 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-09-07/uncharted |title=Uncharted : Sep 07, 2013 &#124; Billboard Chart Archive |publisher=Billboard.com |date=7 September 2013 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-10-05/uncharted |title=Uncharted : Oct 05, 2013 &#124; Billboard Chart Archive |publisher=Billboard.com |date=5 October 2013 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Nigam recorded a song with the music director [[Khayyam]] for the upcoming project titled ''Gulam Bandhu''.<ref name=\"Indian Express\">{{cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/music/words-not-enough-to-praise-sonu-nigam-khayyam/ |title=Words not enough to praise Sonu Nigam: Khayyam |publisher=Indian Express |date=1 September 2011 |accessdate=31 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Work in Kannada==\n[[File:Sonu Nigam122.jpg|thumb|upright=2.2|left|alt=Sonu Nigam singing in the concert|Nigam performing at the live concert in 2014]]\nNigam's first song in [[Kannada]] was in 1996 for the film ''[[Jeevanadhi]]''. The song \"Yello Yaro Hego\" was composed by [[Saluri Koteswara Rao]] with lyrics by [[R. N. Jayagopal]]. Nigam has since sung over 600 Kannada songs.<ref name=\"deccanherald.com\">{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/233428/pitching-right.html |title=Pitching it right |publisher=Deccanherald.com |date=11 March 2012 |accessdate=9 July 2013}}</ref> He is known as the Golden Singer Of Karnataka.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/kannada/music/The-Golden-Singer-of-Karnataka-Sonu-Nigam-turns-41/articleshow/39295244.cms |title=The Golden Singer of Karnataka, Sonu Nigam, turns 41 \u2013 The Times of India |language=ru |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=30 July 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/kannada/movies/news-interviews/Sonu-lauded-for-new-song/articleshow/22325543.cms |title=Sonu lauded for new song&nbsp;\u2014 The Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=5 September 2013 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |last=Andanappa |first=Nagarathna |url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/kannada/news/2013/sonu-nigam-15-best-kannada-songs-birthday-special-115901.html |title=Birthday Boy Sonu Nigam's 15 Best Kannada Songs&nbsp;\u2014 Filmibeat |publisher=Entertainment.oneindia.in |date=30 July 2013 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nHis songs include \"Cheluve Yeke Bande\", from the film ''Majnu'', composed by [[Gurukiran]]; \"Titanic Heroine Nee Nanna Cheluve\", from the film ''[[Snehaloka]]''; the title track from the film ''[[Monalisa (film)|Monalisa]]'' composed by Valisha Sandeep;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kannadachitraranga.com/sonu-nigam-rocks-in-monalisa-monalisa-sadaa-dhyan/ |title=SONU NIGAM rocks in Monalisa&nbsp;\u2013 Monalisa&nbsp;\u2013 Sadaa ,Dhyan &#124; Kannada songs collection, kannada movie news |publisher=Kannadachitraranga.com |date=24 June 2011 |accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref> \"Hamsave Hamsave\" from the film ''Gatti Mela'', composed by [[Hamsalekha]],  \"Kannale Kannale\" from the film ''[[Aham Premasmi]]'', composed by [[V. Ravichandran|V.Ravichandran]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.movieskope.com/songs/tag/aham-premasmi-kannada-movie-songs-mp3/ |title=Welcome movieskope.com&nbsp;\u2014 BlueHost.com |publisher=Movieskope.com |date= |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref> and \"Baaninda Baa Chandira, from the movie ''Kanti'', composed by [[Gurukiran]]. The 2006 film ''[[Mungaru Male]]'' created a sensation and spawned several records, mainly in Karnataka.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/kannada/article/35125.html |title='Mungaru Male' National record&nbsp;\u2014 Kannada Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bangalore365.com/actors/mungaru-male-sucessful-365-days/ |title=Mungaru Male&nbsp;\u2013 Successful 365 days !! at Bangalore 365 |publisher=Bangalore365.com |date=6 December 2007 |accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe songs \"Mungaru Maleye\" and \"[[Anisuthide]]\" were composed by [[Mano Murthy]] and written by [[Yogaraj Bhat]] and [[Jayant Kaikini]] respectively. Nigam has said that he finds Kannada songs more fulfilling than the Hindi numbers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/news-topic/zee-kannada-/video-sonu-finds-kannada-music-fulfilling__IkieBZGaCM.html|title=Sonu Finds Kannada Music Fulfilling|publisher=Moneycontrol.com|date=|accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Deccan Herald]]'' he said \"Kannada songs make me feel positive\".<ref>{{cite web |author=Sudha Hegde |url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/89369/kannada-songs-make-me-feel.html |title='Kannada songs make me feel positive'. |publisher=Deccanherald.com |date=18 August 2010 |accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref> He went on to say: \"I highly respect the musicians of [[Karnataka]] and many of my favourite songs are in Kannada. I consider [[Bangalore]] as my second birthplace. Even if someone requests me to sing a Kannada song while I'm performing in the West Indies, I will sing it for them\".<ref name=\"deccanherald.com\" />\n[[File:Sonu Nigam(1).jpg|thumb|180px|right|Sonu Nigaam during a Peace Rally in [[Mumbai]] on 20 November 2011]]\nFrom the same ''Mungaru Male'' combination, composer Murthy, lyricist Kaikini and Nigam got together to record the Kannada album ''[[Neene Bari Neene]]'', produced by [[Ashok Kheny]]. Videos for the songs \"Neene Bari Neene\" and \"Baa Nodu Gelathi\" were shot on the outskirts of Bangalore featuring Nigam and model [[Madhuri Bhattacharya]] in the lead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Br53jdUFAAY |title=Kannada Sonu Nigam Neene Bari Neene Manomurthy |publisher=YouTube |date=31 August 2009 |accessdate=9 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6U2TkpF_40E |title=Sonu Nigam&nbsp;\u2014 Baa Nodu Gelathi&nbsp;\u2014 Neene Bari Neene (HQ) |publisher=YouTube |date=6 February 2011 |accessdate=9 July 2013}}</ref> Nigam also composed a theme song for the [[Karnataka Bulldozers]] team in the [[Celebrity Cricket League]] and sang it with [[Kunal Ganjawala]] and [[Sowmya Raoh]], who also penned the lyrics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=krDVvYXbR64 |title=Karnataka Bulldozers OFFICIAL THEME SONG [HQ&#93; Celebrity Cricket League |publisher=YouTube |date=12 January 2012 |accessdate=9 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe is called 'The Golden Singer Of Karnataka'.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n==Work as a host and celebrity judge==\nNigam was the host of the ''[[Sa Re Ga Ma]]'' music show from 1995 until 1999 and became household name.<ref name=bbc>{{cite news |title=Does India have the X factor? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-13592636 |accessdate=29 August 2011 |newspaper=BBC News |date=30 May 2011 |author=Rajini Vaidyanathan}}</ref> He returned on ''[[Sa Re Ga Ma Pa L'il Champs International]]'' as a judge with [[Suresh Wadkar]] in October 2007. Nigam was a celebrity judge on the ''[[Sa Re Ga Ma Pa Mega Challenge]]'' grand finale on 12 December 2009 .\n\nNigam hosted the TV show ''Kisme Kitna Hai Dum'' on [[Star Plus]] in 2002. He appeared as the judge on ''[[Indian Idol]]'' in seasons 1 (October 2004&nbsp;\u2013 March 2005) and 2 (November 2005&nbsp;\u2013 April 2006), and was a celebrity judge in seasons 3 (17 August 2007) and 4 (16 January 2009 and 6 February 2009).{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\nIn 2006, Nigam hosted ''Life Ki Dhun with Sonu Nigaam'' on [[Radio City (Indian radio station)|Radiocity 91.1 FM]], interviewing musicians.<ref>{{cite web |title=Life Ki Dhun Sonu Niigaam |url=http://sify.com/radiocity/index.php |accessdate=25 July 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe appeared as a celebrity judge on ''[[ STAR Voice of India]]'' in August 2007 (Season 1) and in December 2008 (Season 2), and on the grand finale of music reality show ''[[Jo Jeeta Wohi Super Star]]'' on 12 July 2008.\n\nNigam was a judge/mentor on ''[[Chhote Ustaad]] \u2013 Do Deshon Ki Ek Awaaz'' (July&nbsp;\u2013 October 2010) with [[Rahat Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan]], and was a judge/mentor on the first season of ''[[X Factor (India)]]'' (29 May&nbsp;\u2013 2 September 2011) along with [[Sanjay Leela Bhansali]] and [[Shreya Ghoshal]].<ref name=bbc />\n\nOn 23 August 2015, he appeared on \"[[The Anupam Kher Show - Kucch Bhi Ho Sakta Hai|The Anupam Kher Show]]\" sharing his life experiences. He has been also one of the three judges of Indian Idol 2016\u201317.\n\n==Film and voice-over acting==\nNigam's acting career<ref>{{cite web |title=Sonu Nigam |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0631415/ |accessdate=25 July 2008}}</ref> started as a child in films including ''[[Betaab]]'' (1983). As an adult, he acted in films such as ''[[Jaani Dushman: Ek Anokhi Kahani]]'', ''[[Kash Aap Hamare Hote]]'' and ''[[Love in Nepal]]''. He has been signed to be in ''Ankhon Ankhon Mein'', about a blind singer.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sonu ready to play blind! |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report_sonu-ready-to-play-blind_1100939 |accessdate=29 August 2011 |newspaper=DNA |date=3 June 2007 |author=Noyon Jyoti Parasara}}</ref> Nigam provided the [[voice-over|voice]] for the lead character, in the Hindi dubbed version of ''[[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]]''.<ref name=disney>{{cite news |title=INDIAN TELEVISION PREMIER OF DISNEY'S ALADDIN |url=http://www.disney.in/corporate/pr_05_feb23.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405231250/http://www.disney.in/corporate/pr_05_feb23.htm |archivedate=5 April 2012  }}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honours ==\n[[File:The President Dr. A.P.J. Abdul Kalam presenting the Best Male Playback Singer Award for the year 2004 to Shri Sonu Nigam at the 51st National Film Award function in New Delhi on February 2, 2005.jpg|thumb|250px|Nigam (''right'') receiving the National Film Award for Best Male Playback Singer from President [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam]] (''left''), 2005.]]\nSonu Nigam is the winner of several awards including 1 [[National Award]], 2 [[Filmfare Awards]] in Hindi & 3 [[Filmfare Awards South]].\n*'''2017'''  Haryana Gaurav Samman by Haryana Government, Government of India<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/music/sonu-nigam-honored-with-haryana-gaurav-samman-by-haryana-government/articleshow/56622768.cms|title=Sonu Nigam honored with Haryana Gaurav Samman by Haryana government - Mumbai Mirror -|work=Mumbai Mirror|access-date=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n*'''[[9th Mirchi Music Awards|2016]]'''   [[Mirchi Music Awards]] for Indie Pop Song of the Year for \"Aye Jahaan Aasmaan\"\n*'''2016'''   Lions Gold Award for Favorite Evergreen Singer jal best\n*'''2015'''  Oscar 2015 nomination list \"Jal\" Sonu Nigam and Bickram Ghosh for their rustic compositions for the drama f ilm\n*'''2015'''   Socialathon Person of the Year\n*'''2014'''   MMASouth Best Male Vocalist Kannada\n*'''2013'''   MTV Video and Music Award 2013 for Best Male Vocalist for Abhi Mujhme Kahin\n*''' 2014'''  MMASouth Best Male Vocalist Kannada<ref>{{Citation |title=#MMASouth Best Male Vocalist Sonu Nigam Kannada Songs specially for Bangalore |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eCYeN1jIuvI |date=18 August 2014 |accessdate=30 January 2016 |last=mirchikannada}}</ref>\n*'''2013'''   Zee Cinema Award for Best Male Playback Singer for Abhi Mujhme Kahin from the film Agneepath\n*'''2013'''   Big Star Entertainment Award for Best Male Playback Singer for Abhi Mujhme Kahin from the film Agneepath\n*'''[[5th Mirchi Music Awards|2012]]'''   Royal Stag [[Mirchi Music Award for Male Vocalist of The Year]] for the song \"Abhi Mujhme Kahin\" from the film Agneepath\n* '''2012\u20132013''' [[Filmfare Awards South]] \u2013 Best Playback Singer Male for the song  \"Chendutiya Pakkadali\" from the movie ''[[Drama (2012 film)|Drama]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/kannada/news-interviews/Bangalore-Times-Film-Awards-2012-goes-to--/articleshow/21893862.cms |work=The Times Of India |title=Bangalore Times Film Awards 2012 goes to... - The Times of India}}</ref>\n*'''2012'''   Lions Gold Award for Favorite Evergreen Singer\n*'''2012'''   GIMA for Best Global Indian Collaboration \u2013 This Is It ft Jermaine Jackson *2011 GIMA(Global Indian Music Award)for MTV Youth Icon.\n*'''2011'''   Gitanjali WoW Award for Live Personality(Music).\n*'''2010''' \u2013 Global Indian Music Award for Best Live Performer (Male)<ref>{{cite news |title=Global Indian Television Awards |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/3-Idiots-wins-five-music-awards/articleshow/6907429.cms |accessdate=16 November 2010 |work=The Times Of India |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101115044219/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/3-Idiots-wins-five-music-awards/articleshow/6907429.cms |archivedate=15 November 2010}}</ref>\n*'''2010'''   GIMA(Global Indian Music Award) for Best Live Performer Male.\n*'''2010'''   GIMA(Global Indian Music Award) for Most Popular Song \u2013 All Izz Well.\n*'''2010'''   Amar Rishtey Award for Zee Icoon\u2013 TVS Sa Re Ga Ma.\n*'''2010'''   Big Star Entertainment Award for Singer of the Decade.\n*'''2009'''   Indian Television Academy Award, Best Male Singer for Dil Mill Gaye title track.\n*'''2009'''  Filmfare Award, Kannada, Best Male Playback Singer for Yenagali, Mussanje Maathu\n*'''2008'''  GPBA (German Public Bollywood Award), Best Singer (Male) for Main Agar Kahoon, Om Shanti Om.\n*'''2008''' Filmfare Award, Kannada, Best Male Playback Singer for Ninnindale, Milana.\n*'''2008'''  Indian Television Academy Award, Best Male Singer for Amber Dhara title track\n*'''2008''' Lions Gold Award for the song 'In lamhon ke Daaman me' from the film 'Jodha Akbar'.\n*'''2007''' Annual Central European Bollywood Awards, Best Male Playback Singer for Mein Agar Kahoon, Om Shanti Om.\n*'''2006''' Bollywood Music and Fashion Awards, Best Male Playback Singer for Kabhi Alvida Na Kehna, Title Track.\n*'''2005''' Indian Television Award Best Singer for Miliee Title Track.\n*'''2005'''  MTV Immies \u2013 Best Pop Album, for his self-composed album titled \"Chanda Ki Doli\".\n*'''2005''' Swaralaya Yesudas Award, for his outstanding performance in Music.\n*'''2005'''  Anadolok Award for \"Chanda Ki Doli\" album.\n*'''2005''' Lion Gold's Award for the song Main Hoon Na from the film \"Main Hoon Na\".\n*'''2005''' Star Screen Award Best Male Playback, for the song \"Dheere Jalna\", from the film \"Paheli\".\n*'''2005''' Teachers' Achievement Award\n*'''2005''' Style Icon, MTV Style Awards.\n*'''2004'''  MTV Style Awards\u2013 Best Male Playback Singer \u2013 [[Bandhan (2004 film)|Bandhan]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1051222/asp/calcutta/story_5632210.asp |title=Anandalok Awards 2004 |location=Calcutta, India |work=The Telegraph |date=22 December 2005}}</ref>\n*'''2004'''   MTV Immies \u2013 Best Male Singer, for the song \"Main Hoon Na\", from the film \"Main Hoon Na\".\n*'''2004''' National Film Award for Best Male Playback Singer, for the song \"Kal Ho Naa Ho\", from the film Kal Ho Naa Ho.\n*'''[[51st National Film Awards|2003]]''' [[National Film Award for Best Male Playback Singer]]: ''[[Kal Ho Na Ho]]'' for \"Kal Ho Naa Ho\"<ref name=\"51stawardPDF\">{{cite web |url=http://dff.nic.in/2011/51st_nff_2004.pdf |title=51st National Film Awards |publisher=[[Directorate of Film Festivals]] |accessdate=14 August 2015 }}</ref>\n*'''2003''' Apsara Film Producers' Guild Award for Best Male Playback Singer for \"Kal Ho Na Ho\" from the film Kal Ho Naa Ho.\n*'''2003''' Bollywood Music Award for Best Male Playback Singer for \"Kal Ho Na Ho\" from the film Kal Ho Naa Ho.\n*'''2003'''  IIFA Best Male Playback Award, for the song \"Kal Ho Naa Ho\", from the film Kal Ho Na Ho\n*'''2003''' Style Icon, MTV Style Awards.\n*'''2003'''  Filmfare Best Male Playback Award, for the song \"Kal Ho Naa Ho\", from the film Kal Ho Naa Ho\".\n*'''2002''' Filmfare Best Male Playback Award, for the song \"Saathiya\", from the f ilm Saathiya.\n*'''2002''' Bollywood Music Award for Best Male Playback Singer for the song \"Saathiya\" from the film \"Saathiya\".\n*'''2002'''  MTV Immies \u2013 Best Male Singer, for the song \"Saathiya\" from the film \"Saathiya\".\n*'''2002''' Zee Cine Award Best Playback Singer- Male, for the song \"Saathiya\", from the film \"Saathiya\".\n*'''2002'''  IIFA Best Male Playback Award, for the song \"Saathiya\", from the film \"Saathiya\".\n*'''2001'''  Star Screen Award Best Male Playback, for the song \"Tanhayee\", from the film \"Dil Chahta Hai\". *'''2001''' Bollywood Music Award for Best Pop Singer for the album \"Yaad\".\n*'''2001'''  IIFA Best Male Playback Award, for the song \"Suraj Hua Maddham\", from the f ilm \"Kabhi Khushi Kabhie Gham\".\n*'''2001''' Zee Cine Award Best Playback Singer<ref>{{Cite web |title=Sonu Nigam |url=http://sonunigam.in/awards.php |website=sonunigam.in |access-date=29 January 2016}}</ref>- Male, for the song \"Suraj Hua Maddham\", from the film \"Kabhi Khushi Kabhie Gham\".\n*'''1998''' Screen Award for Best Male Pop Artist for ''Kismat''<ref>{{cite web |title=Award Winners |url=http://www.expressindia.com/screen/awards/eve.htm |website=[[Screen (magazine)|Screen]] |accessdate=2 October 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19991022044355/http://www.expressindia.com/screen/awards/eve.htm |archivedate=22 October 1999}}</ref>\n*'''1997''' Sansui Viewers' Choice Award for Best Male Singer for the song \"Sandese Aate Hai\", from the film \"Border\".\n*'''1997''' Aashirwad Award for Best Male Singer for the song \"Sandese Aate Hai\", from the film \"Border\".\n*'''1997''' Zee Cine Award Best Playback Singer- Male, for the song \"Sandese Aate Hai\", from the film \"Border\".\n\n==Filmography as composer==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Film\n|-\n| 2013 ||[[Sooper Se Ooper]]\n|-\n| 2016 || Crazy Dil\n|-\n| 2015 || The Music Room\n|-\n| 2014 || [[Jal (film)|Jal]]\n|-\n| 2013 || [[Singh Saab The Great]]\n|}\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Sonu Nigam discography}}\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Film !! Character !! Year\n|-\n| ''[[Kaamchor]]'' || Sonu || 1982\n|-\n| ''[[Ustadi Ustad Se]]'' || Young Raju || 1982\n|-\n| ''[[Betaab]]'' || Young Sunny || 1983\n|-\n| ''[[Hum Se Hai Zamana]]'' || Young Shiva || 1983\n|-\n| ''[[Taqdeer (1983 film)|Taqdeer]]'' || Young Shiva || 1983\n|-\n| ''[[Krishna Krishna]]'' || Sudhama  || 1986\n|-\n| ''[[Pyaara Dushman]]'' || Manish Khadnya  || 1985\n|-\n| ''[[Jaani Dushman: Ek Anokhi Kahani]]'' || Vivek Saxena || 2002\n|-\n| ''[[Kash Aap Hamare Hote]]'' || Jai Kumar || 2003\n|-\n| ''[[Love in Nepal]]'' || Abby || 2004\n|-\n| ''[[Navra Maza Navsacha]]'' || Guest appearance as himself in a song sequence || 2005\n|-\n| ''[[Warning (2013 film)|Warning]]'' || Guest appearance as himself in \"Takeedein\" song sequence || 2013\n|}\n\n==Dubbing roles==\n===Animated films===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Film title !! Original Voice !! Character !! Dub Language !! Original Language !! Original Release !! Dub Release !! Notes\n|-\n| [[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.disney.in/corporate/pr_05_feb23.htm |title=The Walt Disney Company |publisher=Disney.in |date=23 February 2005 |accessdate=14 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405231250/http://www.disney.in/corporate/pr_05_feb23.htm |archivedate=5 April 2012  }}</ref> || [[Scott Weinger]] <br />(Speaking)<br> [[Brad Kane]] <small>(Singing)</small> || [[Aladdin (Disney character)|Aladdin]] <br>(Speaking and Singing) || Hindi || English || 1992 || 1994 || Gave both the Hindi Speaking and Singing voice to Aladdin in this film. <br>Dubbed by Modi Entertainment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.animationxpress.com/index.php/interviews/the-art-of-directing-dubs-a-chat-with-ellie-lewis |title=The art of directing dubs: A chat with Ellie Lewis \u2013 Animation Xpress |publisher=animationxpress.com |date=26 October 2004 |accessdate=20 July 2015}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Controversies==\nHis tweets against making the [[Azaan]] (Muslim call for prayer) through loudspeakers had landed him in controversy. In his tweet he stated that [[Azaan]] through loudspeakers disturbs his sleep.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/sonu-nigam-on-azaan-row-i-stand-by-my-statement/articleshow/58238260.cms|title=Sonu Nigam on Azaan row: I stand by my statement - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=18 April 2017}}</ref> He later clarified that he is not against any specific religious ritual, but against the use of loudspeakers on religious buildings. He clarified that noise pollution should be stopped, irrespective of whether it is from a temple or a mosque.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/music/sonu-nigam-tweets-more-clarification-mentioned-temples-gurudwaras-too/story-o2aWLK29RVvamFqCKNXYeN.html|title=Sonu Nigam tweets more clarification: Mentioned temples, gurudwaras too|date=19 April 2017|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=19 April 2017|language=en}}</ref> Later, Nigam again sparked controversy, when he posted a video of Azaan from his home which proved that he was indeed disturbed very early in the morning.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/music/sonu-nigam-posts-video-of-azaan-from-his-home-sparks-controversy-yet-again/story-kG5eXYQIPAVFwqHU72CuUI.html|title=Sonu Nigam posts video of azaan from his home, sparks controversy yet again|work=Hindustan Times|date=27 April 2017|access-date=23 April 2017|language=en}}</ref> Syed Sha Atef Ali Al Quaderi, vice-president of [[West Bengal United Minority Council]] announced a reward of \u20b910 Lakh to anyone who shaved Nigam's head, to which Sonu Nigam responded by shaving his own head to claim the reward.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/cities/rs-10-lakh-to-shave-sonu-nigam-bengal-fatwa-imam-says-it-s-not-a-fatwa/story-4mGXNnt8P2bS99tAaZUttJ.html|title=Rs 10 lakh to shave Sonu Nigam; Bengal \"fatwa imam\" says it's not a fatwa|date=19 April 2017|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=26 May 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nNigam has deleted his [[Twitter]] account on 24 May 2017, citing a lack of respect for [[freedom of speech]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://https://filmstudio1.blogspot.com/music/sonu-nigam-is-quitting-twitter-rants-at-length-in-support-of-paresh-rawal-abhijeet/story-RmgVo1kjmHonK1hozUUOKL.html|title=Sonu Nigam quits Twitter, rants at length in support of Paresh Rawal, Abhijeet|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Indian playback singers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {}}\n* {https://filmstudio1.blogspot.com/2020/04/blog-post_14.html}\n\n{{National Film Award Best Male Playback Singer}}\n{{FilmfareAwardBestMaleSinger}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nigam, Sonu}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian male film singers]]\n[[Category:Bollywood playback singers]]\n[[Category:Assamese playback singers]]\n[[Category:Bengali playback singers]]\n[[Category:Kannada playback singers]]\n[[Category:Marathi playback singers]]\n[[Category:Nepali-language singers]]\n[[Category:Odia Playback Singers]]\n[[Category:Punjabi-language singers]]\n[[Category:Tamil playback singers]]\n[[Category:Telugu playback singers]]\n[[Category:Indian film score composers]]\n[[Category:Indian male pop singers]]\n[[Category:Indian television presenters]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Indian male child actors]]\n[[Category:Indian male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Performers of Hindu music]]\n[[Category:People from Faridabad]]\n[[Category:Sa Re Ga Ma Pa participants]]\n[[Category:Filmfare Awards South winners]]\n[[Category:Zee Cine Awards winners]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Singers from Haryana]]\n[[Category:Indian pop-folk singers]]\n[[Category:Pop rock singers]]\n[[Category:Best Male Playback Singer National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Male film score composers]]\n[[Category:Actors from Mumbai]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian playback singer}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Sonu Nigam\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = SonuNigam01.jpg\n| caption          = Sonu Nigam at [[Zee Cine Award]]s, 2013\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1973|07|30|df=y}}<ref\nname=\"Biography\">{{cite news |title=Biography |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/singer-of-the-week/sonu-nigam/biography/articleshow/7310398.cms |accessdate=22 September 2016 |work=[[The Times of India]] |agency=TNN |date=18 January 2011 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20160923072010/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/singer-of-the-week/sonu-nigam/biography/articleshow/7310398.cms |archivedate=23 September 2016 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[Faridabad]], [[Haryana]], India<ref name=\"Biography\"/>\n| genre            = [[Pop Rock]], [[Classical Music|classical]], [[semi-classical music|semi-classical]], [[ghazals]], [[Playback singer|playback]]\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer|actor|composer|anchor}}\n| instrument       = [[Vocals]]\n| label            = [[Sony Music India|Sony Music]], [[Super Cassettes Industries T-Series|T-Series]], [[Tips Industries|Tips]], [[Saregama]], Venus Records & Tapes\n| years_active     = 1990 - present\n}}\n\n'''Sonu Nigam''' (born 30 July 1973)<ref name=\"dob\">{{cite web |last1=Sen |first1=Sushmita |title=Happy Birthday Sonu Nigam: Lesser Known Facts and Popular Tracks of the Singing Sensation |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/happy-birthday-sonu-nigam-lesser-known-facts-popular-tracks-singing-sensation-video-640905 |website=International Business Times, India Edition |accessdate=14 May 2016 |date=30 July 2015}}</ref> is an Indian [[playback singer]], [[composer]] . He sings predominantly in [[Bollywood|Hindi]] and [[Kannada]] language films. He has also sung in [[English language|English]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]], [[Meitei language|Manipuri]], [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]], [[Telugu language|Telugu]], [[Marathi language|Marathi]], [[Nepali language|Nepali]], [[Maithili language|Maithili]], [[Malayalam]] and various Indian languages.<ref name=\"languages\"/>  Nigam has also released [[Indian pop]] albums and acted in a number of Hindi films.<ref>{{cite news |title=It's Nigam, not Niigaam, Says Sonu |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-09-08/news-and-interviews/28225350_1_sonu-nigam-change-phase |accessdate=3 April 2012 |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |date=8 September 2010}}</ref> He has been one of the highest paid Indian singers. He is also regarded as the \"Lord of Chords\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-sonu-nigam-creates-magic-in-kannada/20100819.htm |title=sonu nigam creates magic in kannada |date=19 August 2010<!-- 12:42-->}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/kannada/music/The-Golden-Singer-of-Karnataka-Sonu-Nigam-turns-41/articleshow/39295244.cms |title=The golden singer of Karnataka |date=30 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Life and background==\n[[File:Sonu Nigam & Madhurima Nigam at Rakesh Roshan\u2019s birthday bash.jpg|thumb|200px|Sonu Nigam with wife Madhurima Nigam at [[Rakesh Roshan]]'s birthday, 2017]]\nSonu Nigam was born on 30 July 1973 to Agam Kumar Nigam and Shobha Nigam, in the city of [[Faridabad]], [[Haryana]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sonunigam.in/about-me.php |title=Sonu Nigam: About Me |publisher=Sonu Nigam |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref> His father was from [[Agra]] and his mother was from [[Garhwal division|Garhwal]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=I've had marital problems in the past, but I am sorted now: Sonu Nigam |first=Aasheesh |last=Sharma |work=Hindustan Times |date=6 September 2014 |accessdate=16 January 2019 |url= https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/i-ve-had-marital-problems-in-the-past-but-i-am-sorted-now-sonu-nigam/story-CWyPiEzUo8qlXDob2Hv83O.html}}</ref> His sister [[Teesha Nigam]] is also a professional singer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/sonu-nigam-younger-sister-teesha-sings-music-debut-bollywood-news/17673162|title=Say's Younger Sister Teesha Sings Like A Monster|date=10 October 2016|work=Mid-Day|access-date=6 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nNigam began his singing career at the age of four, when he joined his father Agam Kumar Nigam on stage to sing [[Mohammed Rafi]]'s song \"Kya Hua Tera Wada\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-03-03/news-and-interviews/37390250_1_sonu-nigam-mumbai-singer |work=The Times Of India |title=Sonu Nigam: My mother was my best ally&nbsp;\u2014 The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Kaminsky|first1=Arnold P.|last2=Long|first2=Roger D. |title=India Today: An Encyclopedia of Life in the Republic &#91;2 volumes&#93;: An Encyclopedia of Life in the Republic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VVxlfDHGTFYC&pg=PA404|date=23 September 2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-37463-0|pages=404\u2013|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref> Nigam began accompanying his father on his singing appearances at weddings and parties. He moved to [[Mumbai]] with his father to begin his [[Bollywood]] singing career at the age of 18.<ref name=\"earlyyears\">{{cite web |title=Sonu Nigam |url=http://www.sonuniigaam.in/aboutme.php |accessdate=25 July 2008}}</ref> He was trained by Hindustani classical singer [[Ghulam Mustafa Khan (singer)|Ustad Ghulam Mustafa Khan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenational.ae/arts-lifestyle/music/a-look-at-the-rise-and-careers-of-sonu-nigam-and-atif-aslam-ahead-of-their-concert-tomorrow |title=A look at the rise and careers of Sonu Nigam and Atif Aslam ahead of their concert tomorrow |publisher=Abu Dahbi Media |accessdate=27 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nNigam married Madhurima Mishra on 15 February 2002.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sonu Nigam weds city belle |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Sonu-Nigam-weds-city-belle/articleshow/1089529.cms |accessdate=8 November 2016 |work=[[The Times of India]] |agency=PTI |date=15 February 2002 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20161108185254/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Sonu-Nigam-weds-city-belle/articleshow/1089529.cms |archivedate=8 November 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He has a son named Nevaan.<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Sonus-son-sings-with-Lata/articleshow/6387008.cms |title=Sonu's son sings with Lata! |newspaper=[[Times of India]] |date=22 August 2010 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nNigam had changed his name to ''Sonu Niigaam'' citing numerology beliefs, but later decided to go back to his original birth name. He said, \"The name change was one of the journeys I had to take in life. I had to go through that path to learn the truth. And I have realised that I don\u2019t want to tamper with these forces. I am happy with all the astrological arrangements I was born with. I am happy finding success with my original name \u2013 ''Sonu Nigam''.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=It's Nigam, not Niigaam, says Sonu |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Its-Nigamnot-Niigaam-says-Sonu/articleshow/6512924.cms|date=8 September 2010|accessdate=29 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Singing and composing work==\n[[File:Sonu Nigam121.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|left]]\nHe has recorded Romantic, Rock, Sad, Devotional, Ghazal and Patriotic songs. He has sung in: [[Hindi]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]], [[English language|English]], [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Kannada]], [[Maithili language|Maithili]], [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]], [[Meitei language|Manipuri]], [[Marathi language|Marathi]], [[Nepali language|Nepali]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]] and [[Telugu language|Telugu]] till date.<ref name=\"languages\">{{cite news |title=Sonu Nigam and Neha Kakkar to sing a Jagrata track for Vaishno Devi - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/sonu-nigam-and-neha-kakkar-to-sing-a-jagrata-track-for-vaishno-devi/articleshow/72129077.cms |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=The Times of India |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"earlyyears\" /> Nigam has released pop albums in Hindi, Kannada, Odia, Chhattisgarhi and Punjabi, as well as [[Hindu]] and Islamic devotional albums. He has released several Buddhist albums. Nigam has performed in countries in North America, Europe, the Middle East, Africa, Asia and Australia. In May\u2013June 2007, he participated in The Incredibles tour with [[Asha Bhosle]], [[Kunal Ganjawala]], and [[Kailash Kher]]. In September\u2013October of the same year, he gave solo concerts titled Simply Sonu in Canada and Germany, the first Indian singer to do so.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sonu Nigam's Tour to Germany |url=http://www.glamsham.com/movies/scoops/07/aug/08_sonu_nigams_tour_to_germany_080701.asp |accessdate=25 July 2008}}</ref> In April 2008, he toured India promoting his Punjabi single \"Punjabi Please\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Close-Up and BIG 92.7 FM bring Sonu Nigam's concert |url=http://itvx.net/2008/04/18/close-up-and-big-927-fm-bring-sonu-nigam%E2%80%99s-concert/ |accessdate=25 July 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081230074852/http://itvx.net/2008/04/18/close-up-and-big-927-fm-bring-sonu-nigam%E2%80%99s-concert/ |archivedate=30 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nNigam's first film song as a playback singer was for ''Janam'' (1990), which was never officially released. He then began making radio commercials and also acted in some of them.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nHis first released song was \"O Aasman Wale\" from the movie ''[[Aaja Meri Jaan]]'' (1992). Sonu had also sung the title track of Aaja Meri Jaan, but it was dubbed by SP Balasubramaniam. He released his first album \"Rafi Ki Yaadein\" in 1992. After this, he sung in some movies, including  ''[[Muqabla (1993 film)|Muqabla]]'' (1993),  ''[[Meherbaan|Meherban]]'' (1993),  ''[[Shabnam]]'' (1993), ''[[Kasam Teri Kasam]]'' (1993), ''[[Aag (1994 film)|Aag]]'' (1994),  ''[[Khuddar]]'' (1994),  ''[[Hulchul (1995 film)|Hulchul]]'' (1994),   ''[[Stuntman (film)|Stuntman]]'' (1994), ''[[Ram Jaane|Ramjaane]]'' (1995),  ''[[Gaddaar (1995 film)|Gaddaar]]'' (1995), ''[[Jeet (1996 film)|Jeet]]'' (1996) etc. Sonu Nigam was supposed to playback the song \"Ek Ladki Ko Dekha Toh\" from ''[[1942: A Love Story]]'' and Sonu was the first choice of R.D. Burman for this song, but the song was eventually recorded by Kumar Sanu. He began hosting the TV show, ''[[Sa Re Ga Ma]]'' in 1995 and sang \"Accha Sila Diya\" for the film ''[[Bewafa Sanam]]'' and achieved great success because of it. In the same year,<ref name=\"earlyyears\" /> he sang the [[Anu Malik]]-composed song \"[[Sandese Aate Hai]]\" in ''[[Border (1997 film)|Border]]'' and performed the [[Nadeem-Shravan]]-composed song \"Yeh Dil Deewana\" in ''[[Pardes (film)|Pardes]]'' in 1997, which took him out from his stereotyped image of singing. Nigam's album ''[[Deewana (album)|Deewana]]'', with music directed by [[Sajid-Wajid]], was released by T-Series in 1999 and is one of the most selling and celebrated albums till date.<ref name=\"earlyyears\" />\n\nNigam provided playback singing for Hindi movies, including the title song for the film ''[[Kal Ho Naa Ho]]'' in 2003 to \"[[Abhi Mujh Mein Kahin]]\"  for ''[[Agneepath (2012 film)|Agneepath]]'' in 2012 and many more.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}. However, from the past few years, he has gone selective about his songs so that he can focus more on creative works. His upcoming project with [[Bickram Ghosh]] named \"Bollywood Retro\" is one such project.\n\nHe composed the title track of the film ''[[Singh Saab The Great]]'' in 2013 and has also composed music for other films including: ''[[Sooper Se Ooper]]'' and ''[[Jal (film)|Jal]]'', in collaboration with percussionist [[Bickram Ghosh]] in the same year.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\nNigam has released albums of [[Mohammed Rafi]]'s songs including ''Rafi Ki Yaadein'', a collection early in his career, which was re-released in Rafi's memory in September 2007 as a six-disc collection of 100 songs, titled ''Kal Aaj Aur Kal''.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=www.indiaglitz.com |title=Sonu Nigam pays homage to Mohd Rafi |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/hindi/article/33495.html |accessdate=25 July 2008}}</ref> In 2008, soon after releasing ''Classically Mild'', he released a single Punjabi track entitled \"Punjabi Please\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Big FM launches Sonu Niigaam single Punjabi Please |url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k8/mar/mar34.php |accessdate=25 July 2008|date=3 March 2008 }}</ref> and ''Rafi Resurrected'', a two-disc collection of Rafi songs with music by the [[City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra|Birmingham Symphony Orchestra]]. He contributed to the lyrics of several songs and directed the music for his album ''[[Chanda Ki Doli]]''.\n\nSonu has always been loved and respected by the Bollywood industry. Among the new generation of singers, [[Lata Mangeshkar]] loves Sonu the most.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/mar/04sd4.htm|title=rediff.com: Why Lata Mangeshkar likes Sonu Nigam|website=www.rediff.com|accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref> [[Shah Rukh Khan]] has been always seen heaping praises on Sonu whom he considers as an true artiste.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K88t35OVcXc|title=An emotional tribute to Javed Akhtar from Sonu Nigam at the 7th Royal Stag Mirchi Music Awards|accessdate=23 December 2019|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-4Cf9Yivk_Q|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com|accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref> [[Shankar Mahadevan]] considers Sonu Nigam as his favourite singer in recent times.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://sonuniigaamandme.blogspot.in/2012/02/sonu-nigam-is-shankar-mahadevans-ideal.html | title=Sonu Nigam & Me: Sonu Nigam is Shankar Mahadevan's Ideal Singer| date=2 February 2012}}</ref> Music director [[Himesh Reshammiya]] also believes that Sonu is the best singer in the industry.<ref>http://www.bollywood.com/i-think-sonu-nigam-best-singer-india-himesh-reshammiya</ref> Filmmaker [[Shirish Kunder]] is full of praises for Sonu.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.lyricsmint.com/2010/10/shirish-kunder-cant-stop-praising-sonu.html |title = Shirish Kunder can't stop praising Sonu Nigam, He has sung in 54 different voices}}</ref> Shekhar of [[Vishal-Shekhar]] duo considered him as the finest live performer. Even [[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]] who is one of his contemporaries admiring him from a long time. Singing sensation [[Armaan Malik]] idolises Sonu Nigam as his God and Guru draws a lot of inspiration from him.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/living-his-dream/article19209189.ece |title = Armaan Malik, living his dream|newspaper = The Hindu|date = 4 July 2017|last1 = Walia|first1 = Gahna}}</ref>\n\nAfter the death of [[Michael Jackson]],  Nigam released a song as a tribute to Jackson which was included on the tribute album ''The Beat of Our Hearts''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Michael Jackson Trubute portrait |url=http://michaeljacksontributeportrait.com/article.php?article_id=232 |accessdate=15 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2007, at the inauguration of [[Harvard University|Harvard]] University's 28th president, [[Drew Gilpin Faust]], Nigam sang [[Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi|Mahatma Gandhi]]'s favourite [[bhajan]], \"Vaishnav Jan To Tene Kahiye\", with the Harvard College Sangeet.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sonu Nigam invited to perform at Harvard University |url=http://www.glamsham.com/movies/scoops/07/oct/06_sonu_nigam_100704.asp |accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2008, he participated in a three-city tour of the United Kingdom, singing Rafi songs with the City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra (CBSO) . This followed the release of these songs by the CBSO and the Indian music company [[Sa Re Ga Ma]] on ''Rafi Resurrected''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sonu Nigam's new album 'Rafi Resurrected' in July this year |url=http://news.oneindia.in/2007/04/19/sonu-nigams-new-album-rafi-resurrected-in-july-this-year-1176955506.html |accessdate=25 July 2008|date=19 April 2007 }}</ref>\n\nHe participated in a US tour with [[Sunidhi Chauhan]] in 2009 called The Explosion 2009 tour and in a [[United Kingdom|UK]] tour titled ''All Izz Well'' in November 2010. In 2011, Nigam collaborated with Kakas Entertainment and [[Laxmikant-Pyarelal]] for a Maestros Concert performing Mohammed Rafi songs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/top-singers-100-musicians-at-laxmikantpyarelal-concert/789055/ |title=Top singers, 100 musicians at Laxmikant-Pyarelal concert |publisher=Indian Express |date=12 May 2011 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Nigam collaborated with [[Britney Spears]] on a remix of her \"[[I Wanna Go]]\" track,<ref>{{cite web |title=Sonu Nigam and Britney Spears to sing together |url=http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2011/jul/140711-informer-1.htm |publisher=mid-day.com |accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref><ref>*[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-07-14/news-and-interviews/29772881_1_sonu-nigam-britney-spears-baby-one-more-time Sonu Nigam collaborates with Britney Spears]</ref> and with DJ [[Avicii]] on his song \"Indian Levels\", produced by Avicii in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Why-the-Sonu-Nigam-Avicii-track-took-a-year/articleshow/17518336.cms |title=Why the Sonu Nigam-Avicii track took a year! |publisher=The Times of India |date=7 December 2012 |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was ranked the Number 1 artist on the US Billboard Uncharted charts twice in September and October 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-09-07/uncharted |title=Uncharted : Sep 07, 2013 &#124; Billboard Chart Archive |publisher=Billboard.com |date=7 September 2013 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-10-05/uncharted |title=Uncharted : Oct 05, 2013 &#124; Billboard Chart Archive |publisher=Billboard.com |date=5 October 2013 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Nigam recorded a song with the music director [[Khayyam]] for the upcoming project titled ''Gulam Bandhu''.<ref name=\"Indian Express\">{{cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/music/words-not-enough-to-praise-sonu-nigam-khayyam/ |title=Words not enough to praise Sonu Nigam: Khayyam |publisher=Indian Express |date=1 September 2011 |accessdate=31 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Work in Kannada==\n[[File:Sonu Nigam122.jpg|thumb|upright=2.2|left|alt=Sonu Nigam singing in the concert|Nigam performing at the live concert in 2014]]\nNigam's first song in [[Kannada]] was in 1996 for the film ''[[Jeevanadhi]]''. The song \"Yello Yaro Hego\" was composed by [[Saluri Koteswara Rao]] with lyrics by [[R. N. Jayagopal]]. Nigam has since sung over 600 Kannada songs.<ref name=\"deccanherald.com\">{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/233428/pitching-right.html |title=Pitching it right |publisher=Deccanherald.com |date=11 March 2012 |accessdate=9 July 2013}}</ref> He is known as the Golden Singer Of Karnataka.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/kannada/music/The-Golden-Singer-of-Karnataka-Sonu-Nigam-turns-41/articleshow/39295244.cms |title=The Golden Singer of Karnataka, Sonu Nigam, turns 41 \u2013 The Times of India |language=ru |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=30 July 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |author= |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/kannada/movies/news-interviews/Sonu-lauded-for-new-song/articleshow/22325543.cms |title=Sonu lauded for new song&nbsp;\u2014 The Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=5 September 2013 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |last=Andanappa |first=Nagarathna |url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/kannada/news/2013/sonu-nigam-15-best-kannada-songs-birthday-special-115901.html |title=Birthday Boy Sonu Nigam's 15 Best Kannada Songs&nbsp;\u2014 Filmibeat |publisher=Entertainment.oneindia.in |date=30 July 2013 |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nHis songs include \"Cheluve Yeke Bande\", from the film ''Majnu'', composed by [[Gurukiran]]; \"Titanic Heroine Nee Nanna Cheluve\", from the film ''[[Snehaloka]]''; the title track from the film ''[[Monalisa (film)|Monalisa]]'' composed by Valisha Sandeep;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kannadachitraranga.com/sonu-nigam-rocks-in-monalisa-monalisa-sadaa-dhyan/ |title=SONU NIGAM rocks in Monalisa&nbsp;\u2013 Monalisa&nbsp;\u2013 Sadaa ,Dhyan &#124; Kannada songs collection, kannada movie news |publisher=Kannadachitraranga.com |date=24 June 2011 |accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref> \"Hamsave Hamsave\" from the film ''Gatti Mela'', composed by [[Hamsalekha]],  \"Kannale Kannale\" from the film ''[[Aham Premasmi]]'', composed by [[V. Ravichandran|V.Ravichandran]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.movieskope.com/songs/tag/aham-premasmi-kannada-movie-songs-mp3/ |title=Welcome movieskope.com&nbsp;\u2014 BlueHost.com |publisher=Movieskope.com |date= |accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref> and \"Baaninda Baa Chandira, from the movie ''Kanti'', composed by [[Gurukiran]]. The 2006 film ''[[Mungaru Male]]'' created a sensation and spawned several records, mainly in Karnataka.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/kannada/article/35125.html |title='Mungaru Male' National record&nbsp;\u2014 Kannada Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bangalore365.com/actors/mungaru-male-sucessful-365-days/ |title=Mungaru Male&nbsp;\u2013 Successful 365 days !! at Bangalore 365 |publisher=Bangalore365.com |date=6 December 2007 |accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe songs \"Mungaru Maleye\" and \"[[Anisuthide]]\" were composed by [[Mano Murthy]] and written by [[Yogaraj Bhat]] and [[Jayant Kaikini]] respectively. Nigam has said that he finds Kannada songs more fulfilling than the Hindi numbers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/news-topic/zee-kannada-/video-sonu-finds-kannada-music-fulfilling__IkieBZGaCM.html|title=Sonu Finds Kannada Music Fulfilling|publisher=Moneycontrol.com|date=|accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Deccan Herald]]'' he said \"Kannada songs make me feel positive\".<ref>{{cite web |author=Sudha Hegde |url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/89369/kannada-songs-make-me-feel.html |title='Kannada songs make me feel positive'. |publisher=Deccanherald.com |date=18 August 2010 |accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref> He went on to say: \"I highly respect the musicians of [[Karnataka]] and many of my favourite songs are in Kannada. I consider [[Bangalore]] as my second birthplace. Even if someone requests me to sing a Kannada song while I'm performing in the West Indies, I will sing it for them\".<ref name=\"deccanherald.com\" />\n[[File:Sonu Nigam(1).jpg|thumb|180px|right|Sonu Nigaam during a Peace Rally in [[Mumbai]] on 20 November 2011]]\nFrom the same ''Mungaru Male'' combination, composer Murthy, lyricist Kaikini and Nigam got together to record the Kannada album ''[[Neene Bari Neene]]'', produced by [[Ashok Kheny]]. Videos for the songs \"Neene Bari Neene\" and \"Baa Nodu Gelathi\" were shot on the outskirts of Bangalore featuring Nigam and model [[Madhuri Bhattacharya]] in the lead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Br53jdUFAAY |title=Kannada Sonu Nigam Neene Bari Neene Manomurthy |publisher=YouTube |date=31 August 2009 |accessdate=9 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6U2TkpF_40E |title=Sonu Nigam&nbsp;\u2014 Baa Nodu Gelathi&nbsp;\u2014 Neene Bari Neene (HQ) |publisher=YouTube |date=6 February 2011 |accessdate=9 July 2013}}</ref> Nigam also composed a theme song for the [[Karnataka Bulldozers]] team in the [[Celebrity Cricket League]] and sang it with [[Kunal Ganjawala]] and [[Sowmya Raoh]], who also penned the lyrics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=krDVvYXbR64 |title=Karnataka Bulldozers OFFICIAL THEME SONG [HQ&#93; Celebrity Cricket League |publisher=YouTube |date=12 January 2012 |accessdate=9 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe is called 'The Golden Singer Of Karnataka'.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n==Work as a host and celebrity judge==\nNigam was the host of the ''[[Sa Re Ga Ma]]'' music show from 1995 until 1999 and became household name.<ref name=bbc>{{cite news |title=Does India have the X factor? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-13592636 |accessdate=29 August 2011 |newspaper=BBC News |date=30 May 2011 |author=Rajini Vaidyanathan}}</ref> He returned on ''[[Sa Re Ga Ma Pa L'il Champs International]]'' as a judge with [[Suresh Wadkar]] in October 2007. Nigam was a celebrity judge on the ''[[Sa Re Ga Ma Pa Mega Challenge]]'' grand finale on 12 December 2009 .\n\nNigam hosted the TV show ''Kisme Kitna Hai Dum'' on [[Star Plus]] in 2002. He appeared as the judge on ''[[Indian Idol]]'' in seasons 1 (October 2004&nbsp;\u2013 March 2005) and 2 (November 2005&nbsp;\u2013 April 2006), and was a celebrity judge in seasons 3 (17 August 2007) and 4 (16 January 2009 and 6 February 2009).{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\nIn 2006, Nigam hosted ''Life Ki Dhun with Sonu Nigaam'' on [[Radio City (Indian radio station)|Radiocity 91.1 FM]], interviewing musicians.<ref>{{cite web |title=Life Ki Dhun Sonu Niigaam |url=http://sify.com/radiocity/index.php |accessdate=25 July 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe appeared as a celebrity judge on ''[[ STAR Voice of India]]'' in August 2007 (Season 1) and in December 2008 (Season 2), and on the grand finale of music reality show ''[[Jo Jeeta Wohi Super Star]]'' on 12 July 2008.\n\nNigam was a judge/mentor on ''[[Chhote Ustaad]] \u2013 Do Deshon Ki Ek Awaaz'' (July&nbsp;\u2013 October 2010) with [[Rahat Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan]], and was a judge/mentor on the first season of ''[[X Factor (India)]]'' (29 May&nbsp;\u2013 2 September 2011) along with [[Sanjay Leela Bhansali]] and [[Shreya Ghoshal]].<ref name=bbc />\n\nOn 23 August 2015, he appeared on \"[[The Anupam Kher Show - Kucch Bhi Ho Sakta Hai|The Anupam Kher Show]]\" sharing his life experiences. He has been also one of the three judges of Indian Idol 2016\u201317.\n\n==Film and voice-over acting==\nNigam's acting career<ref>{{cite web |title=Sonu Nigam |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0631415/ |accessdate=25 July 2008}}</ref> started as a child in films including ''[[Betaab]]'' (1983). As an adult, he acted in films such as ''[[Jaani Dushman: Ek Anokhi Kahani]]'', ''[[Kash Aap Hamare Hote]]'' and ''[[Love in Nepal]]''. He has been signed to be in ''Ankhon Ankhon Mein'', about a blind singer.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sonu ready to play blind! |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report_sonu-ready-to-play-blind_1100939 |accessdate=29 August 2011 |newspaper=DNA |date=3 June 2007 |author=Noyon Jyoti Parasara}}</ref> Nigam provided the [[voice-over|voice]] for the lead character, in the Hindi dubbed version of ''[[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]]''.<ref name=disney>{{cite news |title=INDIAN TELEVISION PREMIER OF DISNEY'S ALADDIN |url=http://www.disney.in/corporate/pr_05_feb23.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405231250/http://www.disney.in/corporate/pr_05_feb23.htm |archivedate=5 April 2012  }}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honours ==\n[[File:The President Dr. A.P.J. Abdul Kalam presenting the Best Male Playback Singer Award for the year 2004 to Shri Sonu Nigam at the 51st National Film Award function in New Delhi on February 2, 2005.jpg|thumb|250px|Nigam (''right'') receiving the National Film Award for Best Male Playback Singer from President [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam]] (''left''), 2005.]]\nSonu Nigam is the winner of several awards including 1 [[National Award]], 2 [[Filmfare Awards]] in Hindi & 3 [[Filmfare Awards South]].\n*'''2017'''  Haryana Gaurav Samman by Haryana Government, Government of India<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/music/sonu-nigam-honored-with-haryana-gaurav-samman-by-haryana-government/articleshow/56622768.cms|title=Sonu Nigam honored with Haryana Gaurav Samman by Haryana government - Mumbai Mirror -|work=Mumbai Mirror|access-date=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n*'''[[9th Mirchi Music Awards|2016]]'''   [[Mirchi Music Awards]] for Indie Pop Song of the Year for \"Aye Jahaan Aasmaan\"\n*'''2016'''   Lions Gold Award for Favorite Evergreen Singer jal best\n*'''2015'''  Oscar 2015 nomination list \"Jal\" Sonu Nigam and Bickram Ghosh for their rustic compositions for the drama f ilm\n*'''2015'''   Socialathon Person of the Year\n*'''2014'''   MMASouth Best Male Vocalist Kannada\n*'''2013'''   MTV Video and Music Award 2013 for Best Male Vocalist for Abhi Mujhme Kahin\n*''' 2014'''  MMASouth Best Male Vocalist Kannada<ref>{{Citation |title=#MMASouth Best Male Vocalist Sonu Nigam Kannada Songs specially for Bangalore |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eCYeN1jIuvI |date=18 August 2014 |accessdate=30 January 2016 |last=mirchikannada}}</ref>\n*'''2013'''   Zee Cinema Award for Best Male Playback Singer for Abhi Mujhme Kahin from the film Agneepath\n*'''2013'''   Big Star Entertainment Award for Best Male Playback Singer for Abhi Mujhme Kahin from the film Agneepath\n*'''[[5th Mirchi Music Awards|2012]]'''   Royal Stag [[Mirchi Music Award for Male Vocalist of The Year]] for the song \"Abhi Mujhme Kahin\" from the film Agneepath\n* '''2012\u20132013''' [[Filmfare Awards South]] \u2013 Best Playback Singer Male for the song  \"Chendutiya Pakkadali\" from the movie ''[[Drama (2012 film)|Drama]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/kannada/news-interviews/Bangalore-Times-Film-Awards-2012-goes-to--/articleshow/21893862.cms |work=The Times Of India |title=Bangalore Times Film Awards 2012 goes to... - The Times of India}}</ref>\n*'''2012'''   Lions Gold Award for Favorite Evergreen Singer\n*'''2012'''   GIMA for Best Global Indian Collaboration \u2013 This Is It ft Jermaine Jackson *2011 GIMA(Global Indian Music Award)for MTV Youth Icon.\n*'''2011'''   Gitanjali WoW Award for Live Personality(Music).\n*'''2010''' \u2013 Global Indian Music Award for Best Live Performer (Male)<ref>{{cite news |title=Global Indian Television Awards |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/3-Idiots-wins-five-music-awards/articleshow/6907429.cms |accessdate=16 November 2010 |work=The Times Of India |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101115044219/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/3-Idiots-wins-five-music-awards/articleshow/6907429.cms |archivedate=15 November 2010}}</ref>\n*'''2010'''   GIMA(Global Indian Music Award) for Best Live Performer Male.\n*'''2010'''   GIMA(Global Indian Music Award) for Most Popular Song \u2013 All Izz Well.\n*'''2010'''   Amar Rishtey Award for Zee Icoon\u2013 TVS Sa Re Ga Ma.\n*'''2010'''   Big Star Entertainment Award for Singer of the Decade.\n*'''2009'''   Indian Television Academy Award, Best Male Singer for Dil Mill Gaye title track.\n*'''2009'''  Filmfare Award, Kannada, Best Male Playback Singer for Yenagali, Mussanje Maathu\n*'''2008'''  GPBA (German Public Bollywood Award), Best Singer (Male) for Main Agar Kahoon, Om Shanti Om.\n*'''2008''' Filmfare Award, Kannada, Best Male Playback Singer for Ninnindale, Milana.\n*'''2008'''  Indian Television Academy Award, Best Male Singer for Amber Dhara title track\n*'''2008''' Lions Gold Award for the song 'In lamhon ke Daaman me' from the film 'Jodha Akbar'.\n*'''2007''' Annual Central European Bollywood Awards, Best Male Playback Singer for Mein Agar Kahoon, Om Shanti Om.\n*'''2006''' Bollywood Music and Fashion Awards, Best Male Playback Singer for Kabhi Alvida Na Kehna, Title Track.\n*'''2005''' Indian Television Award Best Singer for Miliee Title Track.\n*'''2005'''  MTV Immies \u2013 Best Pop Album, for his self-composed album titled \"Chanda Ki Doli\".\n*'''2005''' Swaralaya Yesudas Award, for his outstanding performance in Music.\n*'''2005'''  Anadolok Award for \"Chanda Ki Doli\" album.\n*'''2005''' Lion Gold's Award for the song Main Hoon Na from the film \"Main Hoon Na\".\n*'''2005''' Star Screen Award Best Male Playback, for the song \"Dheere Jalna\", from the film \"Paheli\".\n*'''2005''' Teachers' Achievement Award\n*'''2005''' Style Icon, MTV Style Awards.\n*'''2004'''  MTV Style Awards\u2013 Best Male Playback Singer \u2013 [[Bandhan (2004 film)|Bandhan]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1051222/asp/calcutta/story_5632210.asp |title=Anandalok Awards 2004 |location=Calcutta, India |work=The Telegraph |date=22 December 2005}}</ref>\n*'''2004'''   MTV Immies \u2013 Best Male Singer, for the song \"Main Hoon Na\", from the film \"Main Hoon Na\".\n*'''2004''' National Film Award for Best Male Playback Singer, for the song \"Kal Ho Naa Ho\", from the film Kal Ho Naa Ho.\n*'''[[51st National Film Awards|2003]]''' [[National Film Award for Best Male Playback Singer]]: ''[[Kal Ho Na Ho]]'' for \"Kal Ho Naa Ho\"<ref name=\"51stawardPDF\">{{cite web |url=http://dff.nic.in/2011/51st_nff_2004.pdf |title=51st National Film Awards |publisher=[[Directorate of Film Festivals]] |accessdate=14 August 2015 }}</ref>\n*'''2003''' Apsara Film Producers' Guild Award for Best Male Playback Singer for \"Kal Ho Na Ho\" from the film Kal Ho Naa Ho.\n*'''2003''' Bollywood Music Award for Best Male Playback Singer for \"Kal Ho Na Ho\" from the film Kal Ho Naa Ho.\n*'''2003'''  IIFA Best Male Playback Award, for the song \"Kal Ho Naa Ho\", from the film Kal Ho Na Ho\n*'''2003''' Style Icon, MTV Style Awards.\n*'''2003'''  Filmfare Best Male Playback Award, for the song \"Kal Ho Naa Ho\", from the film Kal Ho Naa Ho\".\n*'''2002''' Filmfare Best Male Playback Award, for the song \"Saathiya\", from the f ilm Saathiya.\n*'''2002''' Bollywood Music Award for Best Male Playback Singer for the song \"Saathiya\" from the film \"Saathiya\".\n*'''2002'''  MTV Immies \u2013 Best Male Singer, for the song \"Saathiya\" from the film \"Saathiya\".\n*'''2002''' Zee Cine Award Best Playback Singer- Male, for the song \"Saathiya\", from the film \"Saathiya\".\n*'''2002'''  IIFA Best Male Playback Award, for the song \"Saathiya\", from the film \"Saathiya\".\n*'''2001'''  Star Screen Award Best Male Playback, for the song \"Tanhayee\", from the film \"Dil Chahta Hai\". *'''2001''' Bollywood Music Award for Best Pop Singer for the album \"Yaad\".\n*'''2001'''  IIFA Best Male Playback Award, for the song \"Suraj Hua Maddham\", from the f ilm \"Kabhi Khushi Kabhie Gham\".\n*'''2001''' Zee Cine Award Best Playback Singer<ref>{{Cite web |title=Sonu Nigam |url=http://sonunigam.in/awards.php |website=sonunigam.in |access-date=29 January 2016}}</ref>- Male, for the song \"Suraj Hua Maddham\", from the film \"Kabhi Khushi Kabhie Gham\".\n*'''1998''' Screen Award for Best Male Pop Artist for ''Kismat''<ref>{{cite web |title=Award Winners |url=http://www.expressindia.com/screen/awards/eve.htm |website=[[Screen (magazine)|Screen]] |accessdate=2 October 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19991022044355/http://www.expressindia.com/screen/awards/eve.htm |archivedate=22 October 1999}}</ref>\n*'''1997''' Sansui Viewers' Choice Award for Best Male Singer for the song \"Sandese Aate Hai\", from the film \"Border\".\n*'''1997''' Aashirwad Award for Best Male Singer for the song \"Sandese Aate Hai\", from the film \"Border\".\n*'''1997''' Zee Cine Award Best Playback Singer- Male, for the song \"Sandese Aate Hai\", from the film \"Border\".\n\n==Filmography as composer==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Film\n|-\n| 2013 ||[[Sooper Se Ooper]]\n|-\n| 2016 || Crazy Dil\n|-\n| 2015 || The Music Room\n|-\n| 2014 || [[Jal (film)|Jal]]\n|-\n| 2013 || [[Singh Saab The Great]]\n|}\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Sonu Nigam discography}}\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Film !! Character !! Year\n|-\n| ''[[Kaamchor]]'' || Sonu || 1982\n|-\n| ''[[Ustadi Ustad Se]]'' || Young Raju || 1982\n|-\n| ''[[Betaab]]'' || Young Sunny || 1983\n|-\n| ''[[Hum Se Hai Zamana]]'' || Young Shiva || 1983\n|-\n| ''[[Taqdeer (1983 film)|Taqdeer]]'' || Young Shiva || 1983\n|-\n| ''[[Krishna Krishna]]'' || Sudhama  || 1986\n|-\n| ''[[Pyaara Dushman]]'' || Manish Khadnya  || 1985\n|-\n| ''[[Jaani Dushman: Ek Anokhi Kahani]]'' || Vivek Saxena || 2002\n|-\n| ''[[Kash Aap Hamare Hote]]'' || Jai Kumar || 2003\n|-\n| ''[[Love in Nepal]]'' || Abby || 2004\n|-\n| ''[[Navra Maza Navsacha]]'' || Guest appearance as himself in a song sequence || 2005\n|-\n| ''[[Warning (2013 film)|Warning]]'' || Guest appearance as himself in \"Takeedein\" song sequence || 2013\n|}\n\n==Dubbing roles==\n===Animated films===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Film title !! Original Voice !! Character !! Dub Language !! Original Language !! Original Release !! Dub Release !! Notes\n|-\n| [[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.disney.in/corporate/pr_05_feb23.htm |title=The Walt Disney Company |publisher=Disney.in |date=23 February 2005 |accessdate=14 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405231250/http://www.disney.in/corporate/pr_05_feb23.htm |archivedate=5 April 2012  }}</ref> || [[Scott Weinger]] <br />(Speaking)<br> [[Brad Kane]] <small>(Singing)</small> || [[Aladdin (Disney character)|Aladdin]] <br>(Speaking and Singing) || Hindi || English || 1992 || 1994 || Gave both the Hindi Speaking and Singing voice to Aladdin in this film. <br>Dubbed by Modi Entertainment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.animationxpress.com/index.php/interviews/the-art-of-directing-dubs-a-chat-with-ellie-lewis |title=The art of directing dubs: A chat with Ellie Lewis \u2013 Animation Xpress |publisher=animationxpress.com |date=26 October 2004 |accessdate=20 July 2015}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Controversies==\nHis tweets against making the [[Azaan]] (Muslim call for prayer) through loudspeakers had landed him in controversy. In his tweet he stated that [[Azaan]] through loudspeakers disturbs his sleep.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/sonu-nigam-on-azaan-row-i-stand-by-my-statement/articleshow/58238260.cms|title=Sonu Nigam on Azaan row: I stand by my statement - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=18 April 2017}}</ref> He later clarified that he is not against any specific religious ritual, but against the use of loudspeakers on religious buildings. He clarified that noise pollution should be stopped, irrespective of whether it is from a temple or a mosque.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/music/sonu-nigam-tweets-more-clarification-mentioned-temples-gurudwaras-too/story-o2aWLK29RVvamFqCKNXYeN.html|title=Sonu Nigam tweets more clarification: Mentioned temples, gurudwaras too|date=19 April 2017|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=19 April 2017|language=en}}</ref> Later, Nigam again sparked controversy, when he posted a video of Azaan from his home which proved that he was indeed disturbed very early in the morning.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/music/sonu-nigam-posts-video-of-azaan-from-his-home-sparks-controversy-yet-again/story-kG5eXYQIPAVFwqHU72CuUI.html|title=Sonu Nigam posts video of azaan from his home, sparks controversy yet again|work=Hindustan Times|date=27 April 2017|access-date=23 April 2017|language=en}}</ref> Syed Sha Atef Ali Al Quaderi, vice-president of [[West Bengal United Minority Council]] announced a reward of \u20b910 Lakh to anyone who shaved Nigam's head, to which Sonu Nigam responded by shaving his own head to claim the reward.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/cities/rs-10-lakh-to-shave-sonu-nigam-bengal-fatwa-imam-says-it-s-not-a-fatwa/story-4mGXNnt8P2bS99tAaZUttJ.html|title=Rs 10 lakh to shave Sonu Nigam; Bengal \"fatwa imam\" says it's not a fatwa|date=19 April 2017|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=26 May 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nNigam has deleted his [[Twitter]] account on 24 May 2017, citing a lack of respect for [[freedom of speech]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/music/sonu-nigam-is-quitting-twitter-rants-at-length-in-support-of-paresh-rawal-abhijeet/story-RmgVo1kjmHonK1hozUUOKL.html|title=Sonu Nigam quits Twitter, rants at length in support of Paresh Rawal, Abhijeet|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Indian playback singers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Facebook | id= SonuNigamSpace| name= Sonu Nigam}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0631415}}\n\n{{National Film Award Best Male Playback Singer}}\n{{FilmfareAwardBestMaleSinger}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nigam, Sonu}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian male film singers]]\n[[Category:Bollywood playback singers]]\n[[Category:Assamese playback singers]]\n[[Category:Bengali playback singers]]\n[[Category:Kannada playback singers]]\n[[Category:Marathi playback singers]]\n[[Category:Nepali-language singers]]\n[[Category:Odia Playback Singers]]\n[[Category:Punjabi-language singers]]\n[[Category:Tamil playback singers]]\n[[Category:Telugu playback singers]]\n[[Category:Indian film score composers]]\n[[Category:Indian male pop singers]]\n[[Category:Indian television presenters]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Indian male child actors]]\n[[Category:Indian male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Performers of Hindu music]]\n[[Category:People from Faridabad]]\n[[Category:Sa Re Ga Ma Pa participants]]\n[[Category:Filmfare Awards South winners]]\n[[Category:Zee Cine Awards winners]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Singers from Haryana]]\n[[Category:Indian pop-folk singers]]\n[[Category:Pop rock singers]]\n[[Category:Best Male Playback Singer National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Male film score composers]]\n[[Category:Actors from Mumbai]]\n", "name_user": "AS221210000", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonu_Nigam"}
{"title_page": "Elyton", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2020}}\n{{US Census population\n|1880= 700\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=<ref>{{cite web |title=U.S. Decennial Census|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html |publisher=census.gov |accessdate=June 6, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YSasqtfX?url=http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html |archivedate=May 12, 2015 }}</ref>\n}}\n'''Elyton (Ely's Town)''', [[Alabama]],<ref>{{cite book|author=Alabama|title=A Digest of the Laws of the State of Alabama: Containing the Statutes and Resolutions in Force at the End of the General Assembly in January, 1823. To which is Added, an Appendix; Containing the Declaration of Independence; the Constitution of the United States; the Act Authorizing the People of Alabama to Form a Constitution and State Government; and the Constitution of the State of Alabama|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_JvtKAAAAYAAJ|year=1828|publisher=Ginn & Curtis, J. & J. Harper, Printers, New-York|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_JvtKAAAAYAAJ/page/n865 834]}}</ref> was the county seat of [[Jefferson County, Alabama]] from 1821 to 1873. It was the county's second seat, after Carrollsville (1819-1821) (now the Birmingham neighborhood of [[List of neighborhoods in Birmingham, Alabama|Powderly]]).<ref name=encyc>{{cite web|title=Jefferson County|url=http://www.encyclopediaofalabama.org/article/h-1370|publisher=[[Encyclopedia of Alabama]]|access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In 1873 the courthouse was moved to  [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]].<ref name=encyc/> The area that was Elyton is currently bordered by 7th Street Southwest and Cotton Avenue in the [[List of neighborhoods in Birmingham, Alabama|West End]] of Birmingham.<ref>{{cite gnis|151729|Elyton, Alabama}}</ref>\n\nElyton was incorporated as a town December 20, 1820. It was created to be the county seat with a {{convert|160|acre|km2|adj=on}} grant negotiated by federal land agent William Ely, of Connecticut. The new town was named in his honor. The site was previously called Frog Level, and was known primarily as a sporting grounds for horse races.<ref>{{cite book|author=Moss, Florence Hawkins Wood|title=Building Birmingham and Jefferson County|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uC9UAAAAYAAJ|year=1947|publisher=Birmingham Printing Company|pages=14, 66}}</ref> \n\nIn 1821 Elyton had 300 residents, and grew to over 1,000 by 1873. Elyton was listed on the 1880 U.S. Census as having a population of 700.<ref>{{cite web|title=Population of Civil Divisions Less than Counties, in the Aggregate, at the Censuses of 1880 and 1870|url=http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/1880a_v1-09.pdf|publisher=census.gov}}</ref> During this time Elyton was an important community in middle Alabama. It was the residence of  U.S. Representative [[Thomas Haughey]] (1868-69) and the headquarters of the Elyton [[Presbyterian polity#Presbytery|Presbytery]] (formed in 1832).<ref>{{cite web|title=The History of the Cumberland Presbyterian Church in Alabama prior to 1826|url=http://www.alabamapioneers.com/presbyterian-10167/|author=Hall, James H.B.|publisher=Alabama Pioneers}}</ref>\n\nIn 1853 merchant John Cantley established the ''Elyton Herald'' after purchasing the Washington hand press and type from Moses Lancaster after his newspaper, the ''Central Alabamian,'' ceased publication.<ref>https://www.archive.org/stream/jeffersoncountyb00dubo#page/196/mode/2up/search/elyton+herald</ref> After many ownerships, mergers and name changes the paper became the ''[[Birmingham Post-Herald]]'' in 1950.\n\nThe community was incorporated as a municipality in 1907, but was annexed into Birmingham as part of the Greater Birmingham legislation which took effect on January 1, 1910. Frank W. Smith was the first and only mayor of Elyton. The Board of Aldermen was composed of Ollis Brown, Van Smith, C. M. Bitz, T. T. Alley, and W. M. Marriner. \n\nThe name is still preserved in an elementary school and a food market in the area.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} It is still used in news reports to refer to this area of Birmingham.<ref>{{cite news|title=Birmingham police investigate Elyton shooting|url=http://www.foxalabamanews.com/2009/11/birmingham-police-investigate-elyton.html|date=November 4, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100109180056/http://www.foxalabamanews.com/2009/11/birmingham-police-investigate-elyton.html|archive-date=January 9, 2010|publisher=[[Fox News]]}}</ref>{{better source needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Coord|33.5014|-86.8407|display=title}}\n{{Jefferson County, Alabama}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1820]]\n[[Category:1910 disestablishments]]\n[[Category:Geography of Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Former municipalities in Alabama]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2020}}\n{{US Census population\n|1880= 700\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=<ref>{{cite web |title=U.S. Decennial Census|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html |publisher=census.gov |accessdate=June 6, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6YSasqtfX?url=http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html |archivedate=May 12, 2015 }}</ref>\n}}\n'''Elyton (Ely's Town)''', [[Alabama]],<ref>{{cite book|author=Alabama|title=A Digest of the Laws of the State of Alabama: Containing the Statutes and Resolutions in Force at the End of the General Assembly in January, 1823. To which is Added, an Appendix; Containing the Declaration of Independence; the Constitution of the United States; the Act Authorizing the People of Alabama to Form a Constitution and State Government; and the Constitution of the State of Alabama|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_JvtKAAAAYAAJ|year=1828|publisher=Ginn & Curtis, J. & J. Harper, Printers, New-York|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_JvtKAAAAYAAJ/page/n865 834]}}</ref> was the county seat of [[Jefferson County, Alabama]] from 1821 to 1873. It was the county's second seat, after Carrollsville (1819-1821) (now the Birmingham neighborhood of [[List of neighborhoods in Birmingham, Alabama|Powderly]]).<ref name=encyc>{{cite web|title=Jefferson County|url=http://www.encyclopediaofalabama.org/article/h-1370|publisher=[[Encyclopedia of Alabama]]|access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In 1873 the courthouse was moved to  [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]].<ref name=encyc/> The area that was Elyton is currently bordered by 7th Street Southwest and Cotton Avenue in the [[List of neighborhoods in Birmingham, Alabama|West End]] of Birmingham.<ref>{{cite gnis|151729|Elyton, Alabama}}</ref>\n\nElyton was incorporated as a town December 20, 1820. It was created to be the county seat with a {{convert|160|acre|km2|adj=on}} grant negotiated by federal land agent William Ely, of Connecticut. The new town was named in his honor. The site was previously called Frog Level, and was known primarily as a sporting grounds for horse races.<ref>{{cite book|author=Moss, Florence Hawkins Wood|title=Building Birmingham and Jefferson County|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uC9UAAAAYAAJ|year=1947|publisher=Birmingham Printing Company|pages=14, 66}}</ref> \n\nIn 1821 Elyton had 300 residents, and grew to over 1,000 by 1873. Elyton was listed on the 1880 U.S. Census as having a population of 700.<ref>{{cite web|title=Population of Civil Divisions Less than Counties, in the Aggregate, at the Censuses of 1880 and 1870|url=http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/1880a_v1-09.pdf|publisher=census.gov}}</ref> During this time Elyton was an important community in middle Alabama. It was the residence of  U.S. Representative [[Thomas Haughey]] (1868-69) and the headquarters of the Elyton [[Presbyterian polity#Presbytery|Presbytery]] (formed in 1832).<ref>{{cite web|title=The History of the Cumberland Presbyterian Church in Alabama prior to 1826|url=http://www.alabamapioneers.com/presbyterian-10167/|author=Hall, James H.B.|publisher=Alabama Pioneers}}</ref>\n\nIn 1850 merchant John Cantley established the ''Elyton Herald'', Jefferson County's first newspaper. After many ownerships, mergers and name changes the paper became the ''[[Birmingham Post-Herald]]'' in 1950.\n\nThe community was incorporated as a municipality in 1907, but was annexed into Birmingham as part of the Greater Birmingham legislation which took effect on January 1, 1910. Frank W. Smith was the first and only mayor of Elyton. The Board of Aldermen was composed of Ollis Brown, Van Smith, C. M. Bitz, T. T. Alley, and W. M. Marriner. \n\nThe name is still preserved in an elementary school and a food market in the area.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} It is still used in news reports to refer to this area of Birmingham.<ref>{{cite news|title=Birmingham police investigate Elyton shooting|url=http://www.foxalabamanews.com/2009/11/birmingham-police-investigate-elyton.html|date=November 4, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100109180056/http://www.foxalabamanews.com/2009/11/birmingham-police-investigate-elyton.html|archive-date=January 9, 2010|publisher=[[Fox News]]}}</ref>{{better source needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Coord|33.5014|-86.8407|display=title}}\n{{Jefferson County, Alabama}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1820]]\n[[Category:1910 disestablishments]]\n[[Category:Geography of Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Former municipalities in Alabama]]\n", "name_user": "Anarchivist17", "label": "safe", "comment": "The Elyton Herald was not Jefferson County's first newspaper, it was technically The Jones Valley Times, also published in Elyton.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elyton"}
{"title_page": "The Holocaust in Slovakia", "text_new": "{{short description|Systematic dispossession, deportation, and murder of Jews in the Slovak State}}\n{{good article}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n[[File:\"Nebu\u010f slu\u017eobn\u00edkom \u017eida\"\u2014Slovak propaganda poster.jpg|thumb|alt=Man kissing feet of another man with hooked nose, dropping money on his head|A Slovak propaganda poster exhorts readers not to \"be a servant to the Jew\".|upright=1.2]]\n{{The Holocaust sidebar}}\n'''The Holocaust in Slovakia''' was the systematic dispossession, deportation, and murder of Jews in the [[Slovak State]], a [[client state]] of [[Nazi Germany]], during [[World War II]]. Out of 89,000  [[Slovak Jews|Jews]] in the country in 1940, around 69,000 were murdered in the [[Holocaust]].\n\nIn 1938, Slovakia lost significant territory to Hungary in the [[First Vienna Award]]; the following year, the ruling [[ethnonationalist]] [[Slovak People's Party]] declared independence from [[Second Czechoslovak Republic|Czechoslovakia]] with German protection. State propaganda blamed the Jews for the territorial losses. Jews were targeted for discrimination and harassment, including the [[Aryanization in Slovakia|confiscation of property and businesses]]. The exclusion of Jews from the economy impoverished the community, which encouraged the government to conscript them for forced labor. \n\nIn 1941, the Slovak government negotiated with Nazi Germany for the mass deportation of Jews to [[German-occupied Poland]]. Between March and October 1942, [[List of Holocaust transports from Slovakia|58,000 Jews were deported]] to [[Auschwitz concentration camp]] and the [[Lublin District]] of the [[General Governorate]] in German-occupied Poland; only a few hundred survived. The Slovak government organized the transports and paid 500 [[Reichsmarks]] per Jew for the supposed cost of resettlement. The persecution of Jews resumed in August 1944, when [[German occupation of Slovakia|Germany invaded Slovakia]] and triggered the [[Slovak National Uprising]]. Another 13,500 Jews were deported and hundreds to thousands were murdered in Slovakia by [[Einsatzgruppe H]] and the [[Hlinka Guard Emergency Divisions]].\n\nSurvivors faced renewed antisemitism and difficulty regaining stolen property; most emigrated after the [[1948 Communist coup]]. The [[Communist Party of Czechoslovakia|postwar Communist regime]] censored discussion of the Holocaust; free speech was restored after the [[Velvet Revolution|fall of the Communist regime]] in 1989. The Slovak government's complicity in the Holocaust remains a source of controversy.\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Background ==\n{{further|History of the Jews in Slovakia}}\n\n[[File:Synagogue Zilina 1931.jpg|thumb|left|alt=modern square building|The [[New Synagogue (\u017dilina)|New Synagogue]] in [[\u017dilina]] shortly after completion, {{circa|1931}}]]\nBefore 1939, Slovakia had never been an independent country. It had been part of the [[Kingdom of Hungary]] for a thousand years; after World War I, it became part of [[First Czechoslovak Republic|Czechoslovakia]].{{sfn|De\u00e1k|2015|p=31}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=18}} Following [[Jewish emancipation]] in 1896, many Jews had adopted Hungarian language and customs in order to advance in society. Many Jews moved to cities and joined the professions; others remained in the countryside, mostly working as artisans, merchants, and shopkeepers.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=18}}{{sfn|Lorman|2019|pp=47\u201348}} Their multilingualism helped them advance in business, but put them in conflict with [[Slovak nationalism]].{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=18}}{{sfn|Lorman|2019|p=48}}{{sfn|L\u00f4n\u010d\u00edkov\u00e1|2017|p=85}} Traditional [[religious antisemitism]] was joined by the stereotypical view of Jews as exploiters of poor Slovaks ([[economic antisemitism]]), and a form of \"national anti-Semitism\" that accused Jews of sympathizing with [[Hungarian irredentism|Hungarian]] and later [[Czechoslovakism|Czechoslovak national aims]].{{sfn|L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek|2013|p=35}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|pp=18\u201319}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|pp=49\u201350}} \n\nIn the 1930s, economic underdevelopment and perceptions of discrimination in Czechoslovakia led a plurality (about one-third) of Slovaks to support the conservative, [[ethnonationalist]] [[Slovak People's Party]] ({{lang-sk|Hlinkova slovensk\u00e1 \u013eudov\u00e1 strana}}: HS\u013dS).{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=842}}{{sfn|Ward|2015|p=79}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2018|p=5}} HS\u013dS viewed minority groups such as Czechs, Hungarians, Jews, and [[Romani people]] as a destructive influence on the Slovak nation,{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1 |2018|p=5}} and presented [[autonomous region|Slovak autonomy]] as the solution to Slovakia's problems.{{sfn|Ward|2015|p=79}} The party began to emphasize antisemitism during the late 1930s following a wave of Jewish refugees from Austria in [[Anschluss|1938]] and anti-Jewish laws passed by Hungary, [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]], and [[Kingdom of Romania|Romania]].{{sfn|Ward|2015|p=87}}\n\n==Slovak independence==\n[[File:Slovakia borderHungary.png|thumb|upright=1.6|alt=Map of Slovakia reflecting southern losses to Hungary|Slovak territorial losses to Hungary in 1938 and 1939]]\n[[File:Slovak Republic 1939 45 Administrative Map.png|thumb|upright=1.6|alt=Color-coded map of the Slovak Republic|Administrative regions of the Slovak State (1939\u20131945)]]\nThe September 1938 [[Munich Agreement]] ceded the [[Sudetenland]], the German-speaking region of the [[Czech lands]], to Germany. HS\u013dS took advantage of the ensuing political chaos to declare Slovakia's autonomy on 6 October 1938. [[Jozef Tiso]], a Catholic priest and HS\u013dS leader, became prime minister of the Slovak autonomous region.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=842}}{{sfn|L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek|2013|pp=16\u201317}} Catholicism, the religion of 80 percent of the country's inhabitants, was key to the regime with many of its leaders being bishops, priests, or laymen.{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|pp=179\u2013180}}{{sfn|Kornberg|2015|pp=81\u201382}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=23}} Under Tiso's leadership, the Slovak government opened [[First Vienna Award#Negotiations in Kom\u00e1rno|negotiations in Kom\u00e1rno]] with Hungary regarding their border. The dispute was submitted to [[First Vienna Award|arbitration in Vienna]] by Nazi Germany and [[Kingdom of Italy under Fascism (1922\u20131943)|Fascist Italy]]. Hungary was awarded much of southern Slovakia on 2 November 1938, including 40 percent of Slovakia's arable land and 270,000 people who had declared Czechoslovak ethnicity.{{sfn|Ward|2013|pp=161, 163, 166}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|pp=842\u2013843}} HS\u013dS consolidated its power by passing an  [[enabling act]], banning opposition parties, shutting down independent newspapers, distributing antisemitic and anti-Czech propaganda, and founding the paramilitary [[Hlinka Guard]].{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=842}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=20}} Parties for the German and Hungarian minorities were allowed under HS\u013dS hegemony, and the [[German Party (Slovakia)|German Party]] formed the {{lang|de|[[Freiwillige Schutzstaffel]]}} militia.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=842}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|pp=20\u201321}} HS\u013dS imprisoned thousands of its political opponents,{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=22}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2012|p=91}} but never carried out an execution.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=9}} [[1938 Slovak parliamentary election|Un-free elections in December 1938]] resulted in a 95-percent vote for HS\u013dS.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=843}}{{sfn|Lorman|2019|p=216}}\n\nOn 14 March 1939, the [[Slovak State]] proclaimed its independence under German protection.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=843}} Germany annexed and invaded the Czech [[rump state]] the following day, and Hungary seized [[Carpathian Ruthenia]] with German acquiescence.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=843}}{{sfn|L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek|2013|pp=16\u201317}} In a [[German-Slovak treaty of 23 March 1939|treaty signed on 23 March]], Slovakia renounced much of its foreign-policy and military autonomy to Germany in exchange for border guarantees and economic assistance.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=843}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=184}} It was neither fully independent nor a German puppet state, but occupied an intermediate status.{{efn|Views differ on this point. [[Istv\u00e1n De\u00e1k]] writes, \"Despite the claims of some historians, [Slovakia] functioned not as a puppet state but as Nazi Germany\u2019s first but not last Slavic-speaking military ally\".{{sfn|De\u00e1k|2015|pp=35\u201336}} [[Tatjana T\u00f6nsmeyer]], who maintains that the puppet-state narrative overstates German influence and understates Slovakia's autonomy, notes that Slovak authorities frequently avoided implementing measures pushed by the Germans when such measures did not suit Slovak priorities. According to German historian Barbara Hutzelmann, \"Although the country was not independent, in the full sense of the word, it would be too simplistic to see this German-protected state ({{lang|de|Schutzstaat}}) simply as a 'puppet regime'.\"{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=168}} [[Ivan Kamenec]], however, emphasizes German influence on Slovak internal and external politics and describes it as a \"German satellite\".{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|pp=180\u2013182}}}}  In October 1939, Tiso, leader of the conservative-[[clericalism|clerical]] branch of HS\u013dS, became president; [[Vojtech Tuka]], leader of the party's radical fascist wing, was appointed prime minister. Both wings of the party struggled for Germany's favor.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=843}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=184}} The radical wing of the party was pro-German, while the conservatives favored autonomy from Germany;{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=203}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=184}}  the radicals relied on the Hlinka Guard and German support,{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=184}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=216}} while Tiso was popular among the clergy and the population.{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|pp=184\u2013185}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|pp=172, 216}}\n{{clear}}\n\n== Anti-Jewish measures (1938\u20131941) ==\n===Overview===\n[[File:Antisemitick\u00e1 Propaganda na Slovensku.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|left|alt=Non-Jewish man kicks a stereotypically dressed Orthodox Jew|Government propaganda ordering Jews to \"Get out of Slovakia!\"]]\nA 1940 census found that 89,000 Jews lived in the Slovak State, 3.4 percent of the population.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}} The largest number of Jews lived in the eastern [[\u0160ari\u0161]]-[[Zempl\u00edn (region)|Zempl\u00edn]] region,{{sfn|Ward|2002|p=584}} and 15,000 lived in [[Bratislava]].{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=65}}{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=17}} Around 5,000 and 6,000 Jews emigrated between 1938 and 1940, and 45,000 lived in the areas ceded to Hungary.{{sfn|Ward|2015|pp=94, 96}}{{sfn|Legge|2018|p=227}} Immediately after it came to power in 1938, the autonomous government began firing Jewish government employees.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=165}} The [[Committee for the Solution of the Jewish Question]] <!-- Komisiu pre rie\u0161enie \u017eidovskej ot\u00e1zky --> was founded on 23 January 1939 to discuss anti-Jewish legislation.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=844}}{{sfn|Hallon|2007|p=149}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=22}}  The state-sponsored media demonized Jews as \"[[enemies of the state]]\" and [[enemy of the people|of the Slovak nation]].{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=844}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=188}}   Jewish businesses were robbed,{{sfn|Legge|2018|p=226}} and physical attacks on Jews occurred both spontaneously and at the instigation of the Hlinka Guard and Freiwillige Schutzstaffel.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1 |2013|pp=551\u2013552}} On his first radio address following the establishment of the Slovak State in 1939, Tiso emphasized his desire to \"solve the [[Jewish Question]]\";{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1 |2018|p=11}} anti-Jewish legislation was the only concrete measure that he promised.{{sfn|Lorman|2019|p=226}}  The persecution of Jews was a key element of the state's domestic policy.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=844}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1 |2018|p=8}} Discriminatory measures affected all aspects of life, to isolate and dispossess Jews before deporting them.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=844}}\n{{clear}}\n=== 1938 deportation and emigration===\n{{main|1938 deportation of Jews from Slovakia}}\nIn the days after the announcement of the [[First Vienna Award]], antisemitic rioting broke out in Bratislava; newspapers justified the riots because of Jews' alleged support for Hungary during the partition negotiations.{{sfn|Ward|2015|p=92}} [[Adolf Eichmann]], a Nazi official who had been sent to Bratislava, coauthored a plan with Tiso and other HS\u013dS politicians to deport impoverished and foreign Jews to the ceded territory.{{sfn|Ward|2015|p=92}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=21}} Meanwhile, Jews with a net worth of over 500,000 [[Czechoslovak koruna]] (K\u010ds) were arrested in an unsuccessful attempt to prevent [[capital flight]].{{sfn|Ward|2015|p=92}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=844}}  Between 4 and 7 November,{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=844}}  4,000{{sfn|Frankl|2019|p=97}} or 7,600 Jews were deported, in a chaotic, [[pogrom]]-like operation in which Hlinka Guard, {{lang|de|Freiwillige Schutzstaffel}}, and the German Party participated.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=21}} The deportees included young children, the elderly, and pregnant women.{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|2014|p=506}} A few days later, Tiso canceled the operation; most of the Jews were allowed to return home in December.{{sfn|Ward|2015|p=93}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=22}} More than 800 were confined to makeshift tent camps at [[Ve\u013ek\u00fd K\u00fdr]], [[Miloslavov]], and [[\u0160amor\u00edn]] on the new Slovak\u2013Hungarian border during the winter.{{sfn|Frankl|2019|pp=103, 112}} The Slovak deportations occurred just after Germany's [[Polenaktion|deportation of thousands of Polish Jews]],{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=21}}{{sfn|Frankl|2019|p=95}} attracted international criticism,{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=844}} reduced British investment, increased dependence on German capital,{{sfn|Ward|2015|p=96}} and were a rehearsal for the 1942 deportations.{{sfn|Johnson|2005|p=316}} \n\n[[File:Temporary Slovak passport issued in 1940 to a Jewish refugee family.jpg|thumb|alt=See caption|Temporary passport issued in 1940 to a Jew who fled to Italy]]\n\nInitially, many Jews believed that the measures taken against them would be temporary.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=26}} Nevertheless, some attempted to emigrate and take their property with them. Between December 1938 and February 1939, more than 2.25 million K\u010ds were transferred illegally to the Czech lands, the Netherlands, and the United Kingdom; additional amounts were transferred legally. Slovak government officials took advantage of the circumstances to purchase the property of wealthy Jewish emigrants at a significant discount, a precursor to the state-sponsored transfer of Jewish property ([[Aryanization]]).{{sfn|Hallon|2007|pp=149\u2013150}} Interest in emigration among  Jews surged after the [[invasion of Poland]], as Jewish refugees from Poland told of atrocities there. Although  the Slovak government  encouraged Jews to emigrate, it refused to allow the export of foreign currency, ensuring that  most attempts remained unsuccessful. No country was eager to accept Jewish refugees, and the [[White Paper of 1939|tight limits]] on legal emigration to [[Mandatory Palestine]] prevented Jews from seeking refuge there. In 1940, Bratislava became a hub for {{lang|he|[[Aliyah Bet]]}} operatives organizing illegal immigration to Palestine, one of whom, [[Aron Gr\u00fcnhut]], helped 1,365 Slovak, Czech, Hungarian, and Austrian Jews emigrate. By early 1941, further emigration was impossible; even Jews who received valid United States visas were not allowed transit visas through Nazi Germany.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=26}} The total number of Slovak Jewish emigrants has been estimated at 5,000 to 6,000.{{sfn|Ward|2015|pp=94, 96}}{{sfn|Legge|2018|p=227}} \n{{clear}}\n\n=== Aryanization ===\nAryanization in Slovakia, the seizure of Jewish-owned property and exclusion of Jews from the economy,{{sfn|Hallon|2007|p=148}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=25}} was justified by the stereotype (reinforced by HS\u013dS propaganda) of Jews obtaining their wealth by oppressing Slovaks.{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek|2018|p=43}}{{sfn|T\u00f6nsmeyer|2007|p=90}}{{sfn|L\u00f4n\u010d\u00edkov\u00e1|2017|p=85}} Between 1939 and 1942, the HS\u013dS regime received widespread popular support by promising Slovak citizens that they would be enriched by property confiscated from Jews and other minorities.{{sfn|L\u00f4n\u010d\u00edkov\u00e1|2017|p=85}}{{sfn|Cichopek-Gajraj|2018|p=254}}  This was a significant amount of money; in 1940, Jews registered more than 4.322 billion [[Slovak koruna]] (Ks) in property (38 percent of the national wealth).{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=24}}{{efn|Equivalent to [[United States dollar|USD$]]108 million at the time,{{sfn|Foreign Claims Settlement Commission|1968|p=655}} or ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|108,000,000|1942|r=0}}}} today.{{sfn| Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis|2019}} All currency conversions are made from the [[Foreign Claims Settlement Commission]]'s determination of wartime exchange rate.{{sfn|Foreign Claims Settlement Commission|1968|p=655}}}} The process might more aptly be described as \"Slovakization\",{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=28}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=174}}{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|2014|p=510}}  as the Slovak government took steps to ensure that ethnic Slovaks, rather than Germans or other minorities, received the stolen Jewish property. Due to the intervention of the German Party and Nazi Germany, ethnic Germans received 8.3 percent of the stolen property,{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=174}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=28}} but most German applicants were refused, underscoring the freedom of action of the Slovak government.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=28}}\n\nThe first anti-Jewish law, passed on 18 April 1939 and not systematically enforced, was a {{lang|la|[[numerus clausus]]}} four-percent quota of the numbers of Jews allowed to practice law; Jews were also forbidden to write for Christian publications.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}}{{sfn|Rothkirchen|2001|pp=596\u2013597}}{{sfn|Ward|2015|p=97}} The Land Reform Act of February 1940 turned {{convert|101423|ha}} of land owned by 4,943 Jews, about 40 percent of it arable, over to the State Land Office; the land officially passed to the state in May 1942.{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=24}}{{efn|The Land Reform Act did not explicitly target Jews, but it was rarely enforced against non-Jewish landowners.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=25}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=221}}}} The First Aryanization Law was passed in April 1940. {{anchor|Voluntary Aryanization}}Through a process known as \"voluntary Aryanization\", Jewish business owners could suggest a \"qualified Christian candidate\" who would assume at least a 51-percent stake in the company.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}} Under the law, 50 businesses out of more than 12,000 were Aryanized and 179 were liquidated.{{sfn|Hallon|2007|p=151}} HS\u013dS radicals{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}} and the Slovak State's German backers believed that voluntary Aryanization was too soft on the Jews.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=169}}\n\n[[File:Salzburg Conference montage (Tiso and Hitler facing camera).jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|left|alt=Two men standing, facing the camera|[[Jozef Tiso]] and [[Adolf Hitler]] at the [[Salzburg Conference]], 1940]]\nAt the July 1940 [[Salzburg Conference]], German negotiators convinced the Slovaks to replace several members of the cabinet  with  reliably pro-German radicals.{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=177}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|pp=843\u2013844}} [[Ferdinand \u010eur\u010dansk\u00fd]] was replaced as interior minister by Alexander Mach, who aligned the anti-Jewish policy of the Slovak State with that in Germany.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=27}}{{sfn|Legge|2018|p=228}} Another result of the Salzburg talks was the appointment of SS officer [[Dieter Wisliceny]] as a \"[[Judenberater|Jewish adviser]]\" for Slovakia; he arrived in Slovakia in August.{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=65}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=27}} He aimed to impoverish the Jewish community so it became a burden on non-Jewish Slovaks, who would then agree to deport them.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=215}} At Wisliceny's instigation, the Slovak government created the [[Central Economic Office]] (\u00daH\u00da), led by Slovak official {{ill|August\u00edn Mor\u00e1vek|cs||de||sk}} and under Tuka's control, in September 1940.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|pp=169\u2013170}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=27}} The \u00daH\u00da was tasked with assuming ownership of Jewish-owned property.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}} Jews were required to register their property; their bank accounts (valued at 245 million Ks in August 1941){{efn|Equivalent to USD$6.125 million at the time,{{sfn|Foreign Claims Settlement Commission|1968|p=655}} or ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|6,125,000|1942|r=0}}}} today.{{sfn| Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis|2019}}}} were frozen, and Jews were allowed to withdraw only 1,000 Ks (later 150 Ks) per week.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}}{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=24}} The 22,000 Jews who worked in salaried employment were targeted:{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=769}} non-Jews had to obtain \u00daH\u00da permission to employ Jews and pay a fee.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}} By mid-1940, the position of Jews in the Slovak economy had been largely wiped out.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=25}} \n\nA second Aryanization law was passed in November, mandating the expropriation of Jewish property and the Aryanization or liquidation of Jewish businesses.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=170}} In a corrupt process overseen by Mor\u00e1vek's office, 10,000 Jewish businesses (mostly shops) were liquidated and the remainder \u2013 about 2,300 \u2013 were Aryanized.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}}{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=24}}{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|pp=769\u2013770}} Liquidation benefited small Slovak businesses competing with Jewish enterprises, and Aryanization was applied to larger Jewish-owned companies which were acquired by competitors. In many cases, Aryanizers inexpert in business struck deals with former Jewish owners and employees so the Jews would keep working for the company.{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|pp=770\u2013771}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=70}}  The Aryanization of businesses did not bring the anticipated revenue into the Slovak treasury, and only 288 of the liquidated businesses produced income for the state by July 1942.{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|pp=24\u201325}}  The Aryanization and liquidation of businesses was nearly complete by January 1942,{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|pp=770\u2013771}} resulting in 64,000 of 89,000 Jews losing their means of support.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}}{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=26}}  Manufactured Jewish impoverishment was a pressing social problem for the Slovak government, which it \"solved\" in 1942 by deporting the unemployed Jews.{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=25}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=50}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=38}}\n\nAryanization resulted in immense financial loss to Slovakia and great destruction of wealth. The state failed to raise substantial funds from the sale of Jewish property and businesses, and most of its gains came from the confiscation of Jewish-owned bank accounts and financial securities. The main beneficiaries of Aryanization were members of Slovak fascist political parties and paramilitary groups, who were eager to acquire Jewish property but had little  expertise in running Jewish businesses.{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|pp=24\u201325}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|pp=173\u2013174}} During the republic's existence, the government gained 1,100 million Ks from Aryanization and spent 900\u2013950 million Ks on enforcing anti-Jewish measures.{{efn|Gain equivalent to USD$27.5 million at the time,{{sfn|Foreign Claims Settlement Commission|1968|p=655}} or ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|27,500,000|1942|r=0}}}} today.{{sfn| Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis|2019}} Loss equivalent to $22.5 million{{sfn|Foreign Claims Settlement Commission|1968|p=655}} or ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|22,500,000|1942|r=0}}}} today.{{sfn| Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis|2019}}}} In 1942, it paid the German government an additional 300 million Ks for the deportation of 58,000 Jews.{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=25}}\n\n=== Jewish Center ===\n{{Main|\u00dastred\u0148a \u017didov}}\nWhen Wisliceny arrived, all Jewish community organizations were dissolved and the Jews were forced to form the \u00dastred\u0148a \u017didov (Jewish Center, \u00da\u017d, subordinate to the \u00daH\u00da) in September 1940.{{sfn|Fatran|1994|p=165}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=27}} The first {{lang|de|[[Judenrat]]}} outside the Reich and German-occupied Poland, the \u00da\u017d was the only secular Jewish organization allowed to exist in Slovakia; membership was required of all Jews.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}}{{sfn|Bauer|2002|p=176}} Leaders of the Jewish community were divided about how to respond to this development. Although some argued that the \u00da\u017d would be used to implement anti-Jewish measures, more saw participation in the \u00da\u017d as a way to help their fellow Jews by delaying the implementation of such measures and alleviating poverty.{{sfn|Fatran|2002|p=143}}{{sfn|Fatran|1994|p=165}} The first leader of the \u00da\u017d was [[Heinrich Schwartz]], who thwarted anti-Jewish orders to the best of his ability: he sabotaged a census of Jews in eastern Slovakia which was intended to justify their removal to the west of the country; Wisliceny had him arrested in April 1941.{{sfn|Fatran|1994|p=166}}{{sfn|Fatran|2002|pp=144\u2013145}}{{sfn|Rothkirchen|2001|p=597}} The Central Economic Office appointed the more cooperative Arpad Sebestyen as Schwartz' replacement.{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=70}} Wisliceny set up a [[\u00dastred\u0148a \u017didov#Special Affairs|Department for Special Affairs]] in the \u00da\u017d to ensure the prompt implementation of Nazi decrees, appointing the collaborationist [[Karol Hochberg]] (a Viennese Jew) as its director.{{sfn|Fatran|1994|p=166}}{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=70}}\n\n=== Forced labor ===\n{{further|\u00dastred\u0148a \u017didov#Retraining camps}}\n[[File:Sere\u010f m\u00fazeum holokaustu 04.jpg|thumb|alt=Long, low building with a pitched roof|Restored barracks at [[Sere\u010f concentration camp]]]]\nJews serving in the army were segregated in a labor unit in April 1939, and were stripped of their rank at the end of the year. From 1940, male Jews and Romani people were obliged to work for the national defense (generally manual labor on construction projects) for two months every year. All recruits considered Jewish or Romani were allocated to the [[Sixth Labor Battalion]], which worked at military construction sites at [[Sabinov]], [[Liptovsk\u00fd Sv\u00e4t\u00fd Peter]], [[L\u00e1b]], [[Sv\u00e4t\u00fd Jur]], and [[Zohor]] the following year.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}} Although the Ministry of Defense was pressured by the Ministry of the Interior to release the Jews for deportation in 1942, it refused.{{sfn|Bachn\u00e1r|2011}} The battalion was disbanded in 1943, and the Jewish laborers were sent to a number of work camps.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=38}} \n\nThe first labor centers were established in early 1941 by the \u00da\u017d as retraining courses for Jews forced into unemployment; 13,612 Jews had applied for the courses by February, far exceeding the programs' capacity.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007| p= 177}} On 4 July, the Slovak government issued a decree conscripting all Jewish men aged 18 to 60 for labor.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=30}} Although the \u00da\u017d had to supplement the workers' pay to meet the legal minimum, the labor camps greatly increased the living standard of Jews impoverished by Aryanization.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=180}} By September, 5,500 Jews were performing manual labor for private companies at about 80 small labor centers,{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}} most of which were dissolved in the final months of 1941 as part of the preparation for deportation. Construction began on three larger camps \u2013 [[Sere\u010f concentration camp|Sere\u010f]], [[Nov\u00e1ky labor camp|Nov\u00e1ky]], and [[Vyhne labor camp|Vyhne]] \u2013 in September of that year.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=180}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|pp=846\u2013847}}\n\n=== Jewish Code ===\n[[File:\u013dudov\u00e9 noviny 1941.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|left|alt=See caption|Headline of 21 September 1941 propaganda-ministry publication: \"We've dealt with the Jews! The strictest laws against Jews are Slovakia's.\"<!-- translation by User:Buidhe -->]]\nIn accordance with [[Catholic Church and race|Catholic teaching on race]], antisemitic laws initially defined Jews by religion rather than ancestry; Jews who were baptized before 1918 were considered Christian.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=169}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|pp=24, 29}} By September 1940, Jews were banned from secondary and higher education and from all non-Jewish schools, and forbidden from owning motor vehicles, sports equipment, or radios.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=215}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=28}} Local authorities had imposed anti-Jewish measures on their own; the head of the \u0160ari\u0161-Zempl\u00edn region ordered local Jews to wear a yellow band around their left arm from 5 April 1941, leading to attacks.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=29}} As the focus shifted to restricting Jews' civil rights rather than depriving them of their property, [[Department 14]] of the Ministry of the Interior was formed to enforce anti-Jewish measures.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=181}} \n\nThe Slovak parliament passed the Jewish Code on 9 September 1941, which contained 270 anti-Jewish articles.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}} Based on the [[Nuremberg Laws]], the code defined Jews in terms of ancestry, banned intermarriage, and required that all Jews over six years old wear a [[Yellow badge|yellow star]]. The Jewish Code excluded Jews from public life, restricting the hours that they were allowed to travel and shop, and barring them from clubs, organizations, and public events.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|pp=188\u2013189}} In addition, Jews had to pay a 20-percent tax on all property.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=29}} Slovak propaganda boasted that the Jewish Code was the strictest set of anti-Jewish laws in Europe. The president could issue [[presidential exemption (Slovak State)|exemption]]s protecting individual Jews from the law.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}}  Employed Jews were initially exempt from some of the code's requirements, such as wearing the star.{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=774}} \n\nThe racial definition of Jews was criticized by the Catholic Church, and converts were eventually exempted from some of the requirements.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2012|pp=260\u2013262}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=226}} The Hlinka Guard and {{lang|de|Freiwillige Schutzstaffel}} increased assaults on Jews, engaged in antisemitic demonstrations on a daily basis, and harassed non-Jews judged insufficiently antisemitic.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|pp=186\u2013187}} The law enabled the Central Economic Office to force Jews to change their residence.{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=775}} This provision was put into effect on 4 October 1941, when 10,000 of 15,000 Jews in Bratislava (who were not employed or intermarried) were ordered to move to fourteen towns.{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=775}}{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|2016|pp=315, 321}} The relocation was paid for and carried out by the \u00da\u017d's Department of Special Tasks.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|pp=191\u2013192}} Although the Jews were ordered to leave by 31 December 1941, fewer than 7,000 people had moved by March 1942.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=192}}{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|2016|p=321}}\n\n== {{anchor|Deportations}}Deportations (1942) ==\n===Planning===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-A0706-0018-029, Sowjetunion, Storow, Juden vor Exekution.jpg|alt=crowd of people with some digging|thumb|Jews forced to dig their own graves in [[Zboriv]], Ukraine, 4 July 1941]]\nThe highest levels of the Slovak government were aware by late 1941 of mass murders of Jews in German-occupied territories.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=31}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=175}} In July 1941, Wisliceny organized a visit by Slovak government officials to several forced-labor camps run by [[Organization Schmelt]] for the [[Reichsautobahn]] that imprisoned Jews in [[East Upper Silesia]]. The visitors understood that Jews in the camps lived under conditions which would eventually cause their deaths.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|pp=30\u201331}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=170}} Slovak soldiers [[Slovak Expeditionary Army Group|participated]] in the German invasions of Poland and the Soviet Union;{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=23}} they brought word of the mass shootings of Jews, and participated in at least one of the massacres.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=176}} Some Slovaks were aware of the 1941 [[Kamianets-Podilskyi massacre]], in which 23,600 Jews, many of them deported from Hungary, were shot in western Ukraine.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=39}}{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=224}} Defense minister [[Ferdinand \u010catlo\u0161]] and general [[Jozef Turanec]] reported massacres in [[Zhytomyr]] to Tiso by February 1942.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=31}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}} Both bishop [[Karol Kme\u0165ko]] and papal {{lang|fr|[[charg\u00e9 d'affaires]]}} [[Giuseppe Burzio]] confronted the president with reliable reports of the mass murder of Jewish civilians in the Ukraine.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=232}} However, the Slovak government was not aware of the [[Final Solution|Nazi plan to murder all Jews]].{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=71}}\n\nIn mid-1941, the Germans demanded (per previous agreements) another 20,000 Slovak laborers to work in Germany. Slovakia refused to send gentile Slovaks and instead offered an equal number of Jewish workers, although it did not want to be burdened with their families.{{sfn|Bauer|2002|pp=176\u2013177}}{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=65}} A letter sent 15 October 1941 indicates that plans were being made for the mass murder of Jews in the [[Lublin Reservation]] of the [[General Government]] to make room for deported Jews from Slovakia and Germany.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=295, 428}}  In late October, Tiso, Tuka, Mach, and \u010catlo\u0161 visited the [[Wolf's Lair]] (near [[Rastenburg]], [[East Prussia]]) and met with [[Adolf Hitler]]. No record survives of this meeting, at which the deportation of Jews from Slovakia was probably first discussed, leading to historiographical debate over who proposed the idea.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2013|pp=570, 572}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}} Even if the Germans made the offer, the Slovak decision was not motivated by German pressure.{{sfn|L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek|2013|p=110}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2018|p=10}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}} In November 1941, the Slovak government permitted the German government to deport the 659 Slovak Jews living in the Reich and the [[Protectorate of Bohemia and Moravia]],{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}}{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=463}} with the proviso that their confiscated property be passed to Slovakia.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=285}} This was the first step towards deporting Jews from Slovakia,{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=114}} which Tuka discussed with Wisliceny in early 1942.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=229}} As indicated by a cable from the German ambassador to Slovakia, [[Hanns Ludin]], the Slovaks responded \"with enthusiasm\" to the idea.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=116}}\n\nTuka presented the deportation proposals to the government on 3 March, and they were debated in parliament three days later.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}} On 15 May, parliament approved [[Decree 68/1942]], which retroactively legalized the deportation of Jews, authorized the removal of their citizenship, and regulated exemptions.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=233}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=34}} Opposition centered on economic, moral, and legal obstacles, but, as Mach later stated, \"every [legislator] who has spoken on this issue has said that we should get rid of Jews\".{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=230}} The official Catholic representative, Bishop of [[Spi\u0161]] [[J\u00e1n Vojta\u0161\u0161\u00e1k]], only requested separate settlements in Poland for Jews who had converted to Christianity.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=32}} The Slovaks agreed to pay 500 [[Reichsmark]]s per Jew deported (ostensibly to cover shelter, food, retraining and housing){{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=32}}{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|pp=776\u2013777}} and an additional fee to the {{lang|de|[[Deutsche Reichsbahn]]}} for transport.{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=778}} (The 500 Reichsmark fee was equivalent to about [[United States dollar|USD$]]125 at the time,{{sfn|Foreign Claims Settlement Commission|1968|p=655}} or  ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|125|1942|r=0}}}} today).{{sfn| Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis|2019}} The Germans promised in exchange that the Jews would never return, and Slovakia could keep all confiscated property.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=34}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=176}}  Except for Croatia (which paid 30 Reichsmarks per person), Slovakia was the only country which paid to deport its Jewish population.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=121}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2013|p=555}}\n\n==={{anchor|Enaction|First phase|Implementation}}First phase===\n{{further |List of Holocaust transports from Slovakia#Initial phase}}\n[[File:Sere\u010f m\u00fazeum holokaustu 08.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.1 |alt=Photograph of a restored train car, with its sliding door open, used to transport Slovak Jews | Restored train car used to transport Slovak Jews. S\u017d stands for [[Slovensk\u00e9 \u017deleznice]] (Slovak Railways).]]\nThe original deportation plan, approved in February 1942, entailed the deportation of 7,000 women to [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] and 13,000 men to [[Majdanek concentration camp|Majdanek]] as forced laborers.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=324\u2013325}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=301}} Department 14 organized the deportations,{{sfn|Ward|2002|p=576}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}  while the Slovak Transport Ministry provided the [[Holocaust trains|cattle cars]].{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=777}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|pp=216, 230}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=34}}  Lists of those to be deported were drawn up by Department 14 based on statistical data provided by the Jewish Center's Department for Special Tasks.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=301}} At the border station in [[Zwardon]], the Hlinka Guard handed the transports off to the German {{lang|de|[[Schutzpolizei (Nazi Germany)|Schutzpolizei]]}}.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=32}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=153}} Slovak officials promised that deportees would be allowed to return home after a fixed period,{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=302}} and many Jews initially believed that it was better to report for deportation rather than risk reprisals against their families.{{sfn|Bauer|2002|pp=177\u2013178}} On 25 March 1942, the [[First mass transport of Jews to Auschwitz concentration camp|first transport]] departed from [[Poprad transit camp]] for Auschwitz with 1,000 unmarried Jewish women between the ages of 16 and 45.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}  During the first wave of deportations (which ended on 2 April), 6,000 young, single Jews were deported to Auschwitz and Majdanek.{{sfn|Ward|2002|p=579}}\n\nMembers of the Hlinka Guard, the {{lang|de|Freiwillige Schutzstaffel}}, and the [[gendarmerie]] were in charge of rounding up the Jews, guarding the transit centers, and eventually forcing them into train cars for deportation.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}{{sfn|Cichopek|2014|pp=15\u201316}} However, there was a German captain stationed at each of the concentration centers.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=66}} Official exemptions were supposed to keep Jews from being deported, but local authorities sometimes deported exemption-holders.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2012|p=264}} The victims were given only four hours' warning, to prevent them from escaping. Beatings and forcible shaving were commonplace, as was subjecting Jews to invasive searches to uncover hidden valuables.{{sfn|Sokolovi\u010d|2009|pp=346\u2013347}} Although some guards and local officials accepted bribes to keep Jews off the transports, the victim would typically be deported on the next train.{{sfn|Kamenec|2011b|p=107}} Others took advantage of their power to rape Jewish women.{{sfn|Sokolovi\u010d|2009|p=347}} Jews were only allowed to bring {{convert|50|kg}} of personal items with them, but even this was frequently stolen.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=66}}\n\n===Family transports===\n{{further |List of Holocaust transports from Slovakia#Transports to Lublin|List of Holocaust transports from Slovakia#Transports to Auschwitz}}\nSS leader [[Reinhard Heydrich]] visited Bratislava on 10 April, and he and Tuka agreed that further deportations would target whole families and eventually remove all Jews from Slovakia.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=325}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|pp=222\u2013223}} The family transports began on 11 April, and took their victims to the Lublin district.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=325\u2013326}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|pp=313, 320}}  During the first half of June 1942 ten transports stopped briefly at Majdanek, where able-bodied men were [[selection (Holocaust)|selected]] for labor; the trains continued to Sobib\u00f3r, where the remaining victims were murdered.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=325\u2013326}} Most of the trains brought their victims (30,000 in total){{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=785}} to ghettos whose inhabitants had been recently deported to the [[Be\u0142\u017cec extermination camp|Be\u0142\u017cec]] or Sobib\u00f3r [[death camps]]. Some groups stayed only briefly before they were deported again to the death camps, while other groups remained in the ghettos for months or years.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=325\u2013326}}  Some of the deportees ended up in the forced-labor camps in the Lublin area (such as [[Poniatowa concentration camp|Poniatowa]], [[D\u0119blin\u2013Irena Ghetto#Luftwaffe camp|D\u0119blin\u2013Irena]], and [[Krych\u00f3w forced-labor camp|Krych\u00f3w]]).{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|pp=159, 161}} Unusually, the deportees in the Lublin area were quickly able to establish contact with the Jews remaining in Slovakia, which led to [[Working Group (resistance organization)#Aid to deportees|extensive aid efforts]].{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=160}} However, the fate of the Jews deported from Slovakia was ultimately \"sealed within the framework of [[Operation Reinhard]]\" along with that of the Polish Jews, in the words of [[Yehoshua B\u00fcchler]].{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=153}}\n\n[[File:Alinas PL Maceba miejsce zamordowania 18400 zydow na MajdankuP5130085.jpg  |thumb|upright=|alt=Memorial plaque and trenches covered by grass|Trenches at [[Majdanek concentration camp|Majdanek]] where Jews were shot during [[Operation Harvest Festival]] on 3 November 1943.]]\nTransports went to Auschwitz after mid-June, where a minority of the victims were selected for labor and the remainder were killed in the [[gas chambers]].{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=326}}{{sfn| B\u00fcchler |1996|p=320}} This occurred for nine transports, the last of which arrived on 21 October 1942.{{sfn| B\u00fcchler |1996|p=320}}{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=181}} From 1 August to 18 September, no transports departed;{{sfn|Bauer |1994|p=96}}{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=181}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=320}} most of the Jews not exempt from deportation had already been deported or had fled to Hungary.{{sfn|Bauer |1994|pp=75, 97}} In mid-August, Tiso gave a [[Slovak, cast off your parasite|speech in Holi\u010d]] in which he described Jews as the \"eternal enemy\" and justified the deportations according to [[Christian ethics]].{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|pp=8, 234}} Three more transports occurred in September and October 1942 before ceasing until 1944.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=8}}{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=181}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=320}} By the end of 1942, only 500 or 600 Slovak Jews were still alive at Auschwitz.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=34}} Thousands of surviving Slovak Jews in the Lublin District were shot on 3\u20134 November 1943 during [[Operation Harvest Festival]].{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=34}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=160}} \n\nBetween 25 March and 20 October 1942, almost 58,000 Jews (two-thirds of the population) were deported.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=326}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=189}}{{sfn|Fatran|2007|pp=180\u2013181}} The exact number is unknown due to discrepancies in the sources.{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|pp=296\u2013297}} The deportations disproportionately affected poorer Jews from eastern Slovakia. Although the \u0160ari\u0161-Zempl\u00edn region in eastern Slovakia lost 85 to 90 percent of its Jewish population, \u017dilina reported that almost half of its Jews remained after the deportation.{{sfn|Ward|2002|p=584}}{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=187}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=233}} The deportees were held briefly in five camps in Slovakia before deportation;{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=66}} 26,384 from \u017dilina,{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=889}} 7,500 from Patr\u00f3nka,{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=855}} 7,000 from Poprad,{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=879}} 4,463 from Sere\u010f,{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=881}} and 4,000 to 5,000 from Nov\u00e1ky.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=874}} Nineteen trains went to Auschwitz, and another thirty-eight went to ghettos and concentration and extermination camps in the Lublin district.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=151}} Only a few hundred survived the war,{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}} most at Auschwitz; almost no one survived in Lublin.{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=47}}\n\n=== Opposition, exemption, and evasion ===\n{{quotebox|align=right|width=18em|Everyone understands that the Holy See cannot stop Hitler. But who can understand that it does not know how to rein in a priest?|author=[[Domenico Tardini]], Vatican Undersecretary of State{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=232}}{{sfn|Kornberg|2015|pp=83\u201384}}}}\nThe Catholic Church opposed deportation, fearing that such actions from a Catholic government would discredit the church.{{sfn|Kornberg|2015|p=83}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=232}}  According to a SD ({{lang|de|[[Sicherheitsdienst]]}}) report, Giuseppe Burzio threatened Tiso with an [[interdict]].{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=232}} However, Slovak bishops were equivocal in their statement, endorsing [[Jewish deicide]] and other antisemitic myths while urging Catholics to treat Jews humanely.{{sfn|Kornberg|2015|p=82}} The Catholic Church ultimately chose not to discipline any of the Slovak Catholics who were complicit in the regime's actions.{{sfn|Kornberg|2015|p=84}} Officials from the \u00da\u017d{{sfn|Fatran|1994|p=167}} and several of the most influential Slovak rabbis sent petitions to Tiso, but he did not reply.{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|2014|pp=514\u2013515}}  Many Slovaks opposed the deportations,{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=38}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=69}}{{sfn|Kornberg|2015|p=83}} but this did not translate into action against them.{{sfn|Kornberg|2015|p=83}}{{sfn|L\u00f4n\u010d\u00edkov\u00e1|2017|p=91}} By March 1942, the [[Working Group (resistance organization)|Working Group]] (an underground organization which operated under the auspices of the \u00da\u017d) had formed to oppose the deportations. Its leaders, [[Zionism|Zionist]] organizer [[Gisi Fleischmann]] and Orthodox rabbi [[Michael Dov Weissmandl]], bribed [[Anton Va\u0161ek]], head of Department 14, and Wisliceny. It is unknown if the group's efforts had any connection with the halting of deportations.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=848}}{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=326}}{{sfn|Fatran|1994|loc=abstract}}\n\nMany Jews learned about the fate awaiting them during the first half of 1942, from various sources such as letters from deported Jews or escapees.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2012|pp=77\u201378}}{{sfn|Bauer|1994|pp=71\u201372}} Around 5,000 to 6,000 Jews fled to Hungary to avoid the deportations,{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2011b|p=110}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=70}} many by paying bribes{{sfn|Kamenec|2011b|p=110}} or with help from paid smugglers{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2012|p=62, Chapter IV ''passim''}} and [[Hashomer Hatzair]];{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=38}} about one third survived the war.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2012|p=187}}  Many owners of Aryanized businesses applied for work exemptions for the Jewish former owners. In some cases this was a fictitious Aryanization; other Aryanizers, motivated by profit, kept the Jewish former owners around for their skills.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|pp=62, 70}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|pp=176, 178}} About 2,000 Jews had false papers identifying themselves as Aryans.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=70}} Some Christian clergy baptized Jews, even those who were not sincere converts. Although conversion after 1939 did not exempt Jews from deportation,  being baptized made it easier to obtain other exemptions and some clergy edited records to predate baptisms.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2012|pp=279, 297}}{{sfn|Kornberg|2015|p=84}}\n\nAfter the deportations, between 22,000 and 25,000 Jews were still in Slovakia.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=40}}{{sfn|Ward|2002|p=589}} Some 16,000 Jews had exemptions; there were 4,217 converts to Christianity before 1939, at least 985 Jews in mixed marriages,{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=97}}{{sfn|Ward|2002|pp=587\u2013588}} and 9,687 holders of economic exemptions{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=97}} (particularly doctors, pharmacists, engineers, and agricultural experts, whose professions had shortages).{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=190}} One thousand Jews were protected by presidential exemptions, mostly in addition to other exemptions.{{sfn|Ward|2013|pp=232\u2013233}}{{sfn|Ward|2002|pp=583, 587}} In addition to the exempted Jews, around 2,500 were interned in labor camps,{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=40}} and a thousand were serving in the Sixth Labor Battalion.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=38}}  When the deportations were halted, the government knew the whereabouts of only 2,500 Jews without exemptions.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=235}}\n\n==Hiatus (1943)==\nEnforcement of anti-Jewish laws lessened, and many Jews stopped wearing the yellow star.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=303}} Nevertheless, the remaining Jews \u2013 even those with exemptions \u2013 lived in constant fear of deportation.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=848}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|pp=283, 303}} The \u00da\u017d worked to improve conditions for laborers in the Slovak camps{{sfn|Rothkirchen|2001|p=599}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=848}} and to increase productivity, to strengthen the incentive to keep their workers in Slovakia.{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=190}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|pp=315\u2013316, 319}} In 1943, the labor camps earned 39 million Ks for the Slovak State.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=171}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=40}}{{efn|Equivalent to USD$975,000 at the time,{{sfn|Foreign Claims Settlement Commission|1968|p=655}} or ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|975,000 |1942|r=0}}}} today.{{sfn| Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis|2019}}}} The halt in deportations from Slovakia enabled the Working Group to launch the [[Europa Plan]], an unsuccessful effort to bribe SS chief [[Heinrich Himmler]] to spare the surviving Jews under German occupation.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=848}}{{sfn|Bauer|1994|pp=88\u201389, 99, Chapter 5\u20137 ''passim''}} It also smuggled aid to Jews in Poland,{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=162}}{{sfn|Fatran|1994|p=178}}  and helped Polish Jews escape to Hungary via Slovakia.{{sfn|Fatran|1994|p=181}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2012|p=229}} In late April 1944 two Auschwitz escapees, [[Rudolf Vrba]] and [[Alfred Wetzler]], reached Slovakia.{{sfn|Bauer|2002|p=229}} The Working Group sent [[Vrba-Wetzler report|their report]] to Hungary and Switzerland; it reached the Western Allies in July.{{sfn|Bauer|2002|p=237}} \n\nAfter the [[Battle of Stalingrad]] and other reversals in the increasingly unpopular [[Eastern Front (World War II)|war in the east]], Slovak politicians realized that a German defeat was likely.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=405}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=39}} Some HS\u013dS politicians (especially those in the radical faction) blamed economic setbacks on the Jews and agitated for the deportation of the remaining population.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|pp=280\u2013281}} On 7 February 1943, HS\u013dS radical Alexander Mach announced at a rally in [[Ru\u017eomberok]] that the transports would soon resume.{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=86}} In early 1943, the Hlinka Guard and Department 14 prepared for the resumption of deportations: registering Jews, canceling economic exemptions, and hunting down Jews in hiding.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|pp=284\u2013285}} A plan to dispatch four trains between 18 and 22 April was not implemented.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=286}} In response to the threatened resumption, Slovak bishops issued a [[pastoral letter]] in Latin on 8 March condemning antisemitism and totalitarianism and defending the rights of all Jews.{{sfn|Kornberg|2015|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=Qo26CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA85 85]}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|pp=236, 238}} Germany put increasing pressure on the Slovak State to hand over its remaining Jews in 1943 and 1944, but Slovak politicians did not agree to resume the deportations.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=203}}\n\n[[File:May 1944 - Jews from Carpathian Ruthenia arrive at Auschwitz-Birkenau.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A large number of people, with their belongings, getting off a train|Jews from [[Carpathian Ruthenia]] arrive at Auschwitz, May 1944]]\nIn late 1943, leading army officers and [[intelligentsia]] formed the [[Slovak National Council]] to plan an insurrection against the regime;{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=192}} other anti-fascists retreated to the [[Western Carpathians|Carpathian]] mountains and formed [[Slovak partisan|partisan]] groups.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=42}}{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=99}} Preparations for the uprising evoked mixed feelings in the remaining Slovak Jews, who feared that an uprising would bring about a crackdown on their community.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=99}} Underground groups organized at Sere\u010f{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=882}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=41}} and Nov\u00e1ky.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=876}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=41}} Slovak authorities began to re-register Jews in January 1944, prompting some to flee to Hungary.{{sfn|Fatran|1994|p=188}} On 19 March 1944 [[Operation Margarethe|Germany invaded Hungary]], including Carpathian Ruthenia and the areas ceded by Czechoslovakia in 1938.{{sfn|Bauer|2002|p=226}}{{sfn|United States Holocaust Memorial Museum}} The Slovak Jews who had fled to Hungary tried to return, but many were arrested at the border and deported.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=99}} The Slovak ambassador in Budapest, [[J\u00e1n Spi\u0161iak]], issued documents to 3,000 Jews allowing them to legally cross the border,{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=42}} bringing the total Jewish population to 25,000.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=99}} Between 14 May and 7 July 437,000 Jews were deported from Hungary, most to Auschwitz;{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=408}} including many Slovak Jews in the country.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=42}}  To counter the perceived security threat of Jews in the \u0160ari\u0161-Zempl\u00edn region with the front line moving westward, on 15 May 1944 the Slovak government ordered Jews to move to the western part of the country.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=113}}\n{{clear}}\n\n== {{anchor|Resumption of deportations}}Resumption of deportations (1944\u20131945) ==\n=== German invasion ===\n[[File:Karte Slowakischer Nationalaufstand 1944 - Aufstandsbeginn.png|thumb|upright=1.5|alt= Map showing the situation in the first days of the Slovak National Uprising.| Situation during the first days of the [[Slovak National Uprising]]]]\nConcerned about the increase in resistance, Germany invaded Slovakia; this precipitated the [[Slovak National Uprising]], which broke out on 29 August 1944.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=849}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013b|p=585}}{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|2014|p=515}} The insurgent forces seized central Slovakia but were defeated on 27 October at [[Bansk\u00e1 Bystrica]]. Partisans withdrew to the mountains and continued their [[guerrilla warfare|guerrilla campaign]] into 1945.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=849}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|pp=249\u2013250, 252}} A new government was sworn in, with Jozef Tiso's cousin [[\u0160tefan Tiso|\u0160tefan]] as prime minister; Jozef remained president.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=43}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=249}} Burzio met with Tiso on 22 and 29 September, reportedly calling Tiso a liar when the president denied knowledge of deportations.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=251}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|pp=85\u201386}} Pius XII instructed Burzio to tell Tiso that the Vatican condemned the persecution of individuals for their race or nationality.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=86}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=45}} The United States and Switzerland issued formal protests against the deportation of Jews.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|pp=85\u201386}} Slovak propaganda blamed the Jews and [[Persecution of Czechs in the Slovak State|Czechs]] for the uprising.{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|2014|pp=517}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=84}} Nevertheless, the Slovak government preferred the concentration of Jews in concentration camps in Slovakia to their deportation.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=84}} Tiso asked for the Germans to spare at least baptized Jews and those in mixed marriages, but the Slovak exceptions were not honored by the Germans.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=251}}\n\nThe uprising provided the Germans with an opportunity to implement the Final Solution in Slovakia.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=82}} Anti-Jewish actions were nominally controlled by the Slovak State Ministry of Defense, but in practice the Germans dictated policy.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=43}}{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=101}}  Unlike the deportations of 1942, the roundups of Jews were organized and carried out by German forces.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=82}} [[Einsatzgruppe H]], commanded by SS officer {{ill|Josef Witiska|de||fr||sv}}, was formed to suppress the uprising immediately after it began and round up Jews and Romani people.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=101}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013b|p=587}} Local collaborators, including {{lang|de|[[SS-Heimatschutz Slowakei|SS-Heimatschutz]]}} (HS), {{lang|de|Freiwillige Schutzstaffel}} and the [[Hlinka Guard Emergency Divisions]] (POHG),{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=101}}{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=42}} were essential to Einsatzgruppe H's work.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=101}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013b|p=592}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=73}} Collaborators denounced those in hiding, impersonated partisans, and aided with interrogations.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013b|p=592}}\n\n[[File:Stanislav Rejthar 06.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|left|alt=Group of soldiers in a hilly forest|[[Slovak partisans]] during the uprising]]\nAfter the uprising began, thousands of Jews fled to the mountainous interior and partisan-controlled areas around Bansk\u00e1 Bystrica,{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=99}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=42}} including many who left the labor camps after the guards fled.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|pp=100\u2013101}}  Around 1,600 to  2,000 Jews fought as partisans, ten percent of the total insurgent force,{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|2014|p=516}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=42}} although many hid their identity due to antisemitism in the partisan movement.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=119}}  Anti-Jewish legislation in the liberated areas was canceled by the Slovak National Council,{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=42}} but the attitude of the local population varied: some risked their lives to hide Jews, and others turned them in to the police.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013b|p=590}} Unlike in 1942, the death penalty was in effect for rescuers;{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=44}}   the majority provided help for a fee, although there were also cases of selfless rescues.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=45}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|pp=76\u201377}} Many Jews spent six to eight months in makeshift shelters or bunkers in the mountains,{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013b|p=590}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=44}} while others hid in the houses of non-Jews. Regardless, Jews required money for six to eight months of living expenses and the help of non-Jews willing to provide assistance.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|pp=104\u2013105}} Some of the Jews in shelters had to return home later in the winter, risking capture, because of the hunger and cold.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=105}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=44}} Living openly and continuing to work under false papers was typically only possible in Bratislava.{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=52}}\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Roundups ===\nJews who were captured were briefly imprisoned at local prisons or the Einsatzgruppe H office in Bratislava, from which they were sent to Sere\u010f for deportation. Local authorities provided lists of Jews, and many local residents also denounced Jews.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013b|p=590}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=93}}{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=52}}  In the first half of September there were large-scale raids in [[Topo\u013e\u010dany]] (3 September), [[Tren\u010d\u00edn]], and [[Nitra]] (7 September), during which 616 Jews were arrested and imprisoned in Ilava and Sere\u010f.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=43}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=88}} In \u017dilina, Einsatzgruppe 13 and collaborators arrested hundreds of Jews over the night of 13/14 September. The victims were deported to Sere\u010f or Ilava and thence to Auschwitz, where most were murdered.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=43}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|pp=88\u201389}} Einsatzgruppe H reported that some Jews were able to escape because of insufficient personnel, but that both Germans and Slovaks generally supported the roundups and helped track down evaders.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=90}} After the defeat of the uprising, the German forces also hunted the Jews hiding in the mountains.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|pp=92\u201393}}{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=52}} Although the bulk of arrests occurred during the first two months of occupation, the hunt for the Jews continued until 30 March 1945, when a Jewish prisoner was taken to Sere\u010f just three days before the camp was liberated.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013b|p=590}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|pp=99\u2013100}}\n\n{{quotebox|quote=Half of Bratislava was on its feet this morning to watch the show of the {{lang|de|Judenevakuierung}} ... so was the kick, administered by an S.S.-man to a tardy Jew received by the large crowd ... with hand claps and cries of support and encouragement.|source=29 September [[Sicherheitsdienst|SD]] report{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=90}}{{sfn|Aronson|2004|p=177}}|width=22em }}\nIn Bratislava, some Jews were arrested by 20 September. However, the largest roundup was carried out in Bratislava during the night of 28/29 September by [[Einsatzkommando 29]], aided by 600 HS and POHG collaborators and a Luftwaffe unit that guarded the streets: around 1,600 Jews were arrested and taken to Sere\u010f.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=89}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=73}}{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=53}}\nThe United States embassy organized protection for some 300 Jews with foreign citizenship, housing them in a castle in [[Marianka]]. Brunner raided the castle on 11&nbsp;October; all but three of the prisoners were taken to Sere\u010f and deported to Auschwitz on 17 October.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=112}}{{sfn|Hlavinka|2018|p=871}} In mid-October, an office was established at the former Jewish Center to hunt down Jews in hiding, which tortured captured Jews into revealing the names and addresses of other Jews.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=93}} The one to two thousand Jews left in Bratislava were ordered to turn themselves in on 20 November or face imprisonment, but few did so.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|pp=91\u201392}} Half of the Jews arrested after 19 November were in Bratislava, most in hiding with false papers.{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|pp=52, 211}} Henri Dunand of the [[International Committee of the Red Cross|Red Cross]] provided funding for a clandestine group led by Arnold Lazar, which provided money, food, and clothing to Jews in hiding in Bratislava.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=45}}\n\n===Deportation===\n{{further |List of Holocaust transports from Slovakia#1944}} \n[[File:Birkenau Jewish mothers and their children walking to the gas chambers.jpg|thumb|alt=see caption|Jewish women and children from [[Carpathian Ruthenia]] walking towards the gas chambers]]\nSere\u010f concentration camp was the primary facility for interning Jews prior to their deportation. Although there were no transports until the end of September, the Jews experienced harsh treatment (including rape and murder) and severe overcrowding as the population swelled to 3,000 \u2013 more than twice the intended capacity.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=882}}{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=102}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|pp=96\u201397, 99}} SS officer [[Alois Brunner]], who had participated in the organization of transports of Jews from France and Greece,{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=391, 395, 403}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=74}} took over the camp's administration at the end of September.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=74}} About 11,700 people were deported on eleven transports;{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=882}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=74}} the first five (from 30 September to 17 October) went to Auschwitz, where most of the victims were gassed. The final transport to Auschwitz, on 2 November, arrived after the gas chambers were shut down. Later transports left for [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]], [[Bergen-Belsen]], [[Ravensbr\u00fcck]], and [[Theresienstadt Ghetto|Theresienstadt]].{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=44}}{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|pp=54, 68\u201369}} \n\nTwo small transports left [[\u010cadca]] for Auschwitz on 1 and 5 September; Fatran estimates that the total number of deportees was about 400. In September and October, at least 131 people were deported from Slovakia via [[Zakopane]]; two of the transports ended at [[Krak\u00f3w-P\u0142asz\u00f3w concentration camp|Krak\u00f3w-P\u0142asz\u00f3w]] and the third at Auschwitz. A transport from [[Pre\u0161ov]], departing 26 November, ended up at Ravensbr\u00fcck. According to a Czechoslovak criminal investigation, another 800 Jews were deported in two transports from eastern Slovakia on 16 October and 16 December. Details on the transports leaving from locations other than Sere\u010f is fragmentary,{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=104}} and the total number of deportees is not known.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=82}} Slovak historian [[Ivan Kamenec]] estimated that 13,500 Jews were deported in 1944 and 1945, of whom 10,000 died,{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=849}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=337}}{{sfn|Ward|2002|p=589}} but Israeli historian Gila Fatran and Czech historian [[Lenka \u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1]] consider that 14,150 deportees can be verified and the true figure may be higher.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=82}}{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=119}} The Slovak regime also transferred several hundred political prisoners to German custody. Deported to [[Mauthausen concentration camp]], many died there.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=256}}\n\n=== Massacres ===\n{{further|Kremni\u010dka and Nemeck\u00e1 massacres}}\n[[File:Nemecka10Slovakia3.JPG|thumb|left|alt=spiral shaped memorial|Memorial to the victims of the Slovak National Uprising in [[Nemeck\u00e1]]]]\nAfter the German invasion, about 4,000 people were murdered in Slovakia, mostly by Einsatzgruppe H, but with help from local collaborators.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|pp=105\u2013106}} About half (2,000) of the victims were Jews;{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=44}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=253}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=106}} other victims included partisans, supporters of the uprising, and Romani people.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=105}} One of the first executions occurred in the [[Topo\u013e\u010dany]] district, where Einsatzkommando 14 began its mass roundups of Jews. Many of the arrested Jews were taken to Sere\u010f for deportation, but 53 were shot in [[Nem\u010dice]] on 11 September.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|pp=107\u2013108}} The largest execution was in [[Kremni\u010dka and Nemeck\u00e1 massacres|Kremni\u010dka]], a small village {{convert|6|km}} away from Bansk\u00e1 Bystrica. Upon the capture of the rebel stronghold, Jews, partisans, Romanis, and others arrested in the area were held in the prison in the town. Of these, 743 people were brought to Kremni\u010dka for execution in a series of massacres between November and March, by Einsatzgruppe H and the POHG. Victims included 280 women and 99 children; half were Jewish. Hundreds of people were murdered at the nearby village of [[Kremni\u010dka and Nemeck\u00e1 massacres#Nemeck\u00e1|Nemeck\u00e1]], where the victims' bodies were burned after they were shot.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013b|p=592}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=115}}  [[Zvolen]]'s Jewish cemetery was used as an execution site; 218 bodies were exhumed after the end of the war.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=115}} \n{{clear}}\n\n== Aftermath ==\n{{see also|Postwar anti-Jewish violence in Slovakia}}\n[[File:KZ Sere\u010f - Holocaust-Museum - Namen der Ermordeten 2.jpg|thumb|alt=glass panels with many names listed|Names of murdered Jews at the former [[Sere\u010f concentration camp]]]]\nThe [[Red Army]] captured Slovakia by the end of April 1945.{{sfn|Cichopek|2014|p=31}} Around 69,000 Jews, 77 percent of the prewar population, had been murdered.{{sfn|Cichopek-Gajraj|2014|p=52}}{{sfn|Cichopek|2014|p=19}} In addition to the 10,000{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|2014|p=518}} to 11,000 Jews who survived in Slovakia, 9,000 Jews returned who had been deported to concentration camps or fled abroad, and 10,000 Jews survived in the annexed territories. By the end of 1945, 33,000 Jews were living in Slovakia. Many survivors had lost their entire families, and a third suffered from [[tuberculosis]].{{sfn|Cichopek-Gajraj|2014|p=52}} Although a postwar Czechoslovak law negated property transactions arising from Nazi persecution, the autonomous Slovak government refused to apply it.{{sfn|Bazyler et al.|2019|p=402}}{{sfn|Cichopek|2014|p=94}} Heirless property was nationalized in 1947 into the Currency Liquidation Fund.{{sfn|Bazyler et al.|2019|p=402}} Those who had stolen Jewish property were reluctant to return it; former resistance members had also appropriated some stolen property. Conflict over restitution led to [[Postwar anti-Jewish violence in Slovakia| intimidation and violent attacks]], including the September 1945 [[Topo\u013e\u010dany pogrom]] and the [[Partisan Congress riots]] in August 1946.{{sfn|Cichopek|2014|pp=104\u2013105, 111\u2013112, 118\u2013119, 127\u2013129}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1 |2013|pp=556\u2013557}}  Polish historian [[Anna Cichopek]] estimates that at least 36 Jews were murdered and more than 100 injured in postwar violence.{{sfn|Cichopek|2014|p=117}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1 |2018|p=15}}\n\nTiso (who had fled to Austria) was extradited to Czechoslovakia, convicted of treason and collaboration, sentenced to death on 15 April 1947, and executed three days later.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=849}} According to the court, his \"most immoral, most unchristian, and most inhuman\" action was ordering the deportation of the Slovak Jews.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=265}} Other perpetrators, including Tuka, were also tried, convicted, and executed.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=262}}{{sfn|Fedor\u010d\u00e1k|2015|p=42}}  Both Tiso and Tuka were tried under [[wikisource:sk:Nariadenie Slovenskej n\u00e1rodnej rady \u010d. 33 zo d\u0148a 15. m\u00e1ja 1945 o potrestan\u00ed fa\u0161istick\u00fdch zlo\u010dincov, okupantov, zradcov a kolaborantov a o zriaden\u00ed \u013eudov\u00e9ho s\u00fadnictva|Decree 33/1945]], an {{lang|la|[[ex post facto]]}} law that mandated the death penalty for the suppression of the Slovak National Uprising;{{sfn|Ward|2013|pp=258, 263}}{{sfn|Fedor\u010d\u00e1k|2015|p=41}} their roles in the Holocaust were a subset of the crimes for which they were convicted.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=265}}{{sfn|Fedor\u010d\u00e1k|2015|p=44}} The authors of some of the more egregious antisemitic articles and caricatures were prosecuted after the war.{{sfn|L\u00f4n\u010d\u00edkov\u00e1|2017|p=86}} The trials painted Slovak State officials as traitors, thereby exonerating Slovak society from [[responsibility for the Holocaust]].{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=262}} \n\nThe Czechoslovak government supported Zionism, insisting that Jews assimilate into Czechoslovak culture or [[aliyah|emigrate to Palestine]].{{sfn|L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek|2013|p=51}} Jews who had declared German or Hungarian nationality on a prewar census were [[Bene\u0161 decrees|stripped of their citizenship]], losing any right to restitution, and were threatened with deportation.{{sfn|Cichopek|2014|pp=165\u2013166, 169}}  Most Jews in Slovakia emigrated to Israel or other countries in the years after the war. Emigration accelerated in 1948 after the [[1948 Czechoslovak coup d'\u00e9tat|Communist coup]] and nationalization of many businesses after the war. The number of Jewish communities decreased from 126 to 25, while the population decreased by 80 percent. Only a few thousand Jews were left by the end of 1949.{{sfn|Cichopek|2014|pp=228\u2013230}} Many of those who chose to stay changed their surnames and abandoned religious practice in order to fit in with the Slovak middle class.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1 |2018|p=15}} As of 2019, the Jewish population is estimated at 2,000{{sfn|Bazyler et al.|2019|p=402}} to 3,000.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1 |2018|p=17}}\n\n=={{anchor|Reception}}Legacy==\n[[File:Bratislava Holocaust Mahnmal 1289 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|alt=black metal memorial in an urban square |Holocaust Memorial at Rybn\u00e9 n\u00e1mestie in Bratislava]]\nThe [[Soviet anti-Zionism|government's attitude to Jews and Zionism]] shifted after 1948, leading to the 1952 [[Sl\u00e1nsk\u00fd trial]] in which the Czechoslovak government accused fourteen Communists (eleven of them Jewish) of belonging to a Zionist conspiracy.{{sfn|Sniegon|2014|p=61}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2018|pp=15\u201316}} Political censorship hampered the study of the Holocaust, and memorials to the victims of fascism did not mention Jews. In the 1960s, which were characterized by a liberalization known as the [[Prague Spring]], discussion of the Holocaust opened up.{{sfn|Sniegon|2014|pp=58, 62}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2013|p=558}} The [[Academy Award]]-winning 1965 film, ''[[The Shop on Main Street]]'', focused on Slovak culpability for the Holocaust.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2013|p=558}}{{sfn|Sniegon|2014|p=67}} Following the 1968 [[Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia]], authorities [[normalization (Czechoslovakia)|cracked down]]  on free expression,{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=269}}{{sfn|Sniegon|2014|pp=69\u201370}} \nwhile  anti-Zionist propaganda, much of it imported from the Soviet Union, intensified and veered into antisemitism after Israeli victory in the 1967 [[Six-Day War]].{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek|2018|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=7HtTDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA222 217\u2013218]}}\n\nA nationalist resurgence followed the [[Velvet Revolution|fall of the Communist regime]] in 1989, leading to the [[dissolution of Czechoslovakia]] in 1993 and the nationalist [[Vladim\u00edr Me\u010diar|Me\u010diar government]]. After Me\u010diar's fall in 1998,  the Slovak government promoted Holocaust remembrance to demonstrate the country's European identity before it [[2004 enlargement of the European Union|joined the European Union]] in 2004.{{sfn|Sniegon|2014|pp=73, 84\u201385, 166}} Memorials were constructed in many Slovak cities during the 1990s to commemorate Holocaust victims,{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2013|p=574}}{{sfn|Sniegon|2014|pp=89\u201390}} and in October 2001 Slovakia designated 9 September (the anniversary of the passage of the Jewish Code) as Holocaust Victims and Racial Hatred Day.{{efn|{{lang-sk|Pam\u00e4tn\u00fd de\u0148 obet\u00ed holokaustu a rasov\u00e9ho n\u00e1silia}}{{sfn|Slovensk\u00e9 n\u00e1rodn\u00e9 m\u00fazeum|2018}}}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2013|p=575}} The [[National Memory Institute (Slovakia)|National Memory Institute]] was established in 2002 to provide access to the records of both the Slovak State and Communist state.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1 |2013|pp=564\u2013565}}  The post-Communist government enacted various laws for the restitution of Jewish property, but residency and citizenship requirements prevented emigrants from filing claims.{{sfn|Bazyler et al.|2019|pp=401\u2013402}} In 2002, ten percent of the value of the nationalized heirless property was released into a fund that paid for Jewish education and Holocaust memorials.{{sfn|Bazyler et al.|2019|p=411}} {{As of|January 2019}}, [[Yad Vashem]] (the official Israeli memorial to the Holocaust) had recognized 602 Slovaks as [[Righteous Among the Nations]] for risking their lives to save Jews.{{sfn|Yad Vashem|2019}} \n\nHolocaust relativism in Slovakia tends to manifest as attempts to deflect the blame for it onto Germans and Jews.{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|2014|p=506}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2018|p=10}} A 1997 textbook by [[Milan Stanislav \u010eurica]] and endorsed by the government sparked international controversy (and was eventually withdrawn from circulation) because it portrayed Jews as living happily in labor camps during the war.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2013|pp=566\u2013467}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=277}}{{sfn|Sniegon|2014|p=209}} Jozef Tiso and the Slovak State have been the focus of Catholic and [[Ultranationalism|ultranationalist]] commemorations.{{sfn|Ward|2013|pp=276, 278}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2018|p=11}} The [[neo-Nazi]]{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek|2017|p=3}} [[Kotleba \u2013 People's Party Our Slovakia|Kotleba]] party, which is represented in the national parliament and the [[European Parliament]] and is especially popular with younger voters,{{sfn|Spectator|2019}} promotes a positive view of the Slovak State. Its leader, [[Marian Kotleba]], once described Jews as \"devils in human skin\".{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2018|pp=17, 20}} Members of the party have been charged with [[Holocaust denial]],{{sfn|Spectator|2016}}{{sfn|Spectator|2017}} which has been a criminal offense since 2001.{{sfn|Spectator|2016}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n==== Books ====\n{{refbegin|35em|indent=yes}}\n:{{cite book |last1=Aronson |first1=Shlomo|authorlink=Shlomo Aronson (historian) |title=Hitler, the Allies, and the Jews |date=2004 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |location=Cambridge |isbn=978-0-511-51183-7 |language=en }}\n: {{cite book |last1=Bauer |first1=Yehuda |authorlink=Yehuda Bauer |title=Jews for Sale?: Nazi-Jewish Negotiations, 1933\u20131945 |date=1994 |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |isbn=978-0-300-05913-7 |language=en |location=New Haven |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/jewsforsalenazij00baue }}\n: {{cite book |last1=Bauer |first1=Yehuda |title=Rethinking the Holocaust |date=2002 |publisher=Yale University Press |isbn=978-0-300-09300-1  |location=New Haven }}\n:{{cite book |last1=Cichopek |first1=Anna |title=Beyond Violence: Jewish Survivors in Poland and Slovakia, 1944\u201348|title-link=Beyond Violence: Jewish Survivors in Poland and Slovakia, 1944\u201348 |date=2014 |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-03666-6}}\n:{{cite book |last1=De\u00e1k |first1=Istv\u00e1n |authorlink1=Istv\u00e1n De\u00e1k |title=Europe on Trial: The Story of Collaboration, Resistance, and Retribution during World War II |date=2015 |orig-year=2013|publisher=[[Westview Press]] ([[Routledge]]) |location=Boulder, Colorado |isbn=978-0-8133-4790-5 }}\n:{{cite book |last1=Fatran |first1=Gila |t