opedia  |last1=Rajcan |first1=Vanda |entry=\u017dilina|editor1-last=Megargee|editor1-first=Geoffrey P. |editor2-last=White|editor2-first=Joseph R.|editor3-last=Hecker|editor3-first=Mel |series=Encyclopedia of Camps and Ghettos |volume=3 |title=Camps and Ghettos under European Regimes Aligned with Nazi Germany |isbn=978-0-253-02373-5|location=Bloomington |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum  |date=2018|pp=889\u2013890}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==== Web ====\n{{refbegin|35em|indent=yes}}\n*{{cite web |last1=Bachn\u00e1r |first1=Alexander |title=Odtabuizovan\u00fd pr\u00e1por |url=https://www.holocaust.cz/zdroje/clanky-z-ros-chodese/ros-chodes-2002/zari-9/odtabuizovany-prapor/ |publisher=Terez\u00edn Initiative |accessdate=23 January 2019 |language=sk |date=7 August 2011|trans-title=Detached Battalion}}\n*{{cite web |title=Consumer Price Index, 1800\u2013 |url=https://www.minneapolisfed.org/about-us/monetary-policy/inflation-calculator/consumer-price-index-1800- |publisher=Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis |accessdate=29 November 2019 |ref={{sfnref|Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis|2019}}}}\n*{{cite news |title=Mazurek not prosecuted for Holocaust denial |url=https://spectator.sme.sk/c/20266405/mazurek-not-prosecuted-for-holocaust-denial.html |accessdate=16 January 2019 |work=The Slovak Spectator |date=7 September 2016 |language=en|ref={{sfnref|Spectator|2016}}}}\n*{{cite news |title=Extremist charged with Holocaust denial |url=https://spectator.sme.sk/c/20617009/extremist-charged-with-holocaust-denial.html |accessdate=16 January 2019 |work=The Slovak Spectator |date=2 August 2017 |language=en|ref={{sfnref|Spectator|2017}}}}\n*{{cite news |title=Under 30s would vote far-right Kotleba the next PM |url=https://spectator.sme.sk/c/22271423/under-30s-would-vote-far-right-kotleba-the-next-pm.html |accessdate=5 January 2020 |work=The Slovak Spectator |date=28 November 2019 |ref={{sfnref|Spectator|2019}} |language=en}}\n*{{cite web |title=Pam\u00e4tn\u00fd de\u0148 obet\u00ed holokaustu a rasov\u00e9ho n\u00e1silia 2018 |url=http://www.snm.sk/?muzeum-holokaustu-podujatia&clanok=pamatny-den-obeti-holokaustu-a-rasoveho-nasilia-2018-1 |publisher=Slovensk\u00e9 n\u00e1rodn\u00e9 m\u00fazeum |accessdate=28 September 2018 |ref={{sfnref|Slovensk\u00e9 n\u00e1rodn\u00e9 m\u00fazeum|2018}} |language=sk |date=7 September 2018|trans-title=Holocaust Victims and Racial Hatred Day 2018}}\n*{{cite web |title=Names of Righteous by Country |url=https://www.yadvashem.org/righteous/statistics.html |publisher=Yad Vashem |accessdate=28 November 2019 |language=en |ref={{sfnref|Yad Vashem|2019}}}}\n*{{cite web |title=The Holocaust in Subcarpathian Rus and Southern Slovakia |url=https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/the-holocaust-in-subcarpathian-rus-and-southern-slovakia |website=Holocaust Encyclopedia |publisher=[[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]] |accessdate=8 February 2020 |ref={{sfnref|United States Holocaust Memorial Museum}} |language=en}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Holocaust}}\n{{Holocaust Slovakia}}\n{{Czechoslovakia in World War II}}\n{{Slovak People's Party}}\n\n[[Category:Jewish Slovak history]]\n[[Category:The Holocaust by country]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Slovakia during World War II]]\n[[Category:Murder in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:1940s murders in Europe]]\n[[Category:1940s in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Germany\u2013Slovakia relations]]\n", "name_user": "Buidhe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBooks:fix isbn", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Holocaust_in_Slovakia"}
{"title_page": "Old Leake railway station", "text_new": "{{short description|Former railway station in Lincolnshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n | name       = Old Leake\n | image_name = Old Leake railway station.jpg\n | caption    = Station in 2007\n | gridref    = \n | coordinates = {{coord|53.0542|0.0519|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n | original   = [[East Lincolnshire Railway]]\n | pregroup   = [[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway]]    \n | postgroup  = [[London and North Eastern Railway]] <br> [[Eastern Region of British Railways]]\n | locale     = [[Old Leake]] \n | borough    = [[Boston (borough)|Boston]]\n | platforms  = 2 \n | years      = 2 October 1848\n | events     = Opened as '''Hob Hole'''\n | years1     = November 1848 \n | events1    = Renamed '''Leake and Wrangle'''\n | years2     = 1 October 1849\n | events2    = Renamed '''Old Leake and Wrangle'''\n | years3     = October 1852 \n | events3    = Renamed '''Old Leake'''\n | years4     = 17 September 1956\n | events4    = Closed to passenger traffic\n | years5     = 15 June 1964\n | events5    = Closed to goods traffic       \n}}\n\n'''Old Leake''' was a [[railway station]] on the [[East Lincolnshire Railway]]{{sfn|Conolly|2004|loc=p. 17, section C3}} which served the village of [[Old Leake]] in [[Lincolnshire]] between 1848 and 1964.<ref>{{cite PastScape |mnumber=507057 |mname=Old Leake station |accessdate=2013-03-30}}</ref> It originally opened as ''Hob Hole'' and was renamed three times within the first five years of opening. Withdrawal of passenger services took place in 1956, followed by goods facilities in 1964. The line through the station remains in use as the [[Poacher Line]].<ref name=PL>{{cite web |url=http://microsites.lincolnshire.gov.uk/poacherline/east-midlands-trains-and-fares/poacher-line-guide-to-travelling-by-train/ |title=Poacher line guide |publisher=Lincolnshire county council |date=24 March 2010 |accessdate=2013-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe station was opened on 2 October 1848 as ''Hob Hole'',{{sfn|Butt|1995|p=121}} but was renamed one month later as ''Leake and Wrangle''.{{sfn|Butt|1995|p=140}} The name changed again less than one year later in October 1849 to ''Old Leake and Wrangle'',{{sfn|Butt|1995|p=177}} before becoming simply ''Old Leake'' in October 1852.{{sfn|Butt|1995|p=177}} The village of [[Old Leake]] lay to the east of the line, whilst [[Wrangle, Lincolnshire|Wrangle]] is 1\u00bd miles to the north-west.{{sfn|Ludlam|1991|p=49}} The station was constructed by [[Samuel Morton Peto|Peto]] and [[Edward Betts|Betts]] [[civil engineer]]ing [[General contractor|contractors]] who, in January 1848, had taken over the contract to construct the section of the [[East Lincolnshire Railway]] between {{rws|Louth}} and {{rws|Boston}} from John Waring and Sons.{{sfn|Ludlam|1991|p=14}} This section was the last to be completed in September 1848 at an agreed cost of  \u00a3123,000 (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|123000|1848|r=-4}}}} in {{Inflation-year|UK}}).{{sfn|Ludlam|1991|p=14}} At the time, Old Leake village consisted of little more than an [[public house|inn]] and the station itself.{{sfn|Ludlam|1991|p=49}} The July 1922 timetable saw five up and four down services, and one Sunday service each way, call at Old Leake.{{sfn|Ludlam|1991|pp=111-112}} The station was closed to passengers on 17 September 1956{{sfn|Butt|1995|p=177}} and to goods traffic on 15 June 1964.{{sfn|Clinker|1978|p=104}}\n\n{{Historical Rail Start}}\n{{Rail line|next={{Stnlnk|Sibsey}}<br><small>Line open, station closed|previous={{Stnlnk|East Ville}}<br><small>Line open, station closed|route=[[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway]]<br><small>[[East Lincolnshire Railway|East Lincolnshire Line]]</small>|col={{GNR colour}}}}\n{{end}}\n\n==Present day==\nThe line through the station continues to be used by services on the [[Poacher Line]] between {{Stnlnk|Grantham}} and {{Stnlnk|Skegness}}.<ref name=PL/>\n{{clear right}}\n[[File:Pill Box - geograph.org.uk - 363453.jpg|thumb|right|The original station name was taken from the ''Hob Hole Drain'', which the line crosses south of the station]]\n[[File:Hobhole Drain - geograph.org.uk - 363448.jpg|thumb|right|''Hobhole drain'' seen from the railwaybridge]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{Butt-Stations}}\n* {{Cite book | last1 = Clinker | first1 = C.R. | title = Clinker's Register of Closed Passenger Stations and Goods Depots in England, Scotland and Wales 1830-1977 |date=October 1978 | publisher = Avon-Anglia Publications & Services | location = Bristol | isbn = 0-905466-19-5 | pages = | ref = harv}}\n*{{Cite book  | last1 = Ludlam | first1 = A.J. | title = The East Lincolnshire Railway (Locomotive Papers No. 82) | year = 1991 | publisher = The Oakwood Press | location = Headington, Oxford | isbn = 0-85361-416-4 | pages =  | ref = harv}}\n* {{Cite book  | last1 = Conolly | first1 = W. Philip  | title = British Railways Pre-Grouping Atlas and Gazetteer | year = 2004 | origyear = 1958 | publisher = Ian Allan Ltd | location = Hersham, Surrey | isbn = 978-0-7110-0320-0 | pages =  | ref = harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.npemap.org.uk/tiles/map.html#537,352,1 Old Leake station on navigable 1947 O. S. map]\n* [http://www.disusedrailways.co.uk/Closed%20Stations21.htm Webpage including a picture of Old Leake station building]\n\n{{Closed stations Lincolnshire}}\n\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1964]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1848]]\n[[Category:Former Great Northern Railway stations]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Former railway station in Lincolnshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n | name       = Old Leake\n | image_name = Old Leake railway station.jpg\n | caption    = Station in 2007\n | gridref    = \n | coordinates = {{coord|53.0542|0.0519|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n | original   = [[East Lincolnshire Railway]]\n | pregroup   = [[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway]]    \n | postgroup  = [[London and North Eastern Railway]] <br> [[Eastern Region of British Railways]]\n | locale     = [[Old Leake]] \n | borough    = [[Boston (borough)|Boston]]\n | platforms  = 2 \n | years      = 2 October 1848\n | events     = Opened as '''Hob Hole'''\n | years1     = November 1848 \n | events1    = Renamed '''Leake and Wrangle'''\n | years2     = 1 October 1849\n | events2    = Renamed '''Old Leake and Wrangle'''\n | years3     = October 1852 \n | events3    = Renamed '''Old Leake'''\n | years4     = 17 September 1956\n | events4    = Closed to passenger traffic\n | years5     = 15 June 1964\n | events5    = Closed to goods traffic       \n}}\n\n'''Old Leake''' was a [[railway station]] on the [[East Lincolnshire Railway]]{{sfn|Conolly|2004|loc=p. 17, section C3}} which served the village of [[Old Leake]] in [[Lincolnshire]] between 1848 and 1964.<ref>{{cite PastScape |mnumber=507057 |mname=Old Leake station |accessdate=2013-03-30}}</ref> It originally opened as ''Hob Hole'' and was renamed three times within the first five years of opening. Withdrawal of passenger services took place in 1956, followed by goods facilities in 1964. The line through the station remains in use as the [[Poacher Line]].<ref name=PL>{{cite web |url=http://microsites.lincolnshire.gov.uk/poacherline/east-midlands-trains-and-fares/poacher-line-guide-to-travelling-by-train/ |title=Poacher line guide |publisher=Lincolnshire county council |date=24 March 2010 |accessdate=2013-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe station was opened on 2 October 1848 as ''Hob Hole'',{{sfn|Butt|1995|p=121}} but was renamed one month later as ''Leake and Wrangle''.{{sfn|Butt|1995|p=140}} The name changed again less than one year later in October 1849 to ''Old Leake and Wrangle'',{{sfn|Butt|1995|p=177}} before becoming simply ''Old Leake'' in October 1852.{{sfn|Butt|1995|p=177}} The village of [[Old Leake]] lay to the east of the line, whilst [[Wrangle, Lincolnshire|Wrangle]] is 1\u00bd miles to the north-west.{{sfn|Ludlam|1991|p=49}} The station was constructed by [[Samuel Morton Peto|Peto]] and [[Edward Betts|Betts]] [[civil engineer]]ing [[General contractor|contractors]] who, in January 1848, had taken over the contract to construct the section of the [[East Lincolnshire Railway]] between {{rws|Louth}} and {{rws|Boston}} from John Waring and Sons.{{sfn|Ludlam|1991|p=14}} This section was the last to be completed in September 1848 at an agreed cost of  \u00a3123,000 (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|123000|1848|r=-4}}}} in {{Inflation-year|UK}}).{{sfn|Ludlam|1991|p=14}} At the time, Old Leake village consisted of little more than an [[public house|inn]] and the station itself.{{sfn|Ludlam|1991|p=49}} The July 1922 timetable saw five up and four down services, and one Sunday service each way, call at Old Leake.{{sfn|Ludlam|1991|pp=111-112}} The station was closed to passengers on 17 September 1956{{sfn|Butt|1995|p=177}} and to goods traffic on 15 June 1964.{{sfn|Clinker|1978|p=104}}\n\n{{Historical Rail Start}}\n{{Rail line|next={{Stnlnk|Sibsey}}<br><small>Line open, station closed|previous={{Stnlnk|East Ville}}<br><small>Line open, station closed|route=[[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway]]<br><small>[[East Lincolnshire Railway|East Lincolnshire Line]]</small>|col={{GNR colour}}}}\n{{end}}\n\n==Present day==\nThe line through the station continues to be used by services on the [[Poacher Line]] between {{Stnlnk|Grantham}} and {{Stnlnk|Skegness}}.<ref name=PL/>\n{{clear right}}\n[[File:Pill Box - geograph.org.uk - 363453.jpg|thumb|right|The original station name was taken from the ''Hob Hole Drain'', which the line crosses south of the station]]\n[[File:Hobhole Drain - geograph.org.uk - 363448.jpg|thumb|right|''Hobhole drain'' seen from the railwaybridge]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{Butt-Stations}}\n* {{Cite book | last1 = Clinker | first1 = C.R. | title = Clinker's Register of Closed Passenger Stations and Goods Depots in England, Scotland and Wales 1830-1977 |date=October 1978 | publisher = Avon-Anglia Publications & Services | location = Bristol | isbn = 0-905466-19-5 | pages = | ref = harv}}\n*{{Cite book  | last1 = Ludlam | first1 = A.J. | title = The East Lincolnshire Railway (Locomotive Papers No. 82) | year = 1991 | publisher = The Oakwood Press | location = Headington, Oxford | isbn = 0-85361-416-4 | pages =  | ref = harv}}\n* {{Cite book  | last1 = Philip Conolly | first1 = W. | title = British Railways Pre-Grouping Atlas and Gazetteer | year = 2004 | origyear = 1958 | publisher = Ian Allan Ltd | location = Hersham, Surrey | isbn = 978-0-7110-0320-0 | pages =  | ref = harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.npemap.org.uk/tiles/map.html#537,352,1 Old Leake station on navigable 1947 O. S. map]\n* [http://www.disusedrailways.co.uk/Closed%20Stations21.htm Webpage including a picture of Old Leake station building]\n\n{{Closed stations Lincolnshire}}\n\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1964]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1848]]\n[[Category:Former Great Northern Railway stations]]\n", "name_user": "Nempnet", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed Conolly citation anchor", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Leake_railway_station"}
